{ Welcome to Grandmaster Gambits: 1.e4: Part Two!   Here we'll present some more of Simon's favourite attacking and sacrificial lines with that first move which was best by test according to the great Bobby. }
1. e4 d6
{ In Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4 we covered Black's four main defences, 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6. Here we look at everything else he can throw at the 1. e4 player, including a number of club player favourites.   As well as 1...d6, which can lead to a number of lines, arguably the most important first move we'll cover, at least from a practical perspective, is the Scandinavian,   1...d5  2.exd5  . Here after both  2...Nf6  and  2...Qxd5  we recommend  3.Nf3  , denying Black his or her favourite lines and a move which both gives White fairly easy play and can lead to some pretty aggressive play, especially in the critical continuation  3...Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  5.O-O  O-O-O  6.h3  .   Chapter Four rounds up Black's fianchetto alternatives to a ...g6-based approach, including  1...a6  ,  1...g5  and especially  1...b6  , Owen's Defence. Here White has an aggressive and simple set-up available:  2.d4  Bb7  3.Nc3  e6  4.Bd3  when we won't be developing the knight to the standard f3 post, but rather going Nge2, remaining flexible, refusing to obstruct the f-pawn and hoping to obtain an early central initiative with a d5 advance.   Against the Alekhine,  1...Nf6  , we have a surprise in store:  2.e5  Nd5  3.Qf3!?  , which is likely to surprise even quite experienced Alekhine practitioners. White enjoys some early pressure against f7, prevents 3...d6 and the queen may slide across to a fine spot on g3.   1...Nc6  , the Nimzowitsch Defence, is most simply met by  2.Nf3  , angling to transpose back to the 1. e4 e5 part of the repertoire from Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Black may, though, prefer something independent, as we'll see in our final section. }
2. d4 Nf6
{ This can be delayed if Black is a Modern player, but after   2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  White can still go  4.Be2  followed by h4, as covered in Chapter Two. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Black doesn't have to head for Pirc waters with Simon's sometime favourite, the Black Lion, a pretty respectable alternative these days,  3...e5  .   Here we'll opt for a route one approach:  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  and now not one of the main lines, but making White's main pawn break without delay in  6.f4  , which has arguably been underestimated by theory and most certainly can early cause trouble for the black king. }
4. Be2 { A modest little move, but with a venomous follow-up in mind. } 4...
Bg7 5. h4
{ Here we go, putting Harry to immediate use. White simply wants to blast ahead with h5, as we'll see at the start of our detailed coverage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Barua, Dibyendu vs. Nikolic, Predrag (Biel Interzonal, 1993)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6
{ In Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4 we covered Black's four main defences, 1...e5, 1...c5, 1...e6 and 1...c6. Here we look at everything else he can throw at the 1. e4 player, including a number of club player favourites.   As well as 1...d6, which can lead to a number of lines, arguably the most important first move we'll cover, at least from a practical perspective, is the Scandinavian,   1...d5  2.exd5  . Here after both  2...Nf6  and  2...Qxd5  we recommend  3.Nf3  , denying Black his or her favourite lines and a move which both gives White fairly easy play and can lead to some pretty aggressive play, especially in the critical continuation  3...Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  5.O-O  O-O-O  6.h3  .   Chapter Four rounds up Black's fianchetto alternatives to a ...g6-based approach, including  1...a6  ,  1...g5  and especially  1...b6  , Owen's Defence. Here White has an aggressive and simple set-up available:  2.d4  Bb7  3.Nc3  e6  4.Bd3  when we won't be developing the knight to the standard f3 post, but rather going Nge2, remaining flexible, refusing to obstruct the f-pawn and hoping to obtain an early central initiative with a d5 advance.   Against the Alekhine,  1...Nf6  , we have a surprise in store:  2.e5  Nd5  3.Qf3!?  , which is likely to surprise even quite experienced Alekhine practitioners. White enjoys some early pressure against f7, prevents 3...d6 and the queen may slide across to a fine spot on g3.   1...Nc6  , the Nimzowitsch Defence, is most simply met by  2.Nf3  , angling to transpose back to the 1. e4 e5 part of the repertoire from Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Black may, though, prefer something independent, as we'll see in our final section. }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2
{ White has a number of aggressive set-ups against the Pirc, but you might not have thought this was one of them. Well, let's hope that the outwardly calm text move also causes Black to relax his guard. We're not after a Classical Pirc with Nf3, but to... }
4... Bg7 5. h4
{ ...advance Harry! Suddenly the bishop's position on e2 makes a lot of sense and h4-h5 is already a threat. }
5... h5
{ Black's most solid and popular move, and we'll frequently see him drifting into early trouble when he delays it in our detailed Pirc coverage. }
6. Nf3
{ Black has kept the kingside closed, but at a cost: he can no longer go ...h6, so the g5-square is a very tempting post for a white knight. }
6... O-O
{ This might seem a little brave, but is theoretically approved and far from bad, but, yes, Black must now take care to keep the kingside closed. }
7. Ng5
{ 7.Bg5  also has its adherents, but we like to press on f7 and thereby reduce Black's central counterplay. }
7... c6
{ As we'll see in much more detail in Line A6,  7...e5?!  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  is not a tedious queen exchange, but rather a very pleasant position for White after  10.Bc4  . Already the knight on g5 is more than making its weight felt and here Black really has to play his rook forwards as  10...Rf8?  11.b3  suddenly forces the positionally most sub-optimal ...c5 to block the a3-f8 diagonal.   As we'll see, the most important line is  7...Nc6  8.Be3  e5  and here too White's simplest and strongest approach is  9.dxe5  - see Line A6. }
8. a4
{ For now we spend a move on non-aggressive measures, as it makes good sense to deny Black any counterplay with ...b5. }
8... Ng4
{ The strong Bosnian Grandmaster believes that anything that White can do, so can Black, but actually he can only make a knight leap under much worse circumstances than White. Why? Well, f2-f3 will immediately eject the knight, whereas the mirror advance, ...f6, is clearly quite risky since it will expose Black on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
9. f3 Nh6
{ The point of Black's play and even after  9...Nf6  White might well just go  10.g4  . }
10. Be3
{ The Indian Grandmaster continues to develop and wants to target that rather strangely-located knight on  h6  . This is a pretty strong path. So too is  10.g4!?  , as we'll analyse in Line A6. }
10... d5
{ Black hopes to take control of some key light squares after 11. e5?!, but unfortunately for Nikolic, Barua proves able to maintain the tension.   Instead,  10...e5  11.Qd2  would have X-rayed the knight on h6 while simply intending to increase the pressure by castling long or with  11...exd4  12.Bxd4  f6  when even  13.Bc4+!?  is possible, and if  13...d5  14.exd5  fxg5  15.Bxg7  Kxg7  16.hxg5  Nf5  17.O-O-O  with a huge initiative for the piece, since g2-g4 is coming and  17...h4?  18.g4!  hxg3  19.Ne4  would already be quite hopeless for Black's beleaguered king. }
11. Qd2 dxe4 12. Ncxe4
{ Far from bad. Black would have been right back in the game after   12.fxe4  Ng4  , and if  13.Bxg4  Bxg4  14.O-O  Na6  ,  but   12.Ngxe4!  Nf5  13.O-O-O !  would have been extremely strong. Yes, the supposedly key dark-squared bishop is going, but Black's king position is quite vulnerable and g2-g4 imminent: for example,  13...Nxe3  14.Qxe3  b5  15.g4  bxa4  16.gxh5  and White is simply far too fast. }
12... Nf5 13. O-O-O Nxe3 14. Qxe3
{ Even here White is clearly for choice: his attack should outweigh Black's unopposed dark-squared bishop. }
14... Nd7
{ You might be concerned about the combination of a4 and O-O-O, but Black is trailing somewhat in development and White might even meet   14...Qa5  with  15.g4!  Qxa4  16.gxh5!?  , and if   16.Kb1  Na6  17.Nc3  would be a calmer choice  16...Qa1+  17.Kd2  Qxb2  18.hxg6  Bxd4  19.gxf7+  Kh8  20.Qd3  followed by Rb1 and/or Ke1 when, amidst all the debris, White's attack appears much the more potent. }
15. g4 { Here we go... } 15... Nf6
{ Nikolic hurries across a defender, but even here his king can't have been breathing too easily. }
16. gxh5 Nxh5 17. f4 Qa5
{ This just seems to lose.   17...Nf6  18.h5!  would also have been very strong, and if  18...Nxe4  19.Nxe4  Bf5  20.hxg6  Bxg6  or   20...fxg6  21.Bc4+  e6  22.Ng5  , crashing through on the light squares  21.f5!  Bxf5  22.Rdg1  Bg6  23.Bc4  when there's just nothing really to be done about Rxg6, as if  23...e6  24.Rxg6!  fxg6  25.Bxe6+  Rf7  26.Ng5  with a complete massacre.   17...Qd5!  , however, would have kept Black on the board for now, even if he would have remained somewhat under the cosh after  18.Kb1   18.Bxh5  gxh5  19.Ng3  Bg4  is one key difference with the game as here  20.Qe4?  is far from deadly  Bf5  19.Bf3  Qd7  20.Rhg1!  followed by an exchange on h5 and Nf3-e5. }
18. Bxh5 gxh5 19. Ng3
{ Preparing to land a second knight dangerously close to the black king. The game should really be up for Nikolic. }
19... Bf5
{ This is easy to criticise, but if   19...Qxa4  20.Qd3  or just   20.Kb1  Rd8  21.Qh7+  Kf8  22.Kb1  when White is the faster and finally crashes through on f7 after  22...Bg4  23.Nxh5  Bxh5  24.Qxh5  Qc4  25.d5!  ,  and   19...Bg4  20.Qe4  would have been similar. }
20. Nxf5
{ White should still be winning after this. He had to avoid   20.Nxh5?  Qxa4  ,  but as Vishy Anand pointed out after the game,   20.d5!  would have cut the defence across the fifth rank and so won quite straightforwardly: for instance,  20...Bh7  or   20...Qb4  21.c3  Qxa4  22.Nxf5  21.Nxh7  Kxh7  22.Qe4+  Kh8  23.Nxh5  followed by Nxg7. }
20... Qxf5 21. Rhg1 Kh8 22. Kb1
{ White is in no rush and may as well secure his own king position before going after the rather sickly pawn on h5. }
22... Rad8 23. Qe2 Rd5
{ And not   23...Rxd4?  24.Rxd4  Bxd4  25.Qxh5+  Kg8  26.Ne4+!  . } 24. Qxh5+
Kg8 25. Qf3
{ Possibly both players were by now expecting a white win and simply going through the motions - ever a dangerous mindset, and one to avoid! Instead,   25.Rde1!  Rxd4  26.Re5  would have forced the pace and led to a fairly simple win after  26...Qg6  27.Qxg6  fxg6  28.Rxe7  Rdxf4  29.Rxb7  followed by invading on e6 and/or pocketing a7. }
25... Rfd8
{ There actually isn't a killer check after   25...Rxd4!  26.Rxd4  Bxd4  , although  27.Rg2  Bg7  28.h5  keeps White's nose clearly in front. }
26. h5 Kf8 27. Qa3
{ This may well already have been time-trouble. Instead,   27.Qg3  would have introduced some timely tactics against the undefended bishop on g7. }
27... Ke8
{ 27...Bxd4!  28.Rge1  c5  would have been game on and with all bets off the table. }
28. Rh1 Bxd4
{ And here   28...Rxd4!  29.Rxd4  Rxd4  30.h6  Bh8  would have been completely unclear. }
29. h6
{ Definitely time-trouble or White would surely have found something stronger than this panicky advance, such as   29.Nf3!?  , and if  29...Bxb2??  30.Rxd5  . }
29... Bxb2
{ Ouch. This must have been overlooked by Barua and presumably by this point pieces were flying as the players frantically blitzed their way towards move 40 @@StartBracket@@remember: no increments back then@@EndBracket@@. }
30. Rxd5 Qxd5 31. Kxb2
{ Barua finds his only chance, trusting in the far-advanced Harry. } 31... Qxh1
32. h7
{ 32.Qb3!  Qxh6  33.Qxf7+  Kd7  34.Qf5+  Ke8  35.Qf7+  Kd7  36.Qf5+  would arguably have been a fitting and fair end to what has become a most hair-raising encounter. }
32... Qh6
{ 32...f6!  would just have won in view of  33.Qb3  or   33.Nh3  Kf7  34.Qb3+  Kg7  fxg5  34.Qg8+  Kd7  , whereas now Black is once again lost. }
33. Qb3 Qf6+ 34. Ka2 Rd4
{ The final error belongs to Black. He would also have lost after   34...e6?  35.Qxb7  ,  35...Rd7  36.Qc8+  Rd8  37.Qxc6+  Kf8  38.Qc7  and even the ultra-calm   34...Rb8!?  wouldn't have saved the day after  35.f5!   35.Qb2  Qxb2+  36.Kxb2  Kd7  37.Nxf7  Ke6  38.h8=Q  Rxh8  39.Nxh8  Kf6!  40.f5  b5  is most likely a draw  and   35.Nxf7  Kd7!  36.h8=Q  Rxh8  37.Qxb7+  Ke6  38.Nxh8  Qxh8  39.Qxc6+  Kf5  may also be one  Kd7  36.Qd3+!   36.Nxf7  Qxf5  37.h8=Q  Rxh8  38.Nxh8  b6  is again unlikely to be winning for White  Kc7  37.Qg3+!  when the win becomes clear:  37...Qd6  or   37...Kc8  38.Qh2  38.Qxd6+  exd6  39.Nxf7  Kd7  40.h8=Q  Rxh8  41.Nxh8  Ke7  42.Ng6+  Kf6  43.Nh4  , etc. }
35. Qxf7+
{ Black would have been more than fine if instead   35.Nxf7?  Rxa4+!  36.Qxa4  Qxf7+  ,  but he shouldn't be able to construct a fortress after   35.Qxf7+  Qxf7+  36.Nxf7  Kxf7  37.h8=Q  Rxa4+  38.Kb3  Rxf4  39.Qe5  . However, you'd surely try to, so possibly Nikolic lost on time or resigned out of disgust that he'd missed the opportunity to leave White with only one pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Turner, Matthew vs. Fernandez, Daniel (Caplin British Online Championship, 2020)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 { 1.e4  d6  2.d4  would, of course, be our route into the game. } 1... d6
2. e4 Nf6
{ Against the Modern,   2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  , which is, incidentally also one of Daniel Fernandez's favourite openings, we'll continue in the same way as against the Pirc:  4.Be2  and only then h4. }
3. Nc3 e5
{ This, the so-called Black Lion, has becoming fairly popular in recent years, in no small part due to Simon. White has a couple of tempting lines, including Shirov's nowadays quite well-known  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.g4!?  , but we'll stick to something more straightforward. }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ 'What, we've exchanged the queens! How are we ever going to attack?' or so you may just have exclaimed. Well, the key factor lies right in front of our eyes: the uncastled king on d8. Black is quite solidly placed and may well now expect a lengthy manoeuvring struggle after  6.Bc4  or  6.Bg5  , only to be stunned by our next direct move. }
6. f4
{ White's main pawn break and one which most certainly can be played straightaway. The aim is simple: to open the position as quickly as possible against the king on d8. }
6... Bb4
{ This counterstrike against e4 is Black's usual reaction, but he can attempt to be more solid with  6...Nbd7  , as we'll see in Line C1 of our coverage of the Black Lion. }
7. Bd3
{ Unfortunately, there's nothing at all great for White after   7.fxe5?!  Nxe4  , so the light-squared bishop must settle for d3 over c4. }
7... Nc6 8. Nf3
{ White's standard choice and a very logical one at that, increasing the central pressure. With Black's knight on c6, the unplayed   8.f5!?  also deserves attention @@StartBracket@@the idea is less effective when Black's queen's knight is on d7 as then he has ...Nc5@@EndBracket@@. White simply intends to complete development with Nf3, Bd2 and O-O-O followed by a kingside pawn storm, one which may leave Black regretting not covering his potential soft spot on d5 with an early ...c6. }
8... Re8
{ Shoring up the centre and not   8...exf4?!  9.Bxf4  Re8  10.O-O-O  . White's lead in development is a very real one all of a sudden and note too how he isn't in the slightest inconvenienced by  10...Bxc3  11.bxc3  . Black is a very long way from targeting the king on c1 and must be careful to survive in the short term with such aggressive moves as e5 and Ng5 on their way. }
9. fxe5
{ Not forced, but the Scottish-registered Grandmaster wants to lure Black's rook into the centre of the board then develop with tempo against it. }
9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Rxe5 11. Bf4
{ Objectively Black is OK here, but in practice his position looks the harder to handle due to his having the more vulnerable king position and White enjoying the main pawn break in the position: e4-e5.   Moreover, Black Lion players might not be feeling so happy here, the position hardly being the solid, slow struggle they likely expected when the queens were removed. }
11... Ra5
{ 11...Bxc3+!?  12.bxc3  is probably a more critical try by Black, pitting his superior structure against White's bishops and activity. It was seen in Babujian-Gokhale, Chennai 2011, where  12...Rc5   13.O-O-O?  Ke8  14.Kb2  Be6  wasn't especially convincing for White. More dynamic would be   12...Ra5  is also possible when White might regroup with  13.c4  Be6  14.a4!?  , intending Bd2-c3 to stabilise the queenside and ideally also force some sort of kingside weakness. Black remains very solid, but White can at least follow up with O-O and a rook to b1 to keep up some pressure.  13.Be3!?  followed by Bd4 or  13...Rxc3  14.O-O-O  . This looks like a somewhat improved version of Babujian-Gokhale and decent compensation. The immediate threat is Bb5+ and Bd4 and while Black can side-step it fairly easily, he must continue to take care with both his advanced rook and king slightly awkwardly placed: for example,  14...Bg4  15.Rd2  Nd7   15...Ke8?  drops the exchange to  16.Kb2  Rc6  17.Bb5  and   15...Ke7?  16.Bd4  Rc6  17.Bb5  does likewise, in view of  17...Re6?  or   17...Nxe4  18.Bxc6  Nxd2  19.Re1+  Be6  20.Bxb7  Rb8  21.Ba6  when the knight will be lost behind enemy lines  18.Bc5+  16.Bd4  Ra3  17.Bxg7  Ke7!  and not   17...Rxa2?  18.Bc4  Ra5  19.Rf1  Rc5  20.Bb3  when White's initiative appears a decisive one, which perhaps isn't a surprise when you look at the two pieces on Black's back rank  18.Bc4  Be6  19.Rhd1!  Nf6!   19...Bxc4?  20.Rxd7+  Ke6  21.Rxc7  followed by Rdd7 or  21...Bb5  22.Rc5!  wins  20.Kb2  . The position remains quite unbalanced and while Black should be able to hold, accuracy is still required from him in no small part due to his king position and White's ability to invade via d7.  The rook can also go backwards, but after   11...Re8  12.O-O-O !  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Bg4  14.Rd2  we'd certainly be quite happy as White. Not only must Black be on his guard against the immediate ideas of e5, Bg5 and Bb5+, but White can expand on the kingside, beginning with h3 and g4. }
12. Bd2
{ Not only preventing Black from doubling the pawns, but also leaving the rook on a5 looking a little misplaced. }
12... Rh5 13. h3
{ This feels like good prophylaxis to avoid   13.O-O  Bc5+  14.Kh1  Ng4  , which Fernandez may well have been hoping to get in.  As well as the text move, there's also   13.O-O-O !?  , as was seen in Karasev-Ostashevsky, Sochi 2015. White threatens Be2 and after  13...Bg4  14.Rdf1  enjoyed a pleasant edge in the game with h3 and g4 on their way, as well as a timely a3. }
13... Be6
{ Black never manages to coordinate his pieces after this, so probably   13...c6!?  14.O-O-O  Ke8  was a better try. Even here, though, White can hardly be unhappy after  15.a3  Ba5   15...Bd6?  16.g4  creates some serious problems for the black rook in view of  16...Re5  17.Bf4  16.Rhf1  , intending Be2 and a timely Bf4. }
14. O-O-O Ke8
{ Going the other way doesn't really help either:   14...Kc8  15.g4!?   15.a3  Bd6  16.Ne2!  is also quite strong, followed by Bc3 and Nd4  Re5  16.a3  Be7  17.Bf4  Rc5  18.Nb5!  . Black's rooks remain a serious cause for concern for him, White has the positionally strong idea of Nd4-f5 to increase the pressure and  18...Nxe4!?  19.Nxc7!  Rxc7  20.Bxe4  Rc4  21.Rhe1  maintains a large advantage, largely due to that rather inactive rook on a8. }
15. a3 Bd6
{ Easy to criticise, but Black is going to find his rook trapped after   15...Ba5?  16.b4!  Bb6  17.Be2  and   15...Bxc3  16.Bxc3  would leave White with a raking dark-squared bishop and strong kingside pressure. }
16. g4
{ Simple chess.   16.Nb5!?  would also have been rather strong, intending g4, as well as simply Nxd6+ cxd6; Bf4. Once again, Black does have  16...Nxe4!?  , but  17.Nxc7+  Bxc7  18.Bxe4  retains a large advantage for White - don't forget that Black can't castle here! }
16... Re5 17. Rhe1
{ Centralisation and strong centralisation at that. White is now set to go not just Nb5, but also Bf4 when the rook can't move on account of e5. }
17... h5
{ 17...Nd7  was the weaker alternative when  18.Nb5  would have freed c3 for the bishop and so preserved White's large advantage. }
18. g5
{ 18.Bf4?  hxg4  19.Bxe5?!  Bxe5  20.hxg4  Nxg4  would have left Black with control, a pawn and too much for the exchange,  but White might have considered   18.gxh5!?  Rxh5  19.Be2!  . This would have been quite committal and is a little risky, but after  19...Rxh3  20.e5  Bxe5  21.Bb5+  c6  22.Rxe5  cxb5  23.Nxb5  White certainly has some initiative for the pawn, and if  23...Kf8!  24.Bb4+  Kg8  25.Nc7  followed by regaining the material on e6. }
18... Nh7 19. h4
{ Shoring up the advanced pawn on g5 and renewing the threat of Bf4. } 19...
Bg4
{ Fernandez continues to defend a difficult position with great skill, but White is still in the driving seat. }
20. Be2 Bxe2 21. Rxe2 Re6 22. Nb5
{ Having seized space on the kingside and driven Black's knight temporarily to the rim, it's high time to resume going forwards. }
22... g6
{ Missing the devious threat. Black needed to find   22...Rd8!  when  23.Nd4  Rg6  24.Rf1  would have favoured White on account of his extra space and superior co-ordination, but still left a full fight ahead. }
23. e5 { A killer blow, the immediate threat being exd6 and Nxc7+. } 23... Rc8
{ This is hopeless, but if   23...Rxe5  24.Rxe5+  Bxe5  25.Re1  or   23...Bxe5  24.Rxe5!  Rxe5  25.Nxc7+  Kd7  26.Nxa8  when the knight will make it out, as with  26...Re8  27.Bb4+  Kc8  28.Bd6  and Nc7. }
24. Nxa7
{ A pretty enough finish in view of   24.Nxa7!  Ra8  or   24...Rd8  25.exd6!  Rxe2  26.dxc7  25.exd6  Rxe2  26.dxc7  when the c-pawn proves decisive.   24.exd6!  Rxe2  25.Nxa7  would, of course, have also done the trick. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Vachier Lagrave, Maxime vs. Papaioannou, Ioannis (European Team Championship, Warsaw, 2013)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ Sensible development and also a line which may well spoil Black's fun, since many Scandinavian players are looking forward to wheeling out their favourite line, be that   3.Nc3  Qa5  or the trendy  3...Qd6  . }
3... Bg4
{ Black's most aggressive choice and a pretty popular one too. In any event, our plan as White will be quite straightforward: prioritise kingside development then quickly, and surprisingly aggressively, hit back. If Black plays slowly that will be with d4 and c4, but in this critical line White may prefer to aim straight for the black king on the queenside. }
4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O
{ Completing the first stage of development. You can also look on White's modest-looking set-up as having lured the typically solid Scandinavian player into a more aggressive set-up than they would normally deploy. }
5... O-O-O
{ 5...Nf6  should also be met by  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Bxf3  Qd7  8.Re1  . As in our main game this is a pretty decent square for the rook, restricting Black's possibilities and play may even transpose, as it does in the event of  8...O-O-O  9.c3  e5!?  . }
6. h3
{ Continuing the kingside-first theme and a useful little prod too. Black is now likely to either cede the bishop-pair or retreat to h5, which is the square his queen would ideally have liked to have gone to. }
6... Bxf3
{ 6...Bh5  is the main continuation, as we'll see in Line E1 of our Scandinavian coverage. Here White has a few options and doesn't even need to push the central pawns just yet:  7.Nc3  Qd7  8.b4!?  is quite a decent gambit, aiming straight for the black king. }
7. Bxf3 Qd7 8. c3
{ A very useful preparatory move. White not only prepares d4, but also b4 and even facilitates Qa4. }
8... e5
{ A major alternative is   8...Ne5  9.d4  Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  , which we'll cover in some detail later on. White's bishop-pair has gone, but the queen is quite well placed on f3. White will bring his knight to c4 and may even then launch a queenside pawn storm. }
9. Re1
{ Pressing against e5 and also helping to ensure that Black won't find it easy to get ...e4 in. }
9... Nf6 10. b4
{ Our favourite advance when the black king is on the queenside and just quite a strong one here. White wants to force the knight to an inferior square with b5.   10.Bxc6?!  Qxc6  11.Rxe5  isn't impossible, but is a little materialistic.  11...Bd6  12.Re1  g5!  leaves Black with the initiative and we want instead to be the side doing the attacking. Moreover, as you'll see in our detailed Scandinavian coverage, it's surprisingly rare how often Black is able to launch an attack - when White handles the opening correctly and doesn't go pawn-grabbing. }
10... Bd6
{ Completing development is a somewhat wiser policy than   10...e4?  11.Bxe4  Nxe4  12.Rxe4  . White will be quick to go d4 and should here have sufficient control over the kingside, unlike in our last note: for example,  12...f5  13.Re1  g5  14.d4  . Now Bxg5 is a threat and even a timely Qh5 might prove annoying for Black. Meanwhile White most certainly hasn't forgotten about the queenside and a certain b5 advance:  14...g4  15.hxg4  fxg4  16.b5  Ne7  17.Nd2!  sees White happy to return a pawn to open lines on the queenside. Black's attack isn't really getting anywhere and White's knight is all set to dominate the board from e4. }
11. d3
{ Restrained play. This keeps control, although the more aggressive and committal   11.b5!?  Na5  12.d4  could also be explored. }
11... Qf5
{ White takes over surprisingly quickly after this. As such, Black probably had to try the slightly desperate-looking   11...e4!  when White has a choice between:    12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Rxe4  , with similar play to our last note, and   12.dxe4  Qe6  13.Qe2  , dodging the check on h2 while retaining control. White will now look to rush his knight to c4 and even  13...Rhe8   13...Qe5?  14.g3  doesn't lead anywhere for Black  14.Be3!  Nxe4  15.b5  should slightly favour knight. If Black's knight goes to the rim, White will settle his bishop on d4 then go Nbd2 and the more aggressive line need not be overly feared:  15...Qe5!?  16.g3!  Nxg3  and not   16...Na5?  17.Bd4  17.fxg3  Qxg3+  18.Kf1  . An only move, but a strong one as Black is now going to have to trade the queens:  18...Qxh3+  19.Qg2  Qxg2+  20.Kxg2  . Black has three pawns for the piece, but White must be slightly for choice with Nd2 next up and still some possibilities of creating pressure against the black queenside, such as with a4-a5 and then b6 or just Bxa7. }
12. Qa4
{ Going straight for the jugular.   12.Qe2  would have left White in control and with a pleasant edge,  and   12.Nd2!  would have been even stronger. Now there's no tricky ...e4 gambit and White has full control of the centre and light squares. Yes, d3 is hanging, but  12...Qxd3  13.Re3  Qg6  14.Qa4  already carries a powerful threat and  14...Kb8?  15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.Nc4  is just lost for Black with Na5 next up. }
12... Qxd3
{ Once again, we see Black going a pawn to the good, but about to come under significant pressure. As such,   12...e4!  was necessary, although here  13.dxe4  Qe5  14.g3  maintains control, and if  14...Bxb4  15.Bf4  Qa5  16.Qb3  followed by Nd2-c4 when White must be clearly for preference. }
13. b5 Nb8 14. Be3
{ Much stronger than swapping b5 for a7 and now White just enjoys a huge attack. }
14... Qf5
{ Perhaps remarkably, Black is just lost after this.   14...a6  15.Nd2!?  or just   15.c4  Qxb5  16.Qc2  would also have been very dangerous for him, as shown by Tom Rendle on ChessPublishing, when Rab1 is imminent: for example,  16...Qe8  17.Rab1  c6  18.Nc4  Bc7  19.Bb6  and Black is just getting crushed with Qb3 next up.  So desperate are matters that the engines already want to go   14...e4!?  15.Rd1  Qxe3  16.fxe3  exf3  17.gxf3  Bc5  , but it's only two pieces for the queen and after  18.Na3!  Bxe3+  19.Kh1  followed by Nc4 White really should just be winning with a little care. }
15. Nd2
{ Completing development and ensuring that ...e4 won't be anything to worry about. }
15... Bc5
{ Easy to criticise, but even   15...Rhe8  16.Bxa7  should be winning for White followed by b6 or just Rad1 and Ne4 with complete control. }
16. Ne4 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 h5
{ Now a7 falls after all, but Black's queenside also wouldn't have been long for the world in the event of   17...a6  18.bxa6  Nxa6  19.Rb1  with unbearable pressure against b7. }
18. Qxa7 Nd5 19. Nc5
{ And that was already just that. Rarely does one see a 2600+ Grandmaster decimated so quickly. }
19... Nxe3 20. Qxb7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Richmond, Peter vs. Smith, Graham (Major Open, Liverpool, 2008)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3
{ This unusual yet aggressive move is likely to catch out even an experienced Alekhine player. Rather than blitz out one of their favourite lines after  3.d4  d6  , they suddenly have to deal with an immediate attack on their knight and one which has not entailed White having to make the double-edged pawn push that is  4.c4  . }
3... c6
{ Black still hopes that his bishop might make it out along the c8-h3 diagonal one day, but this is a somewhat rare choice compared to   3...e6  , which we'll explore in plenty of detail in our Alekhine coverage later on. }
4. d4
{ Only now that Black has committed to ...c6 does White expand in the centre.  As we'll see, the white queen often takes up an aggressive role in g3 in this variation and the immediate   4.Qg3  is by no means ridiculous.  However, White's best move is   4.Nc3!  , as played by Simon. After  4...Nb6?!  Somewhat passive. Much more active would be   4...Nb4  , but then White can reveal another point behind his set-up in  5.Bc4!  , threatening mate and we'll explore this in a little more detail at the start of Chapter Six.  5.d4  d5  6.exd6  Opening lines, but according to taste White might have preferred   6.Bd3!?  followed by Qg3 and Nf3 when Black is looking rather passively placed indeed.  exd6  7.Bd3  Be7  8.h4!?  True to form, Simon can't resist involving Harry as early as possible;   8.Qg3  would also have left White with an active and promising game.  N8d7  . We've followed the game Williams-Levin, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2016, and, yes, a Russian Grandmaster no less is sitting behind Black's slightly cramped set-up. Now  9.Qg3!  would have been strong, since even gambiting g7 doesn't especially help Black:  9...Nf6!?  Otherwise,   9...g6?!  10.h5  already carries a certain threat  and   9...O-O ?!  10.Bh6  Bf6  11.Nge2  leaves Black under strong, ongoing pressure, with White likely to go O-O-O, Bf4 when needed, Qf3 and g4-g5.  10.Qxg7!  Rg8  11.Qh6  Rxg2  12.Bg5  . This cuts off the rook's retreat, leaving it vulnerable to being trapped. White simply intends Ne2-f4, with Qg7 also likely to prove something of a headache for Black, as could O-O-O and e1. }
4... d6
{ Naturally Black takes the chance to try and break free to an extent. } 5. a3
{ A crafty move, preparing c4.  The immediate   5.c4?!  Nb4!  is a little awkward for White, as  6.Qb3  or   6.Na3  dxe5  7.dxe5  Qa5  8.Qc3  Bf5  when Black is calling the shots  c5  leaves him on the back foot,  but   5.exd6  Qxd6  6.c3  Nd7  wasn't totally ridiculous in Masek-Srba, Prague 2009, where  7.Bc4  e5  8.Ne2  Be7  9.O-O  O-O  would probably have been about equal. There's no reason White shouldn't aim for more than that, though, hence Richmond's crafty choice. }
5... dxe5
{ Unable to actively deploy his light-squared bishop, it makes sense for Black to try and create a target on e5. }
6. dxe5 Qc7
{ Consistent, but not best.  After   6...Nd7  , as well as  7.Qg3  ,  Smith was probably concerned by   7.e6!?  . We'll make good use of this disruptive pawn advance in a number of lines and here  7...fxe6  8.Nh3  , heading for g5, should offer White decent compensation: for example,  8...e5  9.Ng5  N7f6  10.Bd3  . White doesn't object to simply going 0-0 and Re1, but he already has quite a threat in Bxh7 and  10...Bg4   10...Qb6?  rather misses the threat:  11.Bxh7!  Nxh7  12.Qh5+  Kd7  13.Nf7  when White will at least regain his piece with interest, e.g.  13...Ndf6  14.Qf5+  Ke8  15.Qg6  Bf5  16.Nd6+  Kd7  17.Nxf5  and   10...g6  11.O-O  Bg7?!  is also flawed:  12.Nxh7!  , since  12...Nxh7  13.Bxg6+  Kd7  14.Bxh7  regains the material with interest thanks to the potential fork on f5.  11.Qg3  Bh5   11...e6!  12.Nxh7!   12.Bxh7  Rxh7!  13.Nxh7  Ne3!  is a remarkable resource, threatening mate and leaving Black with perpetual check after  14.Nxf6+  gxf6  15.fxe3  Qd1+  16.Kf2  Qe2+  e4!  is probably the critical line when  13.Bxe4  Bd6  14.Nxf6+  Nxf6  15.Bg6+  Kf8  16.Qd3  leads to a quite a mess, where White should aim to quickly develop the queenside with Nc3 and Bg5.  12.O-O  h6  can be met by  13.Ne6  or even   13.Ne4!?  , which keeps Black somewhat tied up, not least in contrast to White's easy development. }
7. Qg3
{ The best of defending e5 and a key feature of the 3.Qf3 variation - the queen slides over to a fine location, tying Black's bishop down to the defense of g7. }
7... Bf5
{ 7...g6  may look more logical, but even here Black will come under pressure:  8.Nf3  Bg7  9.c4  Nb6  10.Bf4  . White already threatens e6, has ideas of Nd2/c3-e4 and Harry may well be quick to join in the fun with h4-h5. }
8. c4 { Driving back the once proud knight. } 8... Nb6
{ Taking stock, we find Black with two minor pieces developed to White's zero, but also definitely worse. Why? Well the bridgehead on e5 divides his position in two and he lacks a good pawn break with ...f6; Bf4 only likely to play into White's hands. White will be quick to develop his knights to c3 and f3, and his extra space should really count for something. }
9. Nc3 e6 10. Nf3 N8d7
{ Smith finds the best defence, directing his knight towards c5 in a bid to exploit White's slightly vulnerable light squares. }
11. Be3
{ Simply preventing ...Nc5 unless Black wants to sacrifice g7.   11.b4?  a5!  would have been too ambitious,  but   11.Bf4!?  Nc5  12.Nd4  followed by Rd1 was a different way of covering the holes on d3 and b3 @@StartBracket@@and not  12...O-O-O  13.O-O-O ??  Rxd4!  14.Rxd4  Nb3+  . }
11... a5
{ Positionally well-motivated, but too slow.   11...Nc5!?  wasn't ridiculous, since Black will castle long and enjoy definite counterplay if White takes on c5 and g7. However,  12.Rd1!  would have cut across such plans, leaving White with an edge after  12...Nba4  13.Bxc5!  Nxc5  14.b4  when White has regained the initiative and it's not impossible to imagine Black being squeezed to death if White gets c5 in.   11...g6  12.Be2  Bg7  13.Bf4  would also have been somewhat better than the game for Black, leaving him still slightly cramped, but free to castle on either side. }
12. Be2
{ White has now caught up in the development stakes.  The bishop-hunting   12.Nh4!?  was also tempting, since Black can't capture on e5 due to the potentially hanging knight on b6. }
12... Bg6
{ Blocking the white queen's route to g7, but, once again, very slow. } 13. h4
{ Even stronger than  13.Nh4  , as Harry joins the party. Smith chooses to block its advance, but doing so only creates even more weaknesses. }
13... h5
{ 13...Nc5!?  14.h5  Bf5  15.O-O  followed by Nd4 would have been excellent for White, but still likely had to be tried by Black. }
14. Ng5
{ The e5-pawn is still taboo and now White has a definite threat on e6. } 14...
O-O-O
{ Desperation, as   14...Bf5  15.Nge4  Bxe4  16.Nxe4  followed by Nd6+ would have been a positional nightmare for Black. }
15. Nxe6
{ Cashing in, but   15.Nce4!  Bxe4  16.Nxe4  was likely even stronger, since, say,  16...Kb8  17.Nd6  Bxd6  18.exd6  Qc8  19.b4  would be extremely unpleasant for Black and surely resignable. }
15... fxe6 16. Qxg6
{ This doesn't quite net a pawn as e5 is now hanging, but White has bagged the bishop-pair and also enjoys much the safer king. }
16... Qxe5 17. Qe4
{ A strong offer to exchange the queens as even now White's knight will be extremely well placed on e4. }
17... Bd6
{ 17...Qxe4  18.Nxe4  Be7  19.O-O-O  would have left White dominating the board,  but Black had to try that or   17...Qf5  when  18.Rh3!  and Rf3 would be a nice touch to confirm White's clear superiority. }
18. c5
{ Ouch and there's little as satisfying as landing a break on a square your opponent thought they controlled. This decisive overloading tactic completes a fine display by the strong Welsh amateur. Unfortunately for Black, he is losing a piece whether he exchanges queens and is then fully forked or with   18.c5  Nxc5  or   18...Bxc5  19.Qxe5  Nxe5  20.Bxc5  19.Qxe5  Bxe5  20.Bxc5  . }
