{ is a pet line of Simon's which should throw even experienced Alekhine players. Black can no longer go 3...d6 and may find himself in an unfamiliar set-up: }
3... Nb6 4. a4
{ continues to disrupt. If Black blocks, White will complete development with d4, Be3 and possibly a pinning Bb5, and if he doesn't, White will seize the initiative: }
4... d6 5. a5 N6d7 6. e6 fxe6 7. a6
{ is an unusual take on a disruptive pawn sacrifice we use wherever possible in the repertoire. Note how awkward it is likely to be for Black to develop his bishop from f8, in part because ...g6 will often run into h4-h5 - see Line F2. }
