[White "Pirc A6: 5...h5"]
[Black "A6: 5...h5  #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... O-O
{ Black's best move according to some Pirc sources, only housing the king now that White can't rip open the h-file. Of the alternatives, the most important are 6...Bg4 and 6... c6. }
7. Ng5
{ Once again, White wastes no time installing his knight on a fine post from where it can, of course, no longer be kicked by ...h6. }
7... c6
{ is again Black's main alternative to trying to counter in the centre and, again, White doesn't have to allow ...b5: }
8. a4
{ Once again,  8.O-O !?  is also a decent option here and seen below in the pretty instructive encounter Neubauer-Lehner, Austrian League 2017. }
8... Ng4
{ 8...e5?  is also best avoided as Black due to a simple plan we've already seen on a few occasions:  9.dxe5!  dxe5  10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.Bc4  Rd7   11...Rf8  12.b3!  will force Black to badly weaken with ...c5 after Ba3.  12.f3  . White simply intends Be3 and Rd1, and it's far from easy for Black to shake off White's firm grip on the position: for example,  12...Nh7  13.Be3  Nxg5  14.hxg5  Re7  15.O-O-O  Re8  16.Rd6!  already left Black rather struggling to deal with the threat of Rxg6 in Marholev-Banos, Figueres 2007, in view of  16...Kf8  17.Bc5  .   8...Nbd7  was suggested by the strong Slovak GM and noted theoretician Igor Stohl and was tested in Drazic-Lupu, Bastia @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2000, where White simply went 9. Be3. That can hardly be bad and White might do even better going route one:  9.f4!?  9...e5  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.f5!  with early and significant pressure on the kingside and light squares. }
9. f3 Nh6
{ This was our introductory game Barua-Nikolic, Biel Interzonal 1993, where a pretty good case was made for  10.Be3  and already White might even have preferred }
10. g4
{ This is blunt, but gxh5 is clearly a threat and White is happy to sacrifice: }
10... hxg4 11. h5
{ Even  11.fxg4  e5  12.d5  is very promising, if arguably less fun. } 11...
gxh5 12. Rxh5
{ Now  12...--  13.fxg4  may just happen or even  12...--  13.Nh7!?  . Black can try to save his knight, but even pushing the f-pawn fails to dent the notion that White is just doing very well:   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppb1/2pp3n/6NR/P2PP1p1/2N2P2/1PP1B3/R1BQK3 b Q - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...f6   Alternatively,  12...gxf3  13.Bxf3  keeps the knight stranded,   12...e5  13.Be3  maintains control while preparing Qd2 and O-O-O,  and  12...Nd7  fails to, among others,  13.Ne6!  fxe6  14.Bxh6  Bxh6  15.Rxh6  Rf6  16.Qd2  Qf8  17.Rh1!  .  13.Nh7!?  Qe8   13...Kxh7  14.Bxh6  Bxh6?  15.Qd2  regains the piece with a devastating attack.  14.fxg4  Kxh7  15.g5  fxg5  16.Bxg5   Yes, it is a whole piece, but Qd2 is next up and Black is also vulnerable down the b1-h7 diagonal, as shown most obviously by  16...Nd7  17.e5!  when even after  17...Rh8   or  17...Rf5  18.Bxh6  18.Qd2  Kg8  19.O-O-O!   19.Bxh6  Qg6  instead would be better for Black!   After long castles, however, White's attack should be winning, for instance: @@StartFEN@@r1b1q1kr/pp1np1b1/2pp3n/4P1BR/P2P4/2N5/1PPQB3/2KR4 b - - 4 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Nf5  20.Rxh8+  Bxh8  21.exd6  Nf8   21...exd6  22.Bc4+!  d5  23.Nxd5!  cxd5  24.Bxd5+  Kf8  25.Bh6+  is the end, and if  25...Nxh6  26.Qxh6+  Bg7  27.Rf1+  22.dxe7  Nxe7  23.Rg1  Neg6  24.Bd3  followed by Bh6 or Ne4.  The moral of the story: when attacking and the opponent has no counterplay what really matters is not just material, but can the defender successfully use their extra material to desperately plug lines? Here the answer would appear to be a resounding no. For the record, best play according to the silicon beast appears to be:  24...Be6  25.Ne4  threatening both Nf6+ and even Bf6  25...Qf7  26.Bh6  Bxd4  27.Rf1  Qh7  28.Kb1!  followed by Qg5 or  28...Bd5  29.Bc4!  Ne6  staying afloat for now on the two long diagonals towards the black king, but after  30.Bxd5  cxd5  31.Nf6+  Bxf6  32.Rxf6  Re8  33.Qg2  White will finally regain his piece and be left with an ongoing powerful initiative. }
