[White "Pirc A6: 5...h5"]
[Black "A6: 5...h5  #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... c5
{ is, of course, very similar to Line A5. Again, White can advance or exchange, with the latter our preference }
7. dxc5 Qa5
{ Here  8.Bd2  would be a little meek, especially when Black might play to occupy the g4-square after  8...Qxc5  , so White has tended to prefer  8.Ng5  Qxc5  9.Be3  . That's pretty logical, but we actually prefer an as-yet-untested approach. It may initially appear greedy, but is also pretty aggressive }
8. cxd6 Nxe4 9. dxe7
{ This is clearly critical and is also quite liked by the engines. Moreover, Black is pretty much forced to exchange }
9... Nxc3
{ 9...Nc6?  gives Black good play, but here White can castle and is doing pretty well:  10.O-O  Nxc3   or  10...Bxc3  11.bxc3  Nxc3  12.Qe1  Nxe2+  13.Qxe2  when Black's dark squares are a truly shocking sight.  11.bxc3  Bxc3?   11...Nxe7  is safer, but still leaves Black in serious danger  12.Bg5  when the threats include Qd6, Nd4-b5, Bc4 and Nd2-e4.  12.Bg5!  is very strong and leaves Black facing ruin thanks to that mighty pawn on e7.   12...f6   12...Bxa1  13.Qxa1  Rg8  14.Rd1  leaves Black so tied up he may as well resign!  13.Rb1!   This brutal sacrifice is even stronger than  13.Bf4  ; now Rb5 and Qd6 are on their way.  13...fxg5  14.Qd6  Nxe7  15.Bb5+  Kf8   15...Nc6  16.Ne5!  is crushing.  16.Rfe1  leaves White with a crushing attack, as shown by  16...Rh7   or  16...Bxe1  17.Qf6+  Kg8  18.Rxe1  17.Nxg5  Rg7  18.Bc4  followed by Re3, with the threat of Rxc3!, or  18...Bxe1  19.Qf6+  Ke8  20.Qxg7 }
10. bxc3 Bxc3+ 11. Bd2
{ Taking stock, we find White still a pawn to the good and, crucially, with much the safer king. Indeed, White is all set to castle, Black can't take the rook and neither is exchanging on c3 anything close to a panacea for him  11...Bxd2+  12.Nxd2  Nc6  13.O-O   Now Ne4 or  Nc4  will follow and while Black doesn't have to recapture the pawn with his king, he will come under significant pressure in any case:  13...Kxe7   13...Nxe7  14.Nc4  comes with tempo, as will Nd6+ and then Bc4.  14.Ne4  Qc7  15.Rb1!?   This sneaky little move is by no means White's only good one -  15.Bc4  and  15.Re1  both spring more readily to mind -, but prepares to increase the pressure with Rb5 and Qa1, and also sets a little trap:   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppq1kp2/2n3p1/7p/4N2P/8/P1P1BPP1/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bf5?  16.Rxb7!  and if  16...Qxb7  17.Qd6+  Ke8  18.Nf6#  Olé! }
