[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... Nc6 { angles for ...e5, but White can beat Black to the central bounce }
7. d5 Ne5
{ 7...Nb8  is untested, but feels like a safer try when you want be content to manoeuvre with, say, O-O, Nd4 and Be3 or Bg5, but our thematic knight advance is also possible:  8.Ng5  O-O  9.Be3   @@StartBracket@@Those of a really aggressive bent may also wish to consider  9.f3  c6  10.g4!?  .@@EndBracket@@  9...c6  10.O-O  . White is now ready to advance with f4-f5. Two other potentially important moves are Bd4 and a2-a4. The latter restricts Black's counterplay, as even does  10...b5?!  11.a3!  again followed by f2-f4 or  11...cxd5  12.Nxd5!  , which takes full advantage of some potential loose pieces in the black camp. }
8. Nxe5
{ Damaging Black's structure and avoiding allowing him the counterplay that  8.Nd4  c6  would, and if  9.f4?  Neg4 }
8... dxe5 9. Bg5
{ White finds a second piece able to make good use of the hole on g5 and we'll see how Black might develop in no less a game than Kasparov-Speelman, Paris @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 1990. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pirc A6: 5...h5"]
[Black "A6: 5...h5  #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... Bg4
{ is, of course, a possibility allowed by the decision to develop the knight to f3, not h3, but need not be feared. Rather than allow Black to exchange on f3 and strike on the dark squares, White should carry out the thematic leap: }
7. Ng5 Bxe2 8. Qxe2
{ The most aggressive and logical follow-up, although Baadur Jobava no less has preferred  8.Nxe2  . }
8... Nc6
{ Black should press on the more sensitive of White's central pawns so, whereas  8...Nbd7?  merely encourages White's favourite central steamroller:  9.e5  dxe5  10.dxe5  Ng4  11.e6!  and Black was already in huge trouble with White's queen or knight set to land on e6 in Garcia Fernandez-P. Garcia, Albacete 1992. }
9. Be3
{ White prepares to give up the dark-squared bishop to maintain his strong centre. This is a big decision, but certainly gives Black less counterplay than  9.d5  Nd4  and  9.e5  Nh7! }
9... Ng4 10. O-O-O
{ Keeping d4 secure and eyeing both central advances, as well as f2-f4. } 10...
Nxe3
{ Standard and  10...e6?  11.d5!  merely saw White crashing through in Marholev-Sibilio, Roseto degli Abruzzi 2014:  11...Nxe3  12.Qxe3  exd5  13.exd5+  Ne7  14.Rhe1  . This clearly prevented Black from castling and while  14...Kf8  15.f3  Nf5  16.Qf2  was possible, this is still very pleasantly better for White thanks to his dominant knight on g5. Now Nce4 and g4 might follow and an exchange on c3 need not be feared:  16...Bxc3  17.bxc3  Qf6  18.g4!  . White seizes the initiative and actually has somewhat the safer king, despite the split queenside pawns. Exchanging on g4 would cost Black a piece due to the pin down the f-file and  18...Ng7  19.Qg3!  maintains the initiative followed by Rd4-f4 or even Qf4:  19...Qxc3?  20.Qf4  f5  21.Re3!  Qa1+  22.Kd2  Qf6  23.gxf5  . White will simply follow up with Rde1 and do just observe how hamstrung Black is due to that gaping weakness on e6. }
11. fxe3
{ This creates some immediate threats, although a pretty decent case can also be made for  11.Qxe3  , as played by a young Gajewski,  followed by f2-f4 or  11...e5  12.dxe5 }
11... Qd7
{ 11...e5?  12.Rdf1!  again sees White playing on the potential weakness of e6. Black clearly can't push the f-pawn, but Rxf7 is a big threat and even  12...Rf8  13.d5  Ne7  14.g4  leaves Black under huge pressure followed by picking off h5 or crashing through down the h-file:  14...hxg4  15.h5  and the rook will reach h7.   11...O-O ?  12.g4  reveals why Black should have brought his queen to d7. He is simply quite lost here:  12...hxg4  13.h5!  gxh5  14.Rxh5  and can you already spot the mate in four White is threatening? }
12. e5
{ Very aggressive, but it makes good sense to seize the initiative with Black's king still in the centre and this appears even stronger than bringing a rook to f1. White now has ideas of not just Rhf1, but also e6 fxe6; Qd3. }
12... Qg4
{ 12...dxe5  13.dxe5  Qg4  was perhaps a better version of the same idea, if still very good for White after  14.e6!  .  Clearly going long as Black would drop the exchange and going short walks straight into two powerful pawn blows   12...O-O ?  13.e6!  fxe6  14.g4  with an overwhelming attack - just observe how vulnerable Black is on the light squares. }
13. Qb5
{ Naturally White retains the queens and now threatens Qxb7, as well as d4-d5. }
13... Rb8 14. Qb3 O-O 15. Rhf1
{ Logically increasing the pressure.  15.e6?  f6!  was much less effective in Sherzer-Zaichik, Philadelphia @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 1996. }
15... e6 16. Rf4
{ The main point of White's last move. Now Black is pretty much forced to snaffle.   16...Qxg2  17.Rdf1!   if  17...Nd8?  then  18.Nce4  dxe5  19.Nf6+!  followed by dxe5 and Nfh7 or  19...Bxf6  20.Rxf6  crashes through. Black's knight needs to stay on d8 to guard f7, but that leaves his rooks split. Meanwhile White threatens dxe5 and/or Qd3, i.e.  20...exd4  21.Qd3!  threatening Rxg6+! and finally picking off f7 after  21...Kg7  22.Qxd4  Kg8  23.Qd7  17...dxe5  18.Rxf7  Rxf7  19.Rxf7  Nd8  20.Re7  Threatening Re8+.  20...Qf1+  21.Nd1  Qf8  Black has done well to beat off the immediate threats and to get his queen back, but remains vulnerable on the light squares and worse after  22.Rxe6!  Kh8  23.Rxg6  Qf5!  24.Qd3  Qxd3  25.cxd3  exd4  26.Kc2  when White is looking for Black to move his knight then go Ne6 or to suddenly increase the pressure with  26...dxe3?  27.Nxe3  and Nf5. }
*

