[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pirc A6: 5...h5"]
[Black "A6: 5...h5  #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... c6 7. Ng5
{ is a fairly common position as it can arise via both Nf3 and Nh3 move orders. Again we see Black not rushing to commit his king, but having to be wary of a timely e4-e5-e6. }
7... b5
{ By some margin Black's main reply and consistent, of course, with his last.  Of the alternatives, you'll likely have a good inkling by now of how to punish   7...Nbd7?  :  8.e5!  . Yes, once again e5-e6 will simply leave Black in huge trouble:  8...dxe5  9.dxe5  Nh7   9...Nxe5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.f4  is the key tactical point which underpins White's play - all made possible by that huge knight on g5.  10.e6  Ne5  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  left White with a few tempting and strong options in V.Onischuk-Rozhko, European Rapid Championship, Tallinn 2016, of which arguably the strongest wastes no time returning an extra pawn to maintain a virulent initiative:  12.Nxf7+!?  Nxf7  13.exf7  Be6  14.Bf4  Bxf7  15.O-O-O+  . Black's cause already looks problematic with both Rhe1 and Ne4 on their way; the latter rather keeps the black knight on h7 as ...Nf6 would be well met by Ng5. }
8. O-O
{ This simple and fairly rare choice and accompanying exclaim may come as a small surprise, but there's no need to fear ...b4 and this is one position where, unfortunately, our standard method fails to impress:  8.e5  dxe5  9.dxe5  Qxd1+  10.Bxd1  Nd5  isn't awful for White, but seems fine for Black largely because, perhaps ironically, White's knight is now away from the key central action on g5, leaving it unable to go to d4 in one move. }
8... O-O
{ 8...b4  9.Na4  is possible with e4 overprotected and White now has a simple plan: Bd2 and a2-a3 with queenside pressure: for example,  9...O-O  10.Bd2  a5  11.a3  bxa3  12.Rxa3  when White may seize further space with c2-c4 or even look to quickly expand with e4-e5, whether immediately or after a preliminary Bc3 or Bf4.   8...Qc7  can be met by either  9.Bf4  e5  10.Bg3  , retaining both control and definite ideas of the pawn breaks a2-a4 and f2-f4, or even the direct  9.f4!?  b4   9...Ng4!?  may improve, taking advantage of the hole White has just created and preparing to meet 10.e5 with d5. Nevertheless, White does still have a powerful centre and after  10.Bf3  is ready to go both e4-e5 and Ne2, not to mention f4-f5. Perhaps the key line runs:  10...Qb6  11.Ne2  c5  12.e5  Nc6  13.Nc3!?  , which does use up two tempi in a rather sharp scenario, but suddenly Nd5 is on its way, after which c2-c3 will bolster things unless Black exchanges, of course:  13...cxd4  14.Nd5  Qd8!   Now  15.Nb4?  Nxb4  16.Bxa8  Qb6  would leave Black with far too many squares and far too much play for the exchange,  but  15.a4!  is a timely challenge, and if  15...bxa4  16.Qd3!  when the threats include Qc4, Nf6+ and even e5-e6.  10.Na4  . Once again, we find White ready to fight back on the queenside, be it with a2-a3 or c2-c3 and  10...Nbd7?  11.e5  Nd5  12.e6!  saw Black once again underestimating White's central play at his peril in Palmiotto-Toniutti, Rio Tercero 2012. }
9. Bf4
{ White calmly continues to develop. Now Qd2, Rad1 and Rfe1 may follow and even e4-e5 dxe5; Bxe5 becomes an idea in some positions, such as if Black's queen's knight is developed via a6. The immediate threat, though, is e5 dxe5; dxe5, opening the position to favour White's superior development, after which Bf3 and/or a2-a4 may leave Black looking rather overextended. Moreover, it's easy for him to err here: }
9... Nbd7 10. e5
{ Suddenly there just isn't a good move for Black with e5-e6 set to land with tempo, or if  10...b4   Angling for  11.Na4  Nd5  .  11.exf6  exf6  12.Nxf7!  Rxf7  13.Ne4  when Black once again finds himself badly overextended. He can hold things together for now with  13...d5  14.Nd6  Re7  15.Qd2  a5  but after  16.Rfe1  the pressure will quickly begin to mount, be it with Bd3, a2-a3 or even c2-c4, laying siege to d5 and aiming to go after Black's weaknesses down the c-file }
*

