1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... c6 7. Ng5
{ is a fairly common position as it can arise via both Nf3 and Nh3 move orders. Again we see Black not rushing to commit his king, but having to be wary of a timely e4-e5-e6. }
7... Qc7
{ is a better way of preparing ...e5 for Black. White has a few options here, but we quite like simply restricting Black's play with }
8. a4 { Now O-O and f2-f4 may follow, as well as Bc4. } 8... e5
{ was consistent, but arguably flawed from Black in Jobava-T.L.Petrosian, World Blitz Championship, Moscow 2019, as now White might again have exploited his strong knight to target Black's weakest point, f7: }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Bc4 O-O 11. Be3
{ White might have lost a tempo with his light-squared bishop, but his pieces coordinate wonderfully. The immediate threat is Bc5 and again we find Black wishing that ...h6 was still legal, with, for example   11...Nbd7  12.Qe2  Ng4  13.Bd2  Nc5  14.f3  Nf6  15.Be3  maintaining control and an excellent version of a Classical Pirc for White who will be quick to increase the pressure, as with  15...Qe7  16.Qf2  b6  17.a5 }
