1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ Black's most popular and sensible choice, stopping our h-pawn in its tracks. }
6. Nf3
{ White immediately spies and prepares to take advantage of the main downside to Black's last move, the weakening of the g5-square. It's also possible to rush the knight towards g5 with  6.Nh3  .  That's far from a terrible choice, but does allow Black the chance to trade off a potentially problematic bishop with  6...Bxh3  7.Rxh3  . If you like bishops, though, you might well be happy enough here and may wish to consider continuing in aggressive vein with 8.f4!?. }
6... c6 7. Ng5
{ is a fairly common position as it can arise via both Nf3 and Nh3 move orders. Again we see Black not rushing to commit his king, but having to be wary of a timely e4-e5-e6. }
7... Qa5 8. O-O
{ quickly unpins and might be followed by a4, Bc4 or even f2-f4 and e4-e5: for instance, }
8... Na6
{ 8...b5?  9.e5!  would again be most unwise for Black, and if  9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Ng4  11.e6  , thematically crashing through in the centre. }
9. Bc4 O-O { as in Otero Acosta-Resende, Havana 2006, where } 10. Bb3
{ would have prepared to meet } 10... b5 11. Ne2
{ Note how again the knight on  g5  does a great job, here of overprotecting e4 while pressing on f7. As such, White is all set to increase the pressure with Nf4 or if  11...e5?!  12.f4!  thereby further increasing the pressure down the f-file and towards the black king. }
