[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games I"]
[Black "Sharafiev, Azat vs. Kupreichik, Viktor"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 c6 6. h5 gxh5
{ Black decides that exchanging so is the lesser option, but already White should be pretty happy with how the opening is panning out. }
7. Nh3
{ Declining the immediate recapture to rush the king's knight towards its favourite square. }
7... Nbd7 8. Nf4 Qb6 9. a3
{ The point of this possibly mysterious move will quickly become clear. It's a good move, but likely not quite as strong as the more aggressive  9.a4  , as advocated in Line A4. }
9... Nf8
{ Black is forced to contort to an extent to untangle his position. He might have preferred to hit back in the centre, but   9...e5  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Be3!  is just extremely pleasant for White after Nxh5 or  11...Qxb2?  12.Na4  , which traps the black queen. You might be worried that things are still a little messy, but following  12...exf4  White doesn't have to capture on b2 and see Black do likewise on e3. Indeed,  13.Bxf4!  just looks very strong, and if  13...Nd5  14.Nxb2  Nxf4  15.Nc4!  , offering to return more material to pursue the initiative and go after the black king.  So too would   9...O-O  be met by  10.Be3  when after  10...Qc7  White might even delay Nxh5 for a move to go  11.Qd2  , the point behind to have the option of Bh6 as soon as Nxh5 has landed and, no,  11...h4  12.Rxh4  e5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Nh5  doesn't improve matters for Black and especially the state of his king. }
10. Be3
{ Once again, the bishop emerges as Black dare not touch the poisoned pawn on b2. }
10... Ng6
{ Sometimes  10...Ng4?  can make White wish he hadn't delayed the capture on h5, but not here:  11.Nxh5  Nxe3  12.Nxg7+  Kd8  13.fxe3  wins a piece. }
11. Nxh5
{ Only now that Sharafiev has developed all the minor pieces does he recoup the pawn and note that  11.Qd2?  would be one developing move too many:  11...Qxb2  is not on because the rook on a1 has lost its protection. }
11... Nxh5 12. Rxh5
{ The most aggressive way to recapture, as well as one which avoids  12.Bxh5?  Qxb2!  , and if  13.Na4  Qb5  . }
12... O-O 13. Bc4
{ Sharafiev decides that it's time to activate. He might also have considered the simple  13.Rb1  and then Qd2. Note that White holds back advancing either pawn as doing so would merely give Black a target and counterplay, as well as that the white king will be quite safe on f1 or g1 should it need to vacate the centre. }
13... Be6
{ This seems as a good a defensive try as anything else and at least it completes Black's development. Instead, something like  13...Qc7?  would have been very well met by  14.Rh1!  and Qh5. }
14. Na4
{ Chasing the queen backwards before exchanging on b2, as White wants to ensure that b2 isn't hanging and don't forget that currently the a5-square is controlled by White, so there's no check to worry about. }
14... Qc7 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qg4
{ Boom! White's queen finally emerges and with some force on the kingside. Black surely won't manage to hold on to both e6 and h7 for long. }
16... Qc8 17. f4
{ Another important move as the pawns assist the pieces in a manner which would have made Philidor proud. Instead,  17.Qh3?  e5!  would have brought Black right back into the game. }
17... e5
{ This fails to convince, but after, say,  17...b5  18.Nc3  a5  White would have crashed through with  19.f5  exf5  20.exf5  followed by Qh3 or Ne4-g5. }
18. f5
{ Naturally White keeps the queens on ahead of teeing up a certain combination. }
18... exd4 19. Rxh7 Kxh7
{ Black's cause would also have been quite hopeless after  19...dxe3  20.Rxg7+!  Kxg7  21.Qxg6+  Kh8  22.Ke2  followed by mate down the h-file. }
20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. fxg6
{ Threatening mate and the routine manner in which Sharafiev now finishes off his famous opponent should really be stored in all chess players' memory banks. }
21... Rf6 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Bh6
{ Black's bishop is fatally overloaded as if  23.Bh6  Bxh6  24.Qh8  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games I"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Speelman, Jonathan"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. d5
{ Pressing straight ahead before Black can get in ...e5. } 7... Ne5
{ This works in some Pirc positions, but there's a good reason why we focused on  7...Nb8  8.Ng5  in Line A6. }
8. Nxe5
{ Not only ruining Black's structure, but also stunting the gaze of the Pirc bishop on g7. }
8... dxe5 9. Bg5
{ Kasparov finds a second piece able to occupy g5 with some effect. Now Black will always need to consider the pin should he want to try and break out with ...e6. }
9... a6
{ 9...c6?!  10.dxc6  Qxd1+  11.Rxd1  bxc6  fails to give Black any real counterplay after simply  12.f3!  . Now White is ready to go Na4-c5 or even Rd3 and Nd1-e3, leaving him in control and also ready to begin targeting Black's weakened queenside.  And what of the other central break? Well,   9...e6?  10.f4!  takes immediate advantage of the pin and after  10...Qd6   10...exf4?  11.e5  simply wins a piece with ...h5-h6, of course, impossible  11.Bb5+!  Bd7  12.fxe5  Qxe5  13.O-O  White's lead in development is already very much felt, with Bf4 but one threat. }
10. Qd2
{ Calmly continuing to develop and allowing White to consider Bh6 should Black castle. Kasparov is also fully aware that there's no need to fear any queenside expansion from Black. }
10... b5 11. f3
{ Making sure that e4 doesn't fall and next White will strike back on the queenside. }
11... Rb8
{ 11...b4  12.Nd1  Rb8  13.a3  would have been similar, and if  13...a5  14.axb4  axb4  15.b3  followed by Ra4 or  15...Bd7  16.Nf2  and Nd3. }
12. a4
{ Not for the first time, we find that Black's early queenside demonstration has actually only weakened his position on that flank. }
12... b4 13. Nd1
{ The knight heads for c4 via e3 and White may also entertain ideas of a4-a5 and Ra4. }
13... c6
{ Speelman decides that he must break, otherwise something like  13...O-O  14.a5  Ne8  15.Nf2  and not   15.Ne3??  f6  15...Nd6  16.Ra4  b3  17.c4  would just have been pretty painful for Black, with c4-c5 on the way and  17...f5  18.O-O  not exactly producing any real counterplay on the kingside. }
14. dxc6 Qc7 15. Ne3
{ Simple chess from the champ, heading for one of the queen's knights favourite squares in many an opening, c4. }
15... Qxc6 16. Nc4
{ 16.Bc4!  Be6  17.b3  was probably more precise, followed by Qe2 if needed. }
16... Nd7
{ 16...Be6!?  17.Nxe5  Qc8  18.Nd3  O-O  would have left White a clear pawn up, but at least this way the rest of Black's pieces would have been fairly well coordinated. }
17. a5
{ Fixing the black pawn on a6 and also creating a potential outpost for the white knight on b6. }
17... Qe6 18. Qd5
{ Kasparov is happy to remove the queens, but he might also have retained a huge positional advantage with the simple  18.O-O  O-O  19.Rfd1  followed by Ra4 or even just Be3 and Nb6. }
18... Qxd5 19. exd5 Bh6
{ Trying to exchange off one of his problematic bishops, as even after  19...f5  20.O-O  e4  21.fxe4  fxe4  22.Rad1  the bishop wouldn't have been all that happy, all the while as White limbered up to crash through with d5-d6. }
20. Kf2
{ Connecting the rooks and not fearing being left with a cramping pawn on g5. }
20... f6
{ 20...Bxg5  21.hxg5  h4  22.Rhd1  would again have seen White looking to break through with d5-d6, or if  22...Rh5?  23.f4  . }
21. Bxh6 Rxh6 22. Rhd1 Rh8 23. g3
{ An unexpected change of approach, or possibly a classically-orientated decision as Kasparov looks to open up a second line of attack on the kingside. He may also have been uncertain as to how to break through after   23.d6  Bb7  24.dxe7  Kxe7  25.Rd6  Rhc8  26.Rad1  Bc6  , but here  27.b3!?  is quite a useful semi-waiting move, and if  27...Bb5  or   27...Nc5  28.Nb6  Rc7  29.Bc4  28.Ne3  , thereby retaining a large positional advantage thanks to Black's weaknesses across the sixth rank. }
23... Kf7 24. f4 exf4
{ 24...Rd8!?  25.fxe5  Nxe5  might have been a better try, although even here Black would have remained under some pressure after  26.Nb6  Bg4  27.Rd4  . }
25. gxf4 Bb7 26. Rd4
{ A powerful rook lift. Kasparov hasn't forgotten about the weakness on b4 and suddenly Speelman must have wished he'd just left his bishop on c8. }
26... Ba8 27. Ne3 Nc5 28. Rg1
{ In typical fashion, Kasparov plays right across the board. } 28... b3 29. c3
Rbd8 30. Rc4 Nb7
{ Attacking a5, but making it rather easy for White.   30...Rc8  31.Rd1  Rc7  was perhaps the last faint chance. }
31. Rc7 Nxa5 32. f5
{ Even more incisive than  32.Ra1  Nb7  33.Rxa6  Nd6  34.Raa7  . Yes, it's the black king Kasparov is hunting. }
32... g5
{ Desperation, as Black's king position would quickly have cost him after  32...gxf5  33.Nxf5  . }
33. hxg5 fxg5 34. Rxg5 Nb7 35. Bxh5+ Kf8 36. f6
{ A final powerful blow heralds the end, as if  36.f6  exf6  37.Rf7+  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games I"]
[Black "Neubauer, Martin vs. Lehner, Oliver"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5. h4 h5 6. Nh3
{ A perfectly valid alternative to our move order of  6.Nf3  . In both cases the knight is bound for g5, but Neubauer's move order does allow Black the opportunity to exchange it off at the cost of the bishop-pair. }
6... c6 7. Ng5
{ Settling in situ and already preventing ....e5 due to the pressure against f7. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Simple chess and a decent alternative to our main recommendation,  8.a4  - see Line A6.   Having castled White will no longer be ripping open the kingside with any g2-g4 break, but does still have the f-pawn to advance. Moreover, he can exploit the control generated in part by the fine knight on g5 to prevent Black from obtaining too much counterplay. }
8... Nbd7
{ With White's king now on g1, perhaps Black might consider  8...Ng4!?  9.f3  Nh6  .   He isn't going to get slaughtered by 10.g4 here and can even inflict some structural damage, but White should still be far from unhappy about the rather original and unclear position which arises after  10.Be3  f6  11.Nh3  Bxh3  12.gxh3  Kh7  13.Qd2  .   The king should be pretty safe on h2 and it will stilll be possible to attack down the g-file and with the f-pawn.   Instead,  8...b5  9.Be3   9.f4  is somewhat more risky when Black can settle a piece on g4 or even break with  9...d5!?  , aiming to weaken White on the light squares as would be the case after  10.exd5?  b4  11.Na4  cxd5  9...Nbd7  would have transposed to the game while bypassing the option in our next note for White. }
9. Be3
{ Simple development, but  9.f4!?  very much came into the equation here, and if  9...d5  10.e5  Ng4  11.Bxg4  hxg4  12.h5!?  , gambiting a pawn to open lines against the black king. Moreover, the attack already looks quite dangerous with both Qd3 and Ne2-g3 on their way. }
9... b5 10. f3
{ Neubauer elects to maintain control, not allow Black decent counterplay with  10.f4  b4  11.Na4  Nb6  , and if  12.Nxb6  axb6  13.f5!  gxf5  14.exf5  Ra5!  , which would just be pretty unclear, but safe enough for the black king. }
10... Nb6
{ White reacts well to this. He would also have maintained control after  10...b4  11.Na4  Nb6  12.c3  ,   so perhaps Black should have begun with  10...a5!?  and only then ...Nb6 or even ...Ba6. }
11. b3
{ Prophylactically keeping Black out of c4, but there was no real reason to hold back on  11.Qd2  , and if  11...b4?!  12.Nd1  when the knight can re-emerge via f2 and White can also strongly fight back on the queenside with  12...a5  13.a3  . }
11... b4 12. Nb1 Nfd7
{ White takes over after this.   12...Ne8!  13.a3  f6  was the way to obtain counterplay, and if  14.Nh3  Bxh3  15.gxh3  e5  , offering a pawn to strike back on the dark squares and potentially against the weakened white king position. }
13. a3
{ 13.c3  a5  14.a3!  was also good. In both cases White takes control of the queenside and thereby denies Black any real counterplay. }
13... bxa3
{ 13...a5  14.Qd2  would have forced matters and after  14...bxa3  15.Nxa3  might even be best, and if  15...a4  16.b4!  . White keeps lines closed on the queenside, since he wants to roll forwards in the centre and on the kingside, as he should be able to here with some effect after c2-c4 and f3-f4. }
14. Rxa3 e5
{ Unable to get anywhere on the queenside and threatened with a central steamroller, Lehner decides that he might as well finally contest the centre. }
15. d5
{ Not White's only good move, but his strongest in our opinion. Neubauer has correctly realised that the forthcoming structural transformation is in White's favour. }
15... cxd5
{ 15...c5?  16.Nc3  would just be very grim for Black, with Qd2 and Rfa1 next up leaving him under significant pressure on the queenside, not enjoying any counterplay whatsoever there - or elsewhere. }
16. exd5
{ White's simple plan should be fairly obvious: c2-c4, b3-b4 and c4-c5. } 16...
a5
{ Preventing b3-b4 and taking a decent grip on the queenside dark squares, but that is far from being all bad news for White, as we will now see. }
17. c4 Nc5 18. Nc3
{ Taking stock, White is clearly better. Black might have a hold on b4 and c5, but that has come at the cost of a rather large hole on b5. Moreover, it's not exactly hard for White to target a5 and, all the while, Black still lacks counterplay. }
18... f5
{ Activating his pawn majority.   18...f6?!  19.Nge4  Nxe4  20.Nxe4  f5  would also have done so, but here White can maintain full control with  21.Ng5   or even go  21.Nxd6!?  Qxd6  22.c5  , and if  22...Qe7  23.d6  , with a huge advantage in both cases. }
19. Qe1
{ A sneaky move, overprotecting h4 and at the same time beginning to eye the pawn on a5. }
19... Bd7
{ Covering b5 and Black could hardly do anything with his own pawn majority:   19...f4?  20.Bxc5  dxc5  21.Bd3  merely cripples his light squares and still leaves the knight on g5 a real Trojan,  while   19...e4?  20.fxe4  fxe4  can be met by  21.Ncxe4   or even  21.Nb5  , ignoring the bounty to press onwards on the queenside and not open the e-file for any potential tricks for Black. }
20. Nb5
{ A nonchalant choice and it's always enjoyable to make a move your opponent may have thought they had prevented. }
20... Qb8
{ Defending d6.   20...Bxb5  21.cxb5  would cripple White's pawns, but that's the end of the good news for Black, as we can see from  21...e4  or   21...Nbd7  22.Ne6!  - very possible now that Black's light-squared guardian has left the scene -  22...Nxe6  23.dxe6  Nf6  24.b6  when the front b-pawn is most certainly an asset, not a weakness, and a5 is falling  22.fxe4  fxe4  23.Rxf8+  Qxf8  24.Rxa5  Rxa5  25.Qxa5  . Black has lost a pawn and is still completely unable to land even the faintest of blows on the kingside, due to all the squares controlled by White's superbly placed trio of minor pieces. }
21. Rxa5
{ Swapping b3 for a5 to open lines. It will be back to laying siege to d6 next. }
21... Nxb3 22. Rxa8 Nxa8 23. Qb4 Nc5
{ White crashes through after this and  23...Nd4  was a better try, if still excellent for White following  24.Bd3  Bxb5  Black only really has a choice of evils at this juncture:   24...Nxb5?  25.cxb5  Nb6  26.Qa5  undermines the blockade  and even   24...Qb6!?  coming up short due to, most brutally and aesthetically,  25.Bxd4  exd4  26.Qxd6  Bxb5  27.Qe7!  Ba4  28.Re1  ; Black might be a piece for a pawn up, but is quite helpless against the threats of Ne6 and d5-d6, or if  28...Qf6  29.Qa7  , hitting the bishop while also threatening Re6 - a graphic difference between a coordinated and an uncoordinated army  25.cxb5  Nb6  26.Bxd4!  exd4  27.Ne6  . A dream square for the knight, although it isn't on e6 to enjoy the view. Rather Nxg7 Kxg7; Qxd4+ is the threat, or if  27...Be5!?   27...Nxd5?  28.Qb3  Nf6  29.Nxf8+  Kxf8  30.b6  leaves Barry, the b-pawn far too powerful  28.Nxf8  Kxf8  29.Qd2  when it will be White, not Black attacking on the kingside after Qh6+ or just f3-f4 and Re1-e6, with even Bxf5 sacrifices also on the agenda. }
24. Bxc5
{ Giving up the custodian of the dark squares to enjoy connected central passed pawns and, in part due to that fine creature on g5, where even now is Black's counterplay? }
24... dxc5 25. Qxc5 Nb6
{ 25...e4!?  was perhaps worth a punt, although even here it's not so hard for White to maintain full control, as with  26.fxe4  Qg3  27.exf5  Be5  28.Nf3  . }
26. Nc7
{ Fittingly considering the strategy begun back in the opening by White, Black's game is going to collapse on e6 and the light squares in general. }
26... Na4 27. Qd6 Rd8 28. Qxg6 { Seizing the opportunity to finish in style. }
28... Qxc7 29. Qf7+ Kh8 30. Qxh5+ Kg8 31. Qf7+ Kh8 32. Ne6
{ Everything comes with tempo. Black can save his queen, but not the game. }
32... Qa7+ { 32...Qb6+  33.c5!  is also a game-ender. } 33. Kh1 Bh6
{ There wasn't really anything better in view of  33...Rg8?  34.Qh5+  , but now it's going to be mate after all. }
34. Qf6+ Kh7 35. Qxf5+
{ Lehner doesn't wait to be shown  35.Qxf5+  Kh8  36.Qf6+  Kh7  37.Bd3+  .   That would have been quite the triumphant entrance by White's light-squared control which in part set up victory by helping to keep everything tight at the back. }
