1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ Straightforward defence of the extra pawn. } 5... Nbd7 6. Nf3
{ This is fine, but  6.Bb3  Nb6  7.Nf3  is our recommended move order at the start of the chapter. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Nbxd5
{ Black decides to recapture without delay, but now White can free his c-pawn for duty ahead of completing development along good, classical lines. }
8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 c6 11. Bg5
{ As we've already seen and as is often the case, it's well worth flicking in  11.h3!  here to prevent ...Bg4. }
11... Re8
{ Overprotecting e7, but possibly leaving f7 vulnerable. Black would do better with   11...Bg4!  when White can calmly go  12.c3  or even   12.h3!  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  with a small but definite edge in both cases. Note too that here the d-pawn is poisoned:  13...Bxd4?  14.Rad1  Bg7  15.c4  and Black loses a piece. }
12. Qd2
{ Connecting the rooks and facilitating Rad1 as well as a timely Bh6, but again  12.h3  was likely a stronger option. }
12... a5
{ As we've already seen, Black usually relies on this advance for some counterplay. Here this isn't, of course, a handy Na4 resource, so White should simply block in the conventional fashion. }
13. a4 Be6
{ An instructive mistake.   13...f6  14.Bh6   14.Bf4!  Bg4  15.Qd3  would maintain control and an edge  Bg4  15.Re4!?  Bxf3  16.gxf3  had just been very unclear in Shabala-Rakhmangulov, Kremenchug 2011,  and while   13...Bg4  was still on,  14.Ne5  Bf5  15.Bf4  would leave White with an edge, since it's not so easy for Black to liberate his slightly cramped position @@StartBracket@@he doesn't have a great square for his queen being one issue@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Bh6
{ Strong, but so would have been the immediate   14.Rxe6!  fxe6  15.Re1  . This exchange sacrifice on e6 has been known since the heyday of the Soviet chess school, if not before, to generally favour White somewhat. Black's e-pawns are clearly weak, but his problems go beyond that. His king is now in some danger and should the knight ever leave d5, he will clearly be in some trouble on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
14... Bh8 15. Rxe6 { Here we go... } 15... fxe6 16. Ng5
{ The experienced Russian Grandmaster was clearly in a rush, or at least determined to attack, but once again there was absolutely nothing wrong with the calm   16.Re1!  : for example,  16...Qc8  even   16...e5!?  17.Nxe5  e6  18.Bg5  Bf6  19.h4  feels rather dangerous for Black with Ng4 on the way, not to mention c4 and Bc2  17.h4!  Bf6  18.h5!  gxh5  19.Ne5  when it would be a surprise if Black survived on the kingside. Not only might White go Qd3-g3+, but also c4 and Bd1. }
16... e5 { The German amateur does his best to break out. } 17. c4 Nf4 18. d5
{ A rather ungrandmasterly choice, but possibly Karpatchev had underestimated Black's last or missed   18.g3!  Qxd4  19.Qc2  when White should just be winning in view of  19...Nd3  20.c5+  . }
18... Qd7
{ Suddenly Black too has his threats and it's very much game on again. } 19. g3
Nh3+
{ Far too rushed. The calm   19...Bf6!  was indicated when  20.h4!?   20.gxf4  Bxg5  21.fxg5  Qg4+  22.Kh1  Qf3+  23.Kg1  is very likely to end in perpetual check, be it immediately or after  23...Qxb3  24.Qe2  Qh3  25.Qxe5  Qg4+  26.Kf1  Qxc4+  when Black has just enough checks  Bxg5  21.hxg5  Ne6!  22.c5!  cxd5  23.Qxd5  Qxd5  24.Bxd5  Kf7  25.Re1  would have remained very unclear. The engines suggest that White is OK, but you'd certainly be worried about how to get the bishop on h6 back into the game. }
20. Nxh3 Qxh3 21. c5
{ Levering open a key diagonal with near decisive effect. } 21... Rad8
{ 21...cxd5  22.Bxd5+  e6  was a better try, but still excellent for White after  23.Bxb7  Rad8  24.Qc1!  and c6. }
22. d6+ e6 23. Bg5 Rd7 24. Qxa5
{ White can simply harvest the pawn with Black badly tied up and completely devoid of any real counterplay. }
24... Qf5 25. Qd2 e4 26. Be3
{ Maintaining control, as does White's next and already the game is pretty much up for Huemmer. }
26... h5 27. h4 Be5 28. Bc4
{ Heading for f1, but  28.Qe2!  followed by Qf1 if Black invades with his queen or  28...Rf8  29.Kg2  was the way to maintain White's huge advantage @@StartBracket@@a5 and Ra4 will likely follow@@EndBracket@@. }
28... Rf8
{ Missing   28...g5!  when Black suddenly has some counterplay, as if  29.Bxg5!  Bxg3  30.fxg3  Qxc5+  . }
29. Bf1 Qg4
{ Far too routine - and slow. Instead,   29...Rdf7  30.Bg2  g5!  31.hxg5  h4  would again have very much fought on. Possibly Black was simply resigned to his fate against his much higher-rated opponent, but it's always worth giving your best right until the very end of the game, seeking out every resource even when in a grim position. }
30. Bg2 Rf3 31. Ra3 { White has regained control. } 31... Kh7
{ Hopeless, but so would have been   31...Rf5  32.a5  followed by Ra4. } 32.
Bxf3 exf3 33. Bf4 { Now f3 will be lost and with it the game. } 33... Bg7 34.
Qe3 Bxb2 35. Rb3 e5 36. Rxb2
{ White's play may not have been flawless, but Karpatchev now finishes off in typical, ruthless grandmaster vein. }
36... exf4 37. Qxf4 Qe6 38. Qxf3 Rf7 39. Re2 Qd7 40. Qxf7+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games II"]
[Black "Tomczak, Jacek vs. Heberla, Bartlomiej"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. Be2 d5 5. e5 Nh6 6. h4
{ Now that Black cannot block with ...h5, Harry launches himself straight into the fray. }
6... f6 7. h5 g5
{ Closing lines, but   7...fxe5!?  8.dxe5  is the critical test, as we saw in Line B2. }
8. f4 { White is determined to open lines... } 8... g4
{ ...And Black to keep them closed. } 9. Bd3
{ It's well worth a tempo to activate this bishop and facilitate Ne2-g3. The g- and h-files might be closed, but it's not hard to imagine Black's outlier on g4 becoming a target sooner or later. }
9... O-O
{ Of course,   9...Bf5?  fails to  10.Bxf5  Nxf5  11.Qxg4  ,  and   9...Nf5??  10.Qxg4  would be even worse for Black, which means that his knight must remain stuck on h6 for the time being. }
10. Nge2 f5
{ Solving the problem of a loose pawn on g4, but at some cost. Tomczak had clearly seen this move, which possibly should even be denoted as dubious, coming and was clearly happy to allow it. Why? Well, while it will take Black quite some time to bring his king's bishop and knight into play, if indeed he can manage to, White will be able to open lines on the queenside. Don't forget that there's always the c4 break after due preparation. }
11. Na4
{ Freeing the c-pawn.   11.b4!?  followed by a4, Qd2, Nd1-e3 and c4 might have been even stronger. }
11... b6 12. b3 e6 13. Ba3
{ Bringing the bishop to a fine diagonal. Yes, Black will now be able to exchange off his bishop on g7, but from a look at the pawn structure you should be able to spot that it's also Black's good bishop, at least relatively! }
13... Rf7 14. Qd2 Bf8 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. c4
{ Not that long ago, everything seemed closed for White on the queenside, but already Tomczak has got in the key break and while still leading in development. He must have been delighted with how the game was proceeding. }
16... dxc4
{ A big decision, but   16...Bb7  17.cxd5  cxd5  18.Nac3!  would have left Black under some pressure. The threat is Nb5-d6 or if  18...a6?!  19.Na4!  Qd8  20.Qb4  Nd7  21.Rc1  when Black will do well to avoid the rather weakening ...b5 for long.  Likewise,   16...Ba6  17.Nac3  would have left White clearly for choice, and if  17...Nd7?  18.cxd5!  Bxd3  19.dxe6  . }
17. bxc4 Bb7 18. d5
{ 'Boom!' must have thought White, but actually the game is only now extremely unclear. Instead, he should have gone   18.O-O  or even   18.c5!?  b5  19.Nb2  . Black can keep lines closed here after  19...a5  20.a4!  b4  21.Nc4  , but we're far from convinced that this should be a draw. Just look at the hole on d6, the weakness of e6 and White's ability to manoeuvre, be it with Nc1-b3 or Qf2-h4. }
18... cxd5 19. Nd4 Qe7
{ Now White is rewarded for his brave sacrifice. He also would have been after   19...dxc4  20.Bxc4  ,  but   19...Qe8!  would have left matters simply very unclear following  20.cxd5!?   20.Nc3  Nc6  21.Nxc6?  can now be met by  21...dxc4!  Qxa4  21.Bc2  Qa3  22.Nxe6  Qg3+  23.Kf1  when only Black can really be better after  23...Nd7  . }
20. Nc3 { Bringing the knight back into play, and with some effect. } 20... Nc6
{ 20...dxc4  21.Bxc4  Bc8  was pretty grim, but probably a better chance. } 21.
Nxc6 Bxc6 { Unfortunately for Black, now forced. } 22. cxd5 Bxd5
{ Black is also a pawn up, but most likely positionally lost after   22...exd5  23.Rc1  followed by Nb5 or Ne2-d4. White's minor pieces are much the more powerful and his king should be somewhat safer than its airy counterpart on g8. }
23. Nxd5 exd5 24. Rc1 { Simply preparing to invade via c6. } 24... Rff8
{ 24...Qd7  25.Qb4  Rc8  26.Kd2  would also be very bad news for Black, and if  26...Rff8  27.Ba6  . }
25. Rc6 Kg7 26. Qc3 { Claiming the c-file and simply threatening Rc7. } 26...
d4
{ Desperation, as if   26...Nf7  27.Bxf5  or   26...Rad8  27.Ke2  followed by Rc1. This is completely lost for Black, due in no small part to that sidelined knight on the rim: for example,  27...d4  28.Qc4  Rd7  or   28...Ng8  29.h6+!  Kh8  30.Rh5  29.Rc1  Rfd8  30.Qe6!  Qxe6  31.Rxe6  @@StartBracket@@threatening to double on the sixth@@EndBracket@@  31...Rf8  32.Rcc6  Ng8  33.h6+  Kh8  34.Red6  and Black's pawns and position will finally collapse. }
27. Qxd4 Rac8 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 29. Kf2
{ 29.Ke2!  was also good,  but   29.O-O ?  Rd8  wouldn't have been so clear, followed by ...Qh4 or  30.Qe3?  Qa3  . }
29... Rd8 30. Qc3 Qc5+
{ This is clearly hopeless, but so would have been   30...g3+!?  31.Kf3!  and not   31.Kxg3?  Qc5!  .  Black is also lost after   30...Qd7?  31.e6+!  Qd4+  32.Qxd4+  Rxd4  33.e7  Kf7  34.Re1  and even   30...Kf8  31.Kg3  Qd7  32.Be2  , keeping everything safe before finally - and decisively - swinging the rook on h1 into play. }
31. Qxc5 bxc5 32. Ke3 Ng8
{ Letting the kingside fall, but what else to try with Rb1 on its way? } 33.
Bxf5 Ne7 34. h6+
{ 34.h6+  Kg8  35.Be4  followed by f5 would fast become a rout. } *

