[White "Black Lion Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ Now  3...g6  would, of course, be a Pirc, but here we're investigating those independent lines for Black which are usually associated with an early ...e5   The immediate  3...e5  will be seen in Line C1, where we'll also see what happens if Black prepares the push with 3...Nbd7.   Instead,  3...c6  remains flexible and may be followed up with an early ...Qa5, as we'll see in Line C2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Lion Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4
{ Very occasionally Black begins with 2...c6 or 2...Nd7, but after 3. Nc3 play normally transposes to the lines considered in this chapter after a subsequent ...Nf6. There's also }
2... e5
{ which looks a little strange. White can, just as we'll do in our coverage of  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  , displace the black king }
3. dxe5 dxe5 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now  5.Bc4  is a simple route to an edge, partly because  5...Be6?!  , which works well enough with Nc3 and ...Nf6 inserted, can be by  6.Bxe6  fxe6  followed by developing the queen's knight via d2 to c4. There's also the aggressive }
5. f4 { as played by the legendary attacking Swedish Grandmaster Jonny Hector }
5... Nd7
{ 5...Nf6  allows White to consider  6.fxe5  Nxe4  7.Nd2  or simply transpose into our main line and C1 with   6.Nc3  . }
6. Nf3 Bd6
{ Here Hector's  7.Nbd2  Ngf6  8.Bc4?!  exf4!  9.Bxf7  Rf8  10.Bb3  h6  11.O-O  g5  doesn't seem entirely sound, but White doesn't have to gambit the f-pawn }
7. Nc3 c6
{ 7...Ngf6  8.fxe5  Nxe5  9.Bg5  is a direct transposition to our coverage of the solid 6...Nbd7 in Line C1. }
8. f5
{ Seizing some useful space is a good policy, especially when  8.fxe5  Nxe5  makes less sense now that  9.Bg5+  doesn't pin any knight on f6. }
8... Ngf6 9. g4
{ White hopes to see the g-file open or Black pushed back after g5. Black doesn't have to allow either of those, but he remains a little cramped in any case }
9... h6 10. Bd3 Bc5 11. h3
{ Black can try to advance on the queenside, but we'd still prefer to be White with the kingside space. White's simple plan is Ke2 and Be3 @@StartBracket@@ Nd1-f2 may also occur @@EndBracket@@ followed by breaking the g5 break. }
*

