1. e4 d6 2. d4
{ Very occasionally Black begins with 2...c6 or 2...Nd7, but after 3. Nc3 play normally transposes to the lines considered in this chapter after a subsequent ...Nf6. There's also }
2... e5
{ which looks a little strange. White can, just as we'll do in our coverage of  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  , displace the black king }
3. dxe5 dxe5 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now  5.Bc4  is a simple route to an edge, partly because  5...Be6?!  , which works well enough with Nc3 and ...Nf6 inserted, can be by  6.Bxe6  fxe6  followed by developing the queen's knight via d2 to c4. There's also the aggressive }
5. f4 { as played by the legendary attacking Swedish Grandmaster Jonny Hector }
5... Nd7
{ 5...Nf6  allows White to consider  6.fxe5  Nxe4  7.Nd2  or simply transpose into our main line and C1 with   6.Nc3  . }
6. Nf3 Bd6
{ Here Hector's  7.Nbd2  Ngf6  8.Bc4?!  exf4!  9.Bxf7  Rf8  10.Bb3  h6  11.O-O  g5  doesn't seem entirely sound, but White doesn't have to gambit the f-pawn }
7. Nc3 exf4 8. Nb5
{ ensures that Black's pawn on f4 won't live, albeit at the price of a different gambit: }
8... Ngf6 9. Nxd6 cxd6 10. Bxf4 Nxe4
{ Once again, this looks like decent compensation, with the two bishops and safer king. If you'd like to castle queenside,  11.Rg1  --  and  12.O-O-O  makes good sense and we couldn't help noticing that the engines agree that   even  11.Bd3!?  Re8  12.O-O-O  Nf2  13.Bxd6  Nxh1  14.Rxh1  supplies enough compensation - open lines and the superior coordination. There's also the option of going short }
11. Bc4 f6 12. O-O
{ Black is quite solid here and can bring a knight to e5, but his king position remains a problem. White will likely go Bd5, installing the bishop on a fine post, after which Nd4 may increase the pressure, as will Rad1 and c4, aiming to break with c5. }
*

