1. e4 d6 2. d4
{ Very occasionally Black begins with 2...c6 or 2...Nd7, but after 3. Nc3 play normally transposes to the lines considered in this chapter after a subsequent ...Nf6. There's also }
2... e5
{ which looks a little strange. White can, just as we'll do in our coverage of  2...Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  , displace the black king }
3. dxe5 dxe5 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now  5.Bc4  is a simple route to an edge, partly because  5...Be6?!  , which works well enough with Nc3 and ...Nf6 inserted, can be by  6.Bxe6  fxe6  followed by developing the queen's knight via d2 to c4. There's also the aggressive }
5. f4 { as played by the legendary attacking Swedish Grandmaster Jonny Hector }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ may transpose too to Line C1. In any case, White has rapid and easy development, and may castle on either side. Black can hold back on ...Nf6, but in response White doesn't have to develop his queen's knight to c3, i.e. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2
{ the space-gaining  7.f5!?  also makes some sense, followed by Nc4. The critical line appears to run }
7... Nf6 8. fxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. Nc4
{ tearing open the position ahead of preparing to sacrifice a pawn: } 10... Re8
11. Nxe5 Rxe5 12. Bd3 Nxe4 13. O-O
{ This simply must supply decent compensation. Just look at White's bishops, safer king and the open d-file; Bf4 and Rad1 or Rae1 will likely follow. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Lion C1: 3...e5"]
[Black "C1: 3...e5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ A solid response from Black, angling to take play into the Hanham variation of the Philidor after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  . Following  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  Black can simply play  6...O-O  or aim for more with early aggressive plan on the kingside, as covered in Simon's popular course on the Black Lion. }
4. dxe5
{ This might not seem aggressive, but just as in our Pirc coverage, we should not mind an early queen exchange to displace Black's king and create a large central target.  Such an approach may also frustrate Black Lion players and psychological factors are also at play, as we'll soon see. If you really don't like the idea of such an exchange, while we can't especially recommend  4.f4  exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Bb5  for White, but Black is fine after  6...Be7  ,   there is  4.Nf3  Nbd7  and then, as well as  5.Bc4  , Shirov's  5.g4!?  . }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now White usually goes  6.Bg5  or  6.Bc4  when a protracted manoeuvring struggle, very slightly in White's favour, usually ensures. However, just because White has traded queens at any early stage doesn't mean that he can't continue aggressively. }
6. f4
{ This direct and fairly rare central assault may come as a surprise to an opponent looking forward to gradually untangling their pieces. Objectively, Black should be OK after it, but, especially if caught out, it's easy for him to lose his way.   Moreover, Anish Giri has played this way as White and there surely can't be anything wrong with making White's main and most aggressive pawn break in the position as quickly as possible. }
6... Bb4
{ By quite some margin Black's most popular response, countering against e4, and it was also recommended by Erik Zude and Jörg Hickl in their 'Play 1...d6 Against Everything' course, but White should welcome the resulting unbalanced middlegame. }
7. Bd3
{ Sensibly overprotecting e4.  7.fxe5?!  Nxe4  is definitely not encouraged .   And Black should now be OK after  7.Bd2  exf4!  8.O-O-O  Nbd7  . }
7... Nbd7
{ This natural development and an exchange on f4 have been Black's most popular continuations, but there doesn't yet appear to be a clear consensus as to how he should handle this relatively uncharted position. }
8. Nf3
{ Increasing the central pressure and even allowing White to go short should he so desire. }
8... Re8 9. fxe5
{ Simple chess.  9.O-O !?  also deserves attention, asking Black how he intends to untangle and there doesn't seem to be any reason for White to fear  9...Bc5+  10.Kh1  Ng4  11.h3  Nf2+  12.Kh2  , with definite chances for an edge after an exchange on d3. }
9... Ng4
{ This once again underestimates a certain check.   Black should prefer to immediately recapture:  9...Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Rxe5  11.Bf4  . This position should look familiar by now. We're back in the realm of Turner-Fernandez where White's position was certainly the easier to play. }
10. Bg5+ Be7 11. Bf4
{ A second move with the dark-squared bishop, but Black has also made two with his and is about to have to move it again, with h3 threatened. }
11... Bb4 12. Rf1
{ Simple chess and easier to handle than the  12.O-O!?  Bc5+  13.Kh1  Nf2+  14.Rxf2  Bxf2  of Jamilov-Emeljanov, Togliatti 2014, when  15.Bc4  would have left White with promising play for the exchange. }
12... Bxc3+
{ Black might as well damage White's structure ahead of recapturing on e5 and having to grovel. }
13. bxc3 Ngxe5 14. Nxe5
{ Further simple chess, preparing to make good use of the rook being on f1, although we dare say you could also make a decent case for  14.O-O-O  and  14.Be2  when White should still be clearly better. }
14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. Rxf7
{ White has broken through and Black has only one real way of defending g7.   16...Re7  17.Rf4  Keeping pieces on. White is a clear pawn to the good and while his structure isn't perfect, he must have decent winning chances. For a start, Kd2-e3 will leave his king better placed than its counterpart and c4 will block the black bishop's path from e6, after which even  e5  may become possible.  White may also aim to exert some pressure down the b-file with Rb1 and he doesn't have to double on the f-file, but might look to activate with a timely Rb5. }
*

