{ Sensibly overprotecting e4.  7.fxe5?!  Nxe4  is definitely not encouraged .   And Black should now be OK after  7.Bd2  exf4!  8.O-O-O  Nbd7  . }
7... Nbd7
{ This natural development and an exchange on f4 have been Black's most popular continuations, but there doesn't yet appear to be a clear consensus as to how he should handle this relatively uncharted position. }
8. Nf3
{ Increasing the central pressure and even allowing White to go short should he so desire. }
8... c6
{ is the other main move to have been tried in practice, but is flawed: } 9.
fxe5 Ng4 10. Bg5+
{ This is the issue for Black, not  10.Bf4  Re8  when he does regain his pawn. }
10... Be7 11. Bf4
{ 11...f6!?  What else to try with  h3  threatened?   12.exf6  Bxf6  13.h3  Nge5  14.O-O-O  White had all his usual pressure and was simply a pawn to the good in Neverov-Baljiev, Gyor 1997. Rhf1 and Nd4 was set to follow or even h4 and Ng5. }
