[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Lion C1: 3...e5"]
[Black "C1: 3...e5  #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ A solid response from Black, angling to take play into the Hanham variation of the Philidor after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  . Following  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  Black can simply play  6...O-O  or aim for more with early aggressive plan on the kingside, as covered in Simon's popular course on the Black Lion. }
4. dxe5
{ This might not seem aggressive, but just as in our Pirc coverage, we should not mind an early queen exchange to displace Black's king and create a large central target.  Such an approach may also frustrate Black Lion players and psychological factors are also at play, as we'll soon see. If you really don't like the idea of such an exchange, while we can't especially recommend  4.f4  exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Bb5  for White, but Black is fine after  6...Be7  ,   there is  4.Nf3  Nbd7  and then, as well as  5.Bc4  , Shirov's  5.g4!?  . }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now White usually goes  6.Bg5  or  6.Bc4  when a protracted manoeuvring struggle, very slightly in White's favour, usually ensures. However, just because White has traded queens at any early stage doesn't mean that he can't continue aggressively. }
6. f4
{ This direct and fairly rare central assault may come as a surprise to an opponent looking forward to gradually untangling their pieces. Objectively, Black should be OK after it, but, especially if caught out, it's easy for him to lose his way.   Moreover, Anish Giri has played this way as White and there surely can't be anything wrong with making White's main and most aggressive pawn break in the position as quickly as possible. }
6... Bb4
{ By quite some margin Black's most popular response, countering against e4, and it was also recommended by Erik Zude and Jörg Hickl in their 'Play 1...d6 Against Everything' course, but White should welcome the resulting unbalanced middlegame. }
7. Bd3
{ Sensibly overprotecting e4.  7.fxe5?!  Nxe4  is definitely not encouraged .   And Black should now be OK after  7.Bd2  exf4!  8.O-O-O  Nbd7  . }
7... Re8
{ isn't dissimilar to the  7...Nc6  8.Nf3  Re8  line. Indeed, White might now go  9.fxe5  Nxe4  10.Bxe4  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Nxe5  when he has the startling  12.Bg5+!  . That certainly leaves White with the safer king, but is objectively just rather unclear, so here you may also wish to consider calm development, shoring up c3 and e4: }
8. Ne2
{ 8.Nf3  exf4  works out OK for Black. White is now set to capture on e5 and go Bf4 and O-O-O, and also sets a small trap }
8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Bg4 10. a3
{ Kicking the bishop away. Instead,  10.O-O-O!?  Bxc3  11.Nxc3  Bxd1  12.Rxd1  might tempt aggressive types, but it seems that White has no more than some compensation after  12...Nbd7  . }
10... Ba5 11. b4 Bb6 12. O-O-O
{ The immediate threat is e5 followed by Nd5 and h3 is also likely to prove a handy resource. Note too that White's king is actually quite safe: he will always at least be able to meet ...a5 with b5. Let's see how things might pan out:  12...Nbd7  13.Rhf1!   Perhaps remarkably, there's nothing amazing for White after  13.e5?  Nxe5!  , but this logical improvement of the rook very much puts the break back on the agenda.  13...Kc8  14.h3  Bxe2   If  14...Be6?  15.e5  either picks off h7 after the knight retreats or cleans Black up with  15...Nd5?  16.Nxd5  Bxd5  17.c4!  Bxg2  18.Bf5!  when Black is completely undone down the d-file, as well as by the threat of c5.  15.Bxe2  White will next go Bc4 and retains the initiative, as well as the more pleasant position. Note too that once again  e4  is pretty much taboo:  15...a5  16.b5  Nxe4?   allowing White a very pleasant choice between  17.Bg4  ,  17.Nd5!?  , which may well be strongest of the lot, and the simple  17.Nxe4  Rxe4  18.Bg4  Rxf4!   18...Re7?  fails to a standard tactic:  19.Rxd7!  Rxd7  20.Rd1  19.Rxf4  Be3+  20.Kb1  Bxf4  21.Rxd7  Without the inclusion of ...a5 and b5 Black would be completely lost here, but as is he can limp on into an endgame  21...Kb8  22.Rxf7  Bd6  23.Rxg7  . Now b6 is a seriously strong positional threat, so Black must give up h7, leaving White with connected passed pawns and some winning chances, despite the opposite-coloured bishops and weakness of a3. }
