10... Nh5 11. Bg5+ Be7 12. Be3 Bc5
{ saw Black trying not to lose time while freeing his position with an exchange in Karasev-Zemerov, St. Petersburg 2002. White might simply go  13.Bd2  followed by Rhe1, e5 and Ne4, but he can also very much take up the challenge: }
13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Bc4+
{ Bringing the king to the e-file will walk into a rather awkward Nd5@@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@, but even hiding on the queenside leaves Black under pressure: }
