{ Already h3 is threatened and White would love to gain both the bishop-pair and a dynamic central pawn duo on e4 and f3. Black can avoid such a fate, but not equalize }
10... Ke7 11. h3 Be6 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bf4 Nfd7
{ Black might have a firm grip on e5, but he lacks counterplay and the two bishops. Moreover, White can combine central play with a kingside advance and is already doing pretty well: }
14. Nd5+ Bxd5 15. exd5 f6 { was Varavin-Mishuchkov, Smolensk 1991, where } 16.
h4
{ would have been strong, intending not just g4, but Rh3-c3 and even g3 and Bh3. }
