[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ A solid response from Black, angling to take play into the Hanham variation of the Philidor after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  . Following  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  Black can simply play  6...O-O  or aim for more with early aggressive plan on the kingside, as covered in Simon's popular course on the Black Lion. }
4. dxe5
{ This might not seem aggressive, but just as in our Pirc coverage, we should not mind an early queen exchange to displace Black's king and create a large central target.  Such an approach may also frustrate Black Lion players and psychological factors are also at play, as we'll soon see. If you really don't like the idea of such an exchange, while we can't especially recommend  4.f4  exd4  5.Qxd4  Nc6  6.Bb5  for White, but Black is fine after  6...Be7  ,   there is  4.Nf3  Nbd7  and then, as well as  5.Bc4  , Shirov's  5.g4!?  . }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now White usually goes  6.Bg5  or  6.Bc4  when a protracted manoeuvring struggle, very slightly in White's favour, usually ensures. However, just because White has traded queens at any early stage doesn't mean that he can't continue aggressively. }
6. f4
{ This direct and fairly rare central assault may come as a surprise to an opponent looking forward to gradually untangling their pieces. Objectively, Black should be OK after it, but, especially if caught out, it's easy for him to lose his way.   Moreover, Anish Giri has played this way as White and there surely can't be anything wrong with making White's main and most aggressive pawn break in the position as quickly as possible. }
6... Nbd7
{ was Yannick Pelletier's choice and is Black's most solid option. Once again, the key battleground is likely to be the e5 point: }
7. fxe5
{ It's also possible to begin with  7.Nf3  Bd6  when  8.fxe5  transposes.   Here  8.Ng5  Rf8  9.Bc4  Ke7  seems to be fine for Black, but if you like to maintain tension you may wish to consider instead 8. g3!?, while 8. f5!? would be an approach for fans of space to explore. }
7... Nxe5
{ Just a reminder that we will also reach this position via a 3...Nbd7 move order. }
8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bg5
{ White is quick to mobilize the troops and already threatens Nd5, while making Black realize that he is likely going to have to accept doubled f-pawns should there be an exchange on f6.   Black must also decide what he wants to do with his king: place it on c7, e7 or even e8? He usually begins by keeping White out of d5 }
9... c6 10. O-O-O Kc7 11. Be2
{ Modest but powerful development from White, described by Simon as 'a crafty approach' in his Black Lion course. White tees up Rxd6 and also frees f1 for the king's rook, while avoiding  11.Bf4?  Nd3+!  which picks off an important bishop. That may explain why the four grandmasters who have reached this position have sought to shut down the f-file as Black here, an exchange which also reduces the power of an exchange sacrifice on d6   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppk2ppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bg4?  loses material:  12.Rxd6!  Kxd6  13.Nxe5  followed by taking on f6 and g4 or  13...Bxe2  14.Nxf7+  Ke6  15.Nxh8  followed by something active, such as, after the bishop retreats, e5 and Ne4.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppk2ppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nxf3!?  12.gxf3  Nh5  Now White might just go  13.Bc4  but again there's also a very tempting sacrifice  13.Rxd6!  Kxd6  14.Rd1+  Put that in your pipe and smoke it! Once again, the monster of a dark-squared bishop and Black's rather shaky position leave White with dangerous compensation as we'll see in Spassky-Eliet, French League 2002.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppk2ppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nfg4?  is also rather unwise due to the thematic sacrificial blow  12.Rxd6!  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Kc7  14.Bf4  The pin is just a winner:  14...f6  15.h3  g5  16.Bg3  Ne3  avoids losing a knight, but not the game after  17.Nxe5  Nxd1  18.Bxd1  and the knight is taboo due to the loose rook on h8 and there just isn't a good square for the black king, since it will quickly be hunted down after heading forward  18...Kb6   18...Re8  19.Ng4+  Kd8  20.Nxf6  is also far too strong an initiative for White, not to mention three active pieces and a pawn for the two rooks.  19.Na4+  Ka5  20.Be1+!  aiming to mate with 21.c4 or crash through, as with  20...Ka6  21.Be2+  b5  22.Nxc6  again with far too strong an initiative and at no material cost.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppk2ppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nfd7?!   can be met by  12.Nd4  and even  12.Rxd6!?  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Kc7  14.Be7  White's dark-squared bishop is a monster, he has at least enough compensation, and it's far from easy for Black to unravel. Hommeles-Eisenbeiser, Austrian League 2010, continued:  14...Nxf3  15.Bd6+  Kb6??   15...Kd8  16.gxf3  Re8  was indicated, although even here White retains the initiative and decent compensation after  17.Bc4  f6  18.f4  .  16.Na4+  Ka5  when the right move order was  17.Bc7+!  b6   Note:  17...Kxa4  18.Rd3!  is mate in four after  18...Kb4  19.Ra3!  Kc5  20.c3  and if  20...a5  21.Rxa5+!  Rxa5  22.b4#  18.gxf3  White's threats include Nc3 and Rd4, as well as the lovely Rxd7, and if ...Bxd7; Nc5! followed by a3 and b4#. There's just no defense, as shown by  18...Kxa4  19.Rd4+  Ka5  20.b3  Nc5  21.a3  Be6  22.Ra4+!  Nxa4  23.b4#  Beautiful stuff.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/ppk2pp1/2pb1n1p/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  11...h6!   isn't the most obvious move, but is probably best. White comes up short after  12.Rxd6?  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Ke7  or here  13.Bf4  Nfd7  , and was, unsurprisingly, Simon's recommendation in his Black Lion course. It's still had only the one practical outing, though, so clearly isn't an intuitive choice or even experienced Lion practitioners forget what to do here.  As Simon showed, after the  12.Bxf6?!  gxf6  13.Nd4  of Yeo-Granat, 4NCL 2005,  13...Bd7  followed by ...Rhg8 leaves Black with promising play. As such, White should retain his bishop:   12.Be3!   The vicious threat is  12...--  13.Rxd6!  Kxd6  14.Rd1+  Ke6  15.Bh4  , which explains why Black may want to connect his rooks to have  15...Rhd8  at the end of that sequence - and clearly  12...Be6?  won't do:   12...Bg4!   12...Nfg4?!  13.Rxd6!  Kxd6  14.Rd1+  Ke6  15.Bc5  carries out the threat. Here Black can create a square for his king, but not equalise:  15...f6!  16.h3!  and, of course, Black can't here take on f3 as it would allow mate in two.   12...Neg4!?  13.Rxd6  is very dangerous for Black if he accepts the rook, but he does have a prudent alternative:  13...Nxe3!  14.Rd2  White threatens to cause problems for the knight with Bd3 and should be happy to swap g2 for g7:  14...Nxg2  15.Rg1  Nf4  16.Rxg7  when Nd4 or Ne5 should maintain a small initiative.  13.h3   Here  13.Rxd6  Kxd6  14.Rd1+  Ke6  15.Bc5  can be met by  15...Ne8!  , as well as  15...Rhd8  , so instead White puts the question to the bishop and hints at expansion with a timely g4. As such, Black would probably try to take some dark squares:    13...Bxf3  14.gxf3  Ng6  Wisely getting out of the way of the f-pawn.  15.Kb1  White tucks the king away, enabling him to meet ...Bf4 with Bf2, retaining the bishop-pair. Black should be OK here, but at least White has the two bishops, as well as ideas of Bc4, Rhg1  (to tie down the knight on g6)  , and Bd3 followed by Ne2, fighting to take control of f4 and ideally even get in f3-f4.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/pp2kppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Be6??  12.Rxd6  Nxf3     or  12...Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Ke7  14.Nxe5  when the two active minor pieces will easily outclass Black's extra rook.  13.Rxe6+!  Kxe6  14.gxf3  The dust has settled to leave White's bishops dominant and Black unsurprisingly didn't last much longer in Moskalenko-Amran, Metz 1991:  14...b5  15.f4!  Rae8?  16.e5  1-0 and Black gave up in view of the potential check on g4.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/pp2kppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Re8?  12.Rxd6!  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  reveals Black's problem: to avoid losing material on the dark squares he must go  13...Ke6  14.Bh4!  The threat is the forcing Nxe5 which is far from easy to meet:  14...Nxf3  15.gxf3  b5  prevents Bc4+, but fails to  16.Bxb5!  cxb5  17.Nxb5  followed by Nc7+ and e5 when White will emerge somewhat in front.   @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/pp2kppp/2pb1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1B1PP/2KR3R b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bc7!?  is also sensible, as proposed by Jensen and van Rekom when White should probably centralise:  12.Nd4  h6  13.Be3   The plan is h3 followed by Rhf1, g4 and probably Nf5, and a raid into g4 need not be feared:  13...Neg4  14.Nf5+  disrupts, not least in the event of  14...Bxf5?  15.Bc5+!  Ke8  16.exf5  followed by Rhe1. }
