7... Nxe5
{ Just a reminder that we will also reach this position via a 3...Nbd7 move order. }
8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bg5
{ White is quick to mobilize the troops and already threatens Nd5, while making Black realize that he is likely going to have to accept doubled f-pawns should there be an exchange on f6.   Black must also decide what he wants to do with his king: place it on c7, e7 or even e8? He usually begins by keeping White out of d5 }
9... Ke8 10. O-O-O Be6
{ was very solid, but didn't do a huge amount for Black's rooks in Miladinovic-Lazic, Zeralda 2014. The Serbian GM was content to inflict some structural damage with  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Nb5  , but might have retained the tension with   @@StartFEN@@r1bkr3/ppp2ppp/3b1n2/4n1B1/4P3/2N2N2/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R b - - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10...h6?  saw White exchange on f6 in Robin-Tomb, Internet  (blitz)  2017, but he should have asked himself: do I have anything better?   There is  11.Bh4  and especially  11.Nxe5!  Rxe5   or  11...hxg5  12.Nxf7+  Ke7  13.Nxd6  cxd6  14.Bb5+  with an extra pawn and huge advantage, not least with Rhe1 and e5 on their way.  12.Bf4  when Black must give up the exchange in view of  12...Re6?  13.e5 }
11. Nd4
{ retaining the tension and intending to complete development with Be2 and Rhf1, while Nf5 might well be a timely blow to land. }
