1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 { Another common route for Black is } 3... Nbd7
{ once again intending 4. Nf3 e5 and a Philidor. White should meet this move order in aggressive and strong fashion: }
4. f4 { With e4-e5 imminent, only one response makes any sense: } 4... e5
{ Now the main line runs  5.Nf3  exd4  6.Qxd4  c6  7.Be3  which should favour White, but can become quite messy. In that line 7. Bd2 might be more pragmatic and we should also draw creative souls attention to the little-explored continuation:   5.Be3!?  c6  6.Qf3  on which we spent an enjoyable hour or so. However, there's no need for White to develop here when he can proceed full steam ahead: }
5. dxe5 dxe5 6. fxe5
{ Black is pretty much forced to recapture and allow an early queen exchange: }
6... Nxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ We'll see below via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.f4  Nbd7  7.fxe5  Nxe5  how to go about exploiting the black king's position. }
