[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Lion C2: 3...c6"]
[Black "C2: 3...c6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... Qa5 { The main line and by a large margin Black's usual choice. } 5. Bd2
{ Simple chess, breaking the pin and angling to sacrifice the b-pawn if Black now drops his queen back to b6.   When this line used to be popular, Richard did quite well with  5.e5  Ne4  6.Qf3  and  5.Bd3  e5  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be3  is also quite a promising set-up for White. Nowadays we're happy to keep matters as simple as possible as White, while remaining aggressive, and it shouldn't be too hard to appreciate why this variation is no longer too popular for Black. }
5... e5 { Black probably should react in the centre so. } 6. dxe5
{ Again, far from forced  6.fxe5  dxe5  7.Nd5  is one intriguing alternative, but promising enough, as well as our standard method: meet ...e5 by ripping open the centre. }
6... dxe5 7. fxe5
{ We must admit that a lack of titled players have plumped for this path as White @@StartBracket@@too many decent alternatives and perhaps too crude looking@@EndBracket@@, but the engines agree with our hunch that White should be doing well. }
7... Ng4 { Invariably played. } 8. Qf3
{ A perhaps unexpected deployment @@StartBracket@@it went unnoticed in Cyrus Ladkawala's '1...d6: Move by Move'@@EndBracket@@, and most certainly not a typo, even though ...Nxe5 will now come with tempo. White facilitates queenside castling and also threatens Nb5.   8.Nb5??  badly fails to cut the mustard in view of  8...Qb6  .   We did spend some time on the more straightforward  8.Nf3  , intending  8...Nxe5  9.Nb5!  ,   but  8...Bc5!  9.Bc4!?  Nf2  10.Qe2  Nxh1  11.O-O-O  doesn't appear to lead to anything clear, if definitely offering White enough compensation. }
8... Nxe5
{ With tempo, but White is quite happy to slide his queen over to a fine post on g3. }
9. Qg3
{ This is why the queen was happy to come out to f3. White now threatens Nb5 and Nd5, and it's far from easy to find a great line for Black. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nf3
{ Simple development as White once again enjoys much the easier development. }
10... Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 Qh5 12. O-O-O
{ And why not? Black is scarcely about to start an attack on the queenside.   12...Qg6  Via a rather tortuous queen manoeuvre, Black had managed to overprotect g6 in Van der Lende-J.Farrand, Amsterdam 2012, but that was the end of the good news for the strong English amateur and legal expert.  Now you might well want to go  13.Qf2  Bc5  14.Be3  or even  13.Qe1!?  followed by h4, with a large advantage in both cases, and the game also made a good case for simple chess:   13.f4!?  Qxg3  14.hxg3    Thanks to his large lead in development, pressure down the h-file and mobile central pawns  (it would be ideal to get in e5 then f5)  , White enjoyed a very pleasant, clear advantage. }
*

