5... e5 { Black probably should react in the centre so. } 6. dxe5
{ Again, far from forced  6.fxe5  dxe5  7.Nd5  is one intriguing alternative, but promising enough, as well as our standard method: meet ...e5 by ripping open the centre. }
6... dxe5 7. fxe5
{ We must admit that a lack of titled players have plumped for this path as White @@StartBracket@@too many decent alternatives and perhaps too crude looking@@EndBracket@@, but the engines agree with our hunch that White should be doing well. }
7... Ng4 { Invariably played. } 8. Qf3
{ A perhaps unexpected deployment @@StartBracket@@it went unnoticed in Cyrus Ladkawala's '1...d6: Move by Move'@@EndBracket@@, and most certainly not a typo, even though ...Nxe5 will now come with tempo. White facilitates queenside castling and also threatens Nb5.   8.Nb5??  badly fails to cut the mustard in view of  8...Qb6  .   We did spend some time on the more straightforward  8.Nf3  , intending  8...Nxe5  9.Nb5!  ,   but  8...Bc5!  9.Bc4!?  Nf2  10.Qe2  Nxh1  11.O-O-O  doesn't appear to lead to anything clear, if definitely offering White enough compensation. }
8... Na6
{ is calm and also suggested by the engines as Black's best defense. One point is  9.Qg3  Bc5  , so White might keep things simple and force the issue, even at the cost of a tempo: }
9. h3 { 9.Qf4!?  can also be explored. } 9... Nxe5 10. Qg3
{ Clearly there's no longer ...Nbd7 to shore up e5 and White threatens Nd5/Nb5, as well as to continue development with Nf3 and O-O-O. As such, Black can weaken with ...f6 or retreat: }
10... Ng6 11. Nf3
{ It feels like White should have a pleasant initiative here. There are ideas of all of Bc4, Ng5, e5 and h4 and all the while White is hoping to lure Black forwards: }
11... Nb4 12. O-O-O
{ Now Bc4 or a3 will be next up, unless Black continues down the path of greed:   12...Nxa2+  13.Kb1  Nxc3+  14.Bxc3  Talk about a serious lead in development for the price of just one pawn! Not only is the queen attacked, but White is all set to assault f7. Black's only defence is  14...Bb4  when White can go  15.Bxg7  Be6  16.b3  or simply  15.Bxb4  Qxb4  16.Rd4  Qe7  17.Bc4  with an ongoing initiative for the pawn, as well as much the safer king for White. One idea is e5 to grab more space, another simply Rhd1, and there's also h4 which should ask quite an awkward question of Black. }
