1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... Qa5 { The main line and by a large margin Black's usual choice. } 5. Bd2
{ Simple chess, breaking the pin and angling to sacrifice the b-pawn if Black now drops his queen back to b6.   When this line used to be popular, Richard did quite well with  5.e5  Ne4  6.Qf3  and  5.Bd3  e5  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Be3  is also quite a promising set-up for White. Nowadays we're happy to keep matters as simple as possible as White, while remaining aggressive, and it shouldn't be too hard to appreciate why this variation is no longer too popular for Black. }
5... Qb6
{ does attack two pawns, but White can do much better than 6.Bc1 here. It's tempting to dangle the b-pawn before Black with 6. Nf3, but White can also plough straight ahead: }
6. e5 Nd5
{ Unlike after 4...Qb6,  7.Nxd5  cxd5  8.Bd3?  is no good for White in view of  8...Qxd4  , but it's not so hard to improve }
7. Nf3 Bg4 8. exd6
{ Simple chess.  8.Ne4  is also very promising, as is Lawrence Trent's  8.Na4!?  . }
8... Nxc3 9. Bxc3 e6
{ Thematic for this whole variation, as well as an attempt to avoid an unpleasant check on the e-file. }
10. h3 Bxf3
{ 10...Bf5?  11.Qe2  followed by g4 and f5 is even worse for Black. } 11. Qxf3
Bxd6 12. f5
{ This simple thrust already left Black in serious trouble in Liberzon-Hodgson, Palma de Mallorca 1989. White's bishop on c3 holds everything together and a timely d5 may unleash its power, but he is mainly doing well due to his light-square pressure. Clearly Black doesn't want to take on a major weakness on e6, but the alternative is little better   12...exf5  13.O-O-O   13.Qxf5  Bg3+  isn't quite as good.  13...O-O  14.Qxf5   White enjoys a dream early middlegame. Route one attack with h4 and Bd3 may well happen and there's also a certain threat of Ba5, not to mention possibilities of opening up the not-so-sleepy bishop on c3 with d5, and even  14...Bb4!  15.Bxb4   White might well also switch to targeting f7 with  15.Bc4  .  15...Qxb4  16.h4  Na6  17.h5  looks very promising followed only now by Bd3. }
