[Black "C2: 3...c6  #21"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... g6
{ transposes to a sideline of the Austrian Attack. Now you may well be quite happy with White's set-up after  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Bd3  O-O  7.O-O  when Black is a little low on counterplay and White can consider ideas of both e5 and Qe1-h4. It's also possible to seize the central space on offer without delay }
5. e5 Nd5 6. Nxd5
{ Not forced, but it makes sense to change the structure ahead of denying Black's light-squared bishop an easy post on f5. }
6... cxd5 7. Bd3
{ Once again, this feels like a pretty pleasant edge for White thanks to his extra space and easier development: }
7... Nc6 8. c3
{ is an important point, shoring up d4 while preventing ...Nb4. Play tends to run: }
8... Bg7 9. Nf3 dxe5 10. fxe5
{ Black will look to ...f6 for counterplay @@StartBracket@@if he sits and waits he may simply get mated after O-O, Qe1, Qh4, Bh6 and Ng5@@EndBracket@@, but that is by no means a panacea for him: }
10... Bg4 11. O-O O-O
{ was preferred by a strong Russian IM in Dittmar-Kuporosov, Seefeld 1998, but after }
12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3
{ White should be very happy. Two perhaps non-standard ideas are worth noting: }
13... f6
{ 13...a6  14.h4!?  is the other and if  14...h5?  15.g4!  hxg4  16.Qxg4  when White's attack after h5 already appears to be a decisive one. }
14. e6
{ This pawn is remarkably hard for Black to round up and will most certainly act as a fish bone in his king's throat.   White has Re1 when needed and shouldn't rush to develop his remaining bishop @@StartBracket@@unless Bf4 comes with tempo against a queen on d6@@EndBracket@@, when he can instead quickly up the ante to exploit the bridgehead on e6 with h4-h5, making fine use of Harry once again. }
