1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... g6
{ transposes to a sideline of the Austrian Attack. Now you may well be quite happy with White's set-up after  5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Bd3  O-O  7.O-O  when Black is a little low on counterplay and White can consider ideas of both e5 and Qe1-h4. It's also possible to seize the central space on offer without delay }
5. e5 dxe5
{ 5...Nh5!?  6.Nf3  Ng7  Here though White has at least  7.Be3  ready to meet ...Nf5 with Bf2. Bd3 and O-O will follow, after which, and assuming Black has closed the position with ...d5 and ...h5, White may look to the c4 and b4 breaks for some pressure and to exploit his superior development. }
6. fxe5
{ retains the queens and here White doesn't need to rush into exchanges, but should be happy to rely on his strong centre, a blunted black bishop on g7 and that any exchange of knights on c3 doesn't overly help Black with his tricky task of creating some counterplay: }
6... Nd5 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bc4
{ The most aggressive post for the bishop, reminding Black that f7 is a little tender and also making it that bit harder for any ...f6 break to be successful: }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ This feels like a very pleasant edge for White. He may even go route one with Qe1-h4, Ne4 is also likely to be a decent manoeuvre with Black a little blocked up and there's no need to fear a pin:   9...Bg4  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Clearly Black can't now move his knight, leaving White all set to increase the pressure with  11...e6  12.Qg4!  This usefully overprotects d4 and also inhibits ...f6; Bg5 and Rad1 may follow. }
