{ pressures  d4  and  b2  while hoping for  5.Nf3  Bg4  , but White can again set up a strong central pawn wedge }
5. e5 Nd5 6. Nxd5 cxd5 7. Bd3
{ Following our standard method in such positions, we first disrupt Black's structure then prevent ...Bf5. White will shore up d4 with c3 and then look to swing his queen out to f3, pressuring d5, or to e2, applying pressure down the e-file and aiming to force a favourable ...dxe5; fxe5 f-file opening exchange: }
7... g6 8. c3
{ Now Black must either suffer after Qf3 and Ne2 or allow the further dislocation of his pawn structure: }
8... Bf5 9. Bxf5 gxf5 10. Qh5
{ The most aggressive square for the queen, as well as one which eyes Black's light-squared weaknesses. White simply wants to target f7, as he did in Wells-Rashkovsky, London 1990:  10...e6  11.Nf3  Nc6?   11...Be7  12.O-O  Nd7  is a better defence, dissuading Ng5 and keeping d6 covered with the queen, but  13.Bd2!   still looks very pleasant for White. He hopes to swap b2 for b7, a queenside pawn advance can now occur  (perhaps even Kh1, b3 and c4)  (, and all the while Black's king position remains a chronic cause for concern.)  12.Ng5  Nd8  13.g4!   This ripped open lines and left the Russian Grandmaster facing early ruin with the pressure so quick to mount against f7.   13...fxg4?  14.f5!  exf5   14...Ke7  when White can calmly castle or even go  15.Nxf7!  Nxf7  16.fxe6  and wins, in view of  16...Kxe6  17.O-O  Nd8  18.Qe8+  Be7  19.Rf6#  15.e6  Boom! Either f7 will collapse immediately and with it Black's whole position or it will very shortly:  15...Qc7  16.O-O  when Rxf5 will be absolutely murderous.   13...Be7  14.gxf5  exf5  was preferred in the game where  15.Nxf7!  Nxf7  16.e6  Rf8  17.Rg1  O-O-O  18.exf7  was still a complete disaster for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Lion C2: 3...c6"]
[Black "C2: 3...c6  #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... Qb6
{ pressures  d4  and  b2  while hoping for  5.Nf3  Bg4  , but White can again set up a strong central pawn wedge }
5. e5 Nd5 6. Nxd5 cxd5 7. Bd3
{ Following our standard method in such positions, we first disrupt Black's structure then prevent ...Bf5. White will shore up d4 with c3 and then look to swing his queen out to f3, pressuring d5, or to e2, applying pressure down the e-file and aiming to force a favourable ...dxe5; fxe5 f-file opening exchange: }
7... g6 8. c3
{ Now Black must either suffer after Qf3 and Ne2 or allow the further dislocation of his pawn structure: }
8... Bg7 9. Qf3 Be6 10. Ne2 Nd7 11. Qg3
{ avoided blundering the e-pawn by castling and instead threatened f5 in Kaidanov-Zaichik, Connecticut 2003. There's no good way for Black to deal with the threat, with White also able to consider expanding with a4-a5, whereas Black finds himself rather cramped and low on counterplay. }
