1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6
{ This has gone by a number of names over the years, but is most commonly known as the Czech Pirc. Black's aim is ...e5, but he may first bring out his queen to cause some disruption or pin with ...Bg4.   This line used to be fairly popular and has been used over the years by some pretty strong players, but is nowadays quite rare in part because Black has struggled to counter White's classical yet aggressive set-up we'll be covering. }
4. f4
{ Austrian Attack style and already Black has to think about being hit by e4-e5. }
4... Qb6
{ pressures  d4  and  b2  while hoping for  5.Nf3  Bg4  , but White can again set up a strong central pawn wedge }
5. e5 Nd5 6. Nxd5 cxd5 7. Bd3
{ Following our standard method in such positions, we first disrupt Black's structure then prevent ...Bf5. White will shore up d4 with c3 and then look to swing his queen out to f3, pressuring d5, or to e2, applying pressure down the e-file and aiming to force a favourable ...dxe5; fxe5 f-file opening exchange: }
7... Nc6 8. c3 g6
{ is similar when Black would be fine after  9.exd6  e6!  . Instead, Morozevich was happy to go @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp2pp1p/1qnp2p1/3pP3/3P1P2/2PB4/PP4PP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe2  and }
9. Qf3 e6 10. Qe2
{ also makes plenty of space, entombing Black's light-squared bishop. White will follow up with Nf3 and O-O. If Black goes short, he runs the risk of coming under a direct attack after Ng5, h4 or simply Qf2-h4, but if he goes long, White will be quite to advance the a- and b-pawns, as well as look for a timely Ng5 to pressure f7. }
