[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games III"]
[Black "Spassky, Boris vs. Eliet, Nicolas"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Just a quick reminder that   3...e5  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.f4  can also lead to our game position after  6...Nbd7  7.fxe5  Nxe5  . }
4. f4 e5 5. dxe5
{ Spassky sees no need to retain the tension when he can rip open the centre and displace the black king. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bg5
{ This is fine, but  8.Nf3  is our approved move order, hoping that Black might exchange on f3 and only transposing after  8...Bd6  9.Bg5  c6  . }
8... c6
{ As we saw on a few occasions during Line C1, it makes sense for Black to keep White out of d5 if he can. }
9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O-O Kc7 11. Be2
{ Completing development and by enabling the rook on h1 to swing across to d1, White tees up a certain sacrifice. }
11... Nxf3
{ As we mentioned in Line C1,   11...Nfd7  can be met by  12.Nd4  with a pleasant edge,  or even   12.Rxd6!?  Kxd6  13.Rd1+  Kc7  14.Be7  with sufficient play for the exchange. }
12. gxf3 Nh5
{ Good positional play thus far from the French IM. He not only prevents f4, but prepares to begin to take over the position after 13... Bf4 or even 13...Nf4. As such, White must act. }
13. Rxd6
{ Once again, a dangerous exchange sacrifice, as well as one which objectively offers White enough compensation, as well as somewhat the easier position to handle. }
13... Kxd6 14. Rd1+ Ke5
{ Wowsers. We doubt that the 10th world champion was quite expecting his opponent to advance the king here.  Levon Aronian would later stumble into this position as Black and unsurprisingly preferred   14...Kc7  . With  15.Be7  White keeps the black king firmly in his sights while threatening f4:  15...b6   15...Bh3?!  16.f4  Nf6  17.e5  Nd7  was preferred in Brochet-Seret, French League 2009, where  18.Bd6+!?  Kc8  19.Ne4  would have retained promising compensation, and if  19...h6?!  20.Bc4  Be6  21.Bxe6!  fxe6  22.Rg1  , hitting g7 as well as preparing Rg6  16.f4  g6  . Here  17.b4!?  threatened b5 and retained full compensation in Smerdon-Aronian, Tromso Olympiad 2014, which was eventually drawn after further adventures.  Even stronger, though, appears to be   17.f5!  , as in the later Bozanic-Biti, Sibenik 2015, where White broke through with  17...Kb7?  just as after 17 b4,   17...Re8!  is the best defence when  18.Bd6+  Kb7  19.Bxh5  gxh5  20.Rg1  Rd8  21.Be5  followed by Rg7 simply must retain at least full compensation  18.Bxh5  gxh5  and now  19.Rd6!  followed by Rf6 and annexing f7 would have been very strong. }
15. Be7
{ 15.Bd8!  was more accurate, so that after  15...Re8?   15...g5  16.Bxg5  would transpose to the game  and even the engines'   15...Bh3!?  leaves White with pretty decent compensation after  16.Bc7+  Ke6  17.f4  , keeping up the threats and pressure  16.f4+!  White's darks-squared bishop is defended, meaning he is winning a piece on h5 or with  16...Nxf4  17.Bc7+  . }
15... g5
{ This doesn't especially help the black king, but neither would have   15...Ke6?  16.Bd6  @@StartBracket@@threatening f4@@EndBracket@@  16...g5  17.h4  h6  18.Bc5  . Here the engines feel that  18...Rh7  is necessary , but after   18...Nf4?  19.Bc4+  Kf6  20.Bd4+  reveals the threat  19.Rd6+  Ke5  20.Rd8  White simply must be doing pretty well having immobilised Black's sleeping queenside pieces for now, while preparing Bd6+ followed by e5.  The best defence was the calm   15...Re8!  when  16.Bd6+   16.f4+  Kxf4!  17.Bh4  g6  also sees Black surviving  Kf6  17.f4  g6  would have been forced. Spassky must have quite liked his coordination and attacking chances here, but it transpires that White doesn't have anything clear: for example,  18.e5+   18.f5!?  might be the best practical try, with the idea of  18...Kg7?   18...Kg5!  19.Bc4  Kf6  is necessary according to the engines, but few humans would surely be able to play like this  19.Bxh5  gxh5  20.Rg1+  Kf6  21.Bg3!  followed by Bh4+ and Kd2-e3.  Kg7  19.Bxh5  gxh5  20.Ne4  when Black is under some pressure on the dark squares and kingside, but White is short of an attacker and so only retains full compensation. After  20...Bf5  21.Nf6  Re6  22.Nxh5+  Kg6  23.Nf6  Rxf6  he can avoid a likely draw to the opposite-coloured bishops with  24.Rg1+  Bg4!  25.Rxg4+!?  , but then  25...Kf5  26.Rg7  Rh6  27.Rxf7+  Ke6  28.Rxb7  Rxh2  should give Black enough counterplay and would most certainly leave all three results possible in a practical game. }
16. Bxg5 Rg8
{ Black desperately tries to disrupt. Instead,   16...Nf4  17.Bf1!  Be6  would have been incredibly calm. Unfortunately for White, he doesn't have a good check, but he does have a pawn and ongoing powerful initiative for the exchange after  18.Be7  Ng6  19.Bd6+  Kf6  20.f4  . }
17. Bd8
{ This quickly turns out well.   17.Be7!?  was also a decent choice, and if  17...Bh3  18.Bd6+  .  Here   18.f4+!?  is quite tempting too, but after  18...Ke6!  19.Bg5  Rxg5!  20.fxg5  Nf4  21.Bc4+  Ke5!  Black appears to be successfully walking the defensive tightrope. }
17... Ng7
{ Missing or perhaps failing to realise he could have dealt with the threat. The only move was   17...Bh3  to unveil an attack on the d8-bishop when  18.Bc7+  Kf6  19.b4!?  is how the engines want to maintain White's full compensation. This frees a square for the king, seizes some useful space and prepares Rd4 followed by f4. }
18. f4+
{ It might have arrived 17 moves later than it would have done in his favourite King's Gambit, but we still suspect Spassky enjoyed making this deadly blow. }
18... Kxf4 { Of course, if  18...Ke6?  19.Bc4  . } 19. Rf1+
{ Eliet had seen enough, although he might have allowed a neat enough mate with   19.Rf1+  Ke3   19...Ke5  can be met by  20.Bf6+  or   20.Bc7+  Ke6  21.Bc4+  Ke7  22.Rxf7+  Ke8  23.Bd6  Ne6  24.Rxh7  when there's simply no defence with Black so tied down and one threat that of e5 and Ne4  20.Bf6  Ne8  21.Rf3  . }
