[Black "Introduction  #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ We've already seen Black fianchetto in both the Pirc and Modern, but he can also do so on the queenside, as we'll now see: D1:  1...b6   D2:  1...a6  The former, Owen's Defence, is, of course, a conventional fianchetto; the latter, the St. George, intends an extended fianchetto with ...b5.  Before we come on to those queenside paths, there is another extended fianchetto we should briefly address }
1... g5
{ The reversed Grob or Borg Defence. Black defies conventional opening principles and aims to shock White from the word go. We should be neither surprised nor despondent for there are now a number of aggressive counters to choose from.   Note too that  1...h6  2.d4  g5  is but another route in. }
2. d4
{ Naturally White seizes the space on offer while laying immediate siege to the rather overextended looking black kingside. }
2... h6
{ Black decides to maintain his g-pawn.   2...c5!?  strikes out on the dark squares, but White can simply grab:  3.Bxg5  . Now Black is surely going to go 3...Bg7, transposing to our next note. }
3. Nc3
{ Following our standard development scheme. White may now target f7 and/or deploy Harry to target Black's overextended kingside. }
3... Bg7 4. h4
{ This can also be slightly delayed, as with  4.Be3  , but there's just no reason not to make immediate use of Harry. }
4... g4
{ is the alternative when White should look to castle queenside, while also rushing the king's knight to g3 to eye the weaknesses on f5 and h5: }
5. Be3 d6 6. Nge2
{ A logical start, as well as a move which should show how much easier White's position is to handle. Black has a few Modern-type set-ups to choose from, but in any case White wants to go Ng3, Qd2 and O-O-O. }
6... a6 7. Ng3 h5 { Keeping White out of h5. } 8. Qd2 b5 9. O-O-O e6
{ Black has held his kingside together - for now. Indeed, } 10. f3
{ should see lines quickly opening to benefit White, with Be2 and Bg5 likely to follow and all the while ...b4 not too scary, with e2, a4 and even b1 available to the knight. }
