1. e4
{ We've already seen Black fianchetto in both the Pirc and Modern, but he can also do so on the queenside, as we'll now see: D1:  1...b6   D2:  1...a6  The former, Owen's Defence, is, of course, a conventional fianchetto; the latter, the St. George, intends an extended fianchetto with ...b5.  Before we come on to those queenside paths, there is another extended fianchetto we should briefly address }
1... g5
{ The reversed Grob or Borg Defence. Black defies conventional opening principles and aims to shock White from the word go. We should be neither surprised nor despondent for there are now a number of aggressive counters to choose from.   Note too that  1...h6  2.d4  g5  is but another route in. }
2. d4
{ Naturally White seizes the space on offer while laying immediate siege to the rather overextended looking black kingside. }
2... g4
{ has been tried on a number of occasions by the Borg's greatest modern-day practitioner, the Ukrainian FM Orest Vovk. Black intends  3.Qxg4  d5  , so White should simply ignore the g-pawn and develop: }
3. Nc3 Bg7
{ Now there's absolutely nothing wrong with a great many moves, including  4.Be3  , but it's certainly possible to view the pawn on g4 as a hook to be exploited: }
4. h3 { Already White is able to open the h-file and seize the initiative: }
4... gxh3 5. Nxh3 c5
{ was once tried by Vovk against Vladimir Onischuk when White might have been on to win a miniature had he targeted f7: }
6. Bc4 cxd4
{ or  6...d5  7.Nxd5  e6  when even  8.Ng5!?  exd5  9.Bxd5  is crushing, with f7 falling. }
7. Qh5 e6 8. Ng5 Qe7 9. Nb5
{ Talk about an opening disaster for Black. With Nd6+ threatened, he might try  9...d5!?  but after, amongst others,  10.e5!  dxc4  11.Nxf7!  Kd7  12.Nxd4  White's initiative is most certainly a decisive one with Bg5 next up. }
