1. e4
{ We've already seen Black fianchetto in both the Pirc and Modern, but he can also do so on the queenside, as we'll now see: D1:  1...b6   D2:  1...a6  The former, Owen's Defence, is, of course, a conventional fianchetto; the latter, the St. George, intends an extended fianchetto with ...b5.  Before we come on to those queenside paths, there is another extended fianchetto we should briefly address }
1... g5
{ The reversed Grob or Borg Defence. Black defies conventional opening principles and aims to shock White from the word go. We should be neither surprised nor despondent for there are now a number of aggressive counters to choose from.   Note too that  1...h6  2.d4  g5  is but another route in. }
2. d4
{ Naturally White seizes the space on offer while laying immediate siege to the rather overextended looking black kingside. }
2... Bg7
{ is the move Black would like to make work, but White can be fearless and simply capture: }
3. Bxg5 c5
{ Now White is rather spoilt for choice, but in any case should be looking to return the pawn to seize the initiative. }
4. Nf3 { attempts to lure Black's queen or queen's knight into play: } 4... Nc6
5. d5 { is also a strong sacrifice: } 5... Bxb2 6. Nbd2
{ Now White is ready to go Rb1, as well as take on c6, and pocketing the exchange is far from a panacea for Black: }
6... Bxa1 7. Qxa1 Nd4 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ White's pressure down the long diagonal will force a grotesque weakening in the black kingside:  9...f6  10.Be2!  h5  11.Be3  White is now ready to castle and also to blast ahead with e5, with even  11...d6  12.O-O  Bg4  13.f3  Bd7  14.f4  excellent for him followed by beginning to cause direct issues for the black king after e5. }
