[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other Fianchettoes D1: 1...b6"]
[Black "D1: 1...b6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Reverend Owen's favourite defence and a queenside Modern if you like. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3
{ Our standard method of development, as well as one which here helps to maintain White's strong centre. Unlike after  3.Bd3  , Black now cannot really contemplate  3...Nf6  4.e5  would be on, or even  3...f5?  , so is likely to continue with the mirrored Pirc approach. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The best square for the bishop, overprotecting e4 and making way for the king's knight to come to e2.   With Black's king unlikely to run to the queenside,  4.a4  wouldn't make too much sense, so White prioritizes development while remaining fairly flexible. }
4... Bb4
{ The main line, pinning the knight on c3 Nimzo and Winawer style.   4...c5?!  is once again flawed because of a certain strong central advance:  5.d5!  Nf6  . Now White has a few decent options, including 6. Nf3, but effective and strong too is  6.Nge2  , transposing to our coverage of 4...Nf6. }
5. Ne2
{ Once again, the best square for the knight, as well as a choice which avoids being saddled with doubled c-pawns. }
5... Nf6
{ By some margin Black's most popular move, but simply not a good one when the knight arriving on e4 won't come with tempo against c3.   5...c5?!  6.d5!  is once again a possibility to avoid as Black - and to hope for as White!  6...exd5   6...Nf6  7.O-O  will very like our coverage of 4...Nf6 5. Nge2 c5 6. d5 if Black somehow dares to touch d5 @@StartBracket@@ Nf4 will be quick to arrive on the scene @@EndBracket@@, but otherwise  7...O-O  8.Bg5  is just a rather awkward pin.  7.exd5  Bxd5  8.O-O  once again leaves White's somewhat superior development providing far too much compensation for the pawn. Nf4 will be next up and if the c3-knight moves, Black may even find his bishop in trouble on b4. As such, he might trade, but in any case will continue to suffer:  8...Bxc3  9.Nxc3  Be6  10.Nb5!  . White threatens Bf4, as well as Nd6+, and even Be4 may become a serious headache for Black who is just in some trouble. }
6. a3 Be7
{ 6...Bxc3+?!  7.Nxc3  merely bags the bishop-pair and leaves both e5 and Bg5 very much on the agenda. }
7. e5
{ Sergey Karjakin once castled against Hikaru Nakamura in a bullet game, but this is even stronger as Black isn't about to obtain a degree of freedom through an exchange of knights. }
7... Nd5
{ Now a leading Russian player made a pretty decent case for  8.Ne4!?  f5  9.N4g3  with a very pleasant advantage in Kosteniuk-Herbrechtsmeier, Biel 2004, and White has something even stronger: }
8. Nxd5 Bxd5 9. Nf4
{ Our favourite leap and one which just leaves Black in serious trouble. His bishop is attacked and White all set to crank up the queenside pressure with Qg4 or even Qh5, as well as just to castle and/or expand with c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other Fianchettoes D1: 1...b6"]
[Black "D1: 1...b6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Reverend Owen's favourite defence and a queenside Modern if you like. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3
{ Our standard method of development, as well as one which here helps to maintain White's strong centre. Unlike after  3.Bd3  , Black now cannot really contemplate  3...Nf6  4.e5  would be on, or even  3...f5?  , so is likely to continue with the mirrored Pirc approach. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The best square for the bishop, overprotecting e4 and making way for the king's knight to come to e2.   With Black's king unlikely to run to the queenside,  4.a4  wouldn't make too much sense, so White prioritizes development while remaining fairly flexible. }
4... Bb4
{ The main line, pinning the knight on c3 Nimzo and Winawer style.   4...c5?!  is once again flawed because of a certain strong central advance:  5.d5!  Nf6  . Now White has a few decent options, including 6. Nf3, but effective and strong too is  6.Nge2  , transposing to our coverage of 4...Nf6. }
5. Ne2
{ Once again, the best square for the knight, as well as a choice which avoids being saddled with doubled c-pawns. }
5... d5
{ might be Black's relatively best try, aiming to reach a strange sort of French Winawer position after  6.e5  . That should favour White  6...Be7  7.Nb1!  is one important idea, but can also obtain a pretty pleasant advantage through simple means: }
6. O-O dxe4 7. Nxe4
{ Now Black's bishop looks a little redundant on b4 and White can always obtain a pleasant set-up with Nf4, c3 and Re1. That may well translate into attacking chances on the kingside: for example, }
7... Nd7 8. N2g3 Ngf6 9. Qf3
{ White refuses to fear the tactics and even creates a certain threat down the long diagonal. }
9... Rb8 10. Rd1
{ Placing the rook opposite the enemy queen, with a definite edge. White is now ready to go c4, b3 and Bb2, after which it's not too hard to imagine the black king beginning to feel the heat one day, especially if a timely d5 pawn sacrifice lands to activate the bishop on b2. }
*

