[Black "D1: 1...b6  #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Reverend Owen's favourite defence and a queenside Modern if you like. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nc3
{ Our standard method of development, as well as one which here helps to maintain White's strong centre. Unlike after  3.Bd3  , Black now cannot really contemplate  3...Nf6  4.e5  would be on, or even  3...f5?  , so is likely to continue with the mirrored Pirc approach. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The best square for the bishop, overprotecting e4 and making way for the king's knight to come to e2.   With Black's king unlikely to run to the queenside,  4.a4  wouldn't make too much sense, so White prioritizes development while remaining fairly flexible. }
4... Nf6
{ is Black's main alternative to our main line,  4...Bb4  . Interestingly, Stockfish is so unenamoured with Black's position it already wants to gain space with  5.h4!?  here. White can very much also continue with our favourite anti-Owen's set-up: }
5. Nge2
{ Here rather than f3, as the knight overprotects its colleague on c3  @@StartBracket@@very useful should Black go ...Bb4 @@EndBracket@@, may emerge on f4 or g3 and also doesn't block the f-pawn. Now Black is likely to try and bid for some freedom: }
5... d5
{ is the other common move, but it merely swaps avoiding early danger for an inferior version of a French: }
6. e5 Nfd7 7. Nf4
{ A fine spot, indeed, for the knight and White already has a crushing threat - Nxe6. Moreover, Black only has a choice of rather sub-optimal ways to parry the threat: }
7... g6
{ 7...Qe7  8.Nb5!  followed by c3 and O-O once c7 is defended left White with very easy play and Black badly struggling to untangle in Kovalenko-Bogdanovich, Basel 2014. }
8. Qg4 Be7
{ was surprisingly once tried against Richard Rapport, who, equally surprisingly, failed to go }
9. Nxe6
{ 9...fxe6  10.Bxg6+  hxg6  11.Qxg6+  with a winning attack as we saw after 7...Be7. }
