[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other Fianchettoes D2: 1...a6"]
[Black "D2: 1...a6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defence, famously once used by Tony Miles to defeat world champion Anatoly Karpov in the European Team Championship. }
2. d4 { Needless to say, White should occupy the centre. } 2... b5
{ Black expands without delay. A great many other moves have been tried here on the odd occasion over the years, often transposing to or leading to inferior versions of other defenses: for example,  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Be2  would take play back into our Modern coverage,   while  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.Nf3  should be an inferior Scandinavian for Black - compare with our next chapter. }
3. Bd3
{ Thus far in the course we've opened with 1. e4, 2. d4 and 3. Nc3, but now we're going to have to grow a little wiser and react to Black's approach.   Here  3.Nc3  doesn't make so much sense with Black having already gone ...b5, but it's hard to imagine a better post for the light-squared bishop than d3.   White will now follow up in classical vein  @@StartBracket@@don't worry, aggression will still follow!@@EndBracket@@, with Nf3 and at some point O-O, all the while keeping a disruptive and weakening a4 break in mind. }
3... Bb7 4. Nf3
{ Continuing White's simple set-up, one which leaves White able to quickly castle and only now will he start to consider more aggressive options in the centre and on the queenside. }
4... e6
{ Black's main move and this position can also occur if ...e6 has been preferred on an earlier move. }
5. O-O
{ Good classical play, making the king safe before looking to seize the initiative with one or more of the a4, d5 and e5 advances. }
5... c5
{ Black's most popular choice, continuing the queenside theme and beginning immediate counterplay. }
6. c3
{ Simply bolstering the centre, although fans of space advantages may also wish to consider  6.d5!?  c4  7.Be2  . }
6... Nf6 { Black's usual choice, increasing the pressure against e4. } 7. e5
{ Once again, White refuses to allow the black knight any peace on f6. } 7...
Nd5 8. dxc5
{ Simple chess, weakening the black position and preparing to bring a knight to e4. This seems even stronger than the also rather tempting  8.Ng5!?  . }
8... Bxc5 9. a4
{ Even stronger than the immediate 9.Nbd2, forcing Black to weaken further and hoping to gain extra attacking firepower after  9...bxa4?!  10.Rxa4  when Rg4 or Rh4 may quickly follow. }
9... b4 10. Nbd2
{ Gambiting the c-pawn for the initiative appears even stronger than the  10.c4  Ne7  11.Nbd2  of Kurmann-Dragnev, Graz 2015. Note too that it isn't really a gambit: }
10... Be7 { Prophylaxis against Ne4 as Black tries to cover the kingside. } 11.
Ne4 bxc3 12. bxc3
{ White's queenside might be shattered, but this still looks like a fine, aggressive set-up for him. He threatens to check on d6, can cause some disruption with Rb1, may regroup against a castled black king with Bc2 and Qd3, and can also increase the pressure with Bg5 or Nfg5. }
