[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defence, famously once used by Tony Miles to defeat world champion Anatoly Karpov in the European Team Championship. }
2. d4 { Needless to say, White should occupy the centre. } 2... b5
{ Black expands without delay. A great many other moves have been tried here on the odd occasion over the years, often transposing to or leading to inferior versions of other defenses: for example,  2...g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Be2  would take play back into our Modern coverage,   while  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.Nf3  should be an inferior Scandinavian for Black - compare with our next chapter. }
3. Bd3
{ Thus far in the course we've opened with 1. e4, 2. d4 and 3. Nc3, but now we're going to have to grow a little wiser and react to Black's approach.   Here  3.Nc3  doesn't make so much sense with Black having already gone ...b5, but it's hard to imagine a better post for the light-squared bishop than d3.   White will now follow up in classical vein  @@StartBracket@@don't worry, aggression will still follow!@@EndBracket@@, with Nf3 and at some point O-O, all the while keeping a disruptive and weakening a4 break in mind. }
3... Bb7 4. Nf3
{ Continuing White's simple set-up, one which leaves White able to quickly castle and only now will he start to consider more aggressive options in the centre and on the queenside. }
4... Nf6
{ was Tony Miles's choice and while there's absolutely nothing wrong with Karpov's  5.Qe2  , White can also be more aggressive at this point: }
5. e5 Nd5 6. a4
{ White wastes no time getting in the disruptive advance. The b-pawn now hangs and once it moves White will gain options involving c4: }
6... b4 7. Ng5
{ White wastes no time seizing the initiative @@StartBracket@@ 7. c4 is also quite promising @@EndBracket@@, with the immediate threat that of Qf3, both hitting f7 and causing chaos down the h1-a8 diagonal: }
7... e6 8. Qf3 Qe7
{ 8...f5?  was preferred in Borchers-Canal Oliveras, correspondence 1996, where White surprisingly managed to reject  9.g4!  We're not at all sure how, though, since there just isn't a good move for Black here:  9...h6  10.Qh3  is the key point when the tactics favour White, as shown by  10...g6  11.gxf5  exf5  12.Rg1!  when the immediate threat is Bxf5. }
9. c4
{ It's down the long diagonal and on the queenside that White wants to seize the initiative; there are bigger fish for now to fry than the h7-pawn:  9...bxc3  10.bxc3  Nc6  11.O-O  .   White will meet ...h6 with Nh7 and just enjoys a very pleasant space advantage. Once his knight is on h7 or e4, Ba3 will become an issue for Black, just as it will if the queen nudges over to g3, for example:  11...Na5  12.Qg3!  Nb3  13.Ba3  Qd8  14.Bxf8  Kxf8  15.Ra3  Black hasn't got anywhere on the queenside and not only is h7 falling, but f4-f5 on White's agenda. }
