[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other Fianchettoes D2: 1...a6"]
[Black "D2: 1...a6  #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defence, famously once used by Tony Miles to defeat world champion Anatoly Karpov in the European Team Championship. }
2. d4 { Needless to say, White should occupy the centre. } 2... e6 3. Nf3
{ is far from forced, but makes sense for our move order. Now  3...b5  4.Bd3  remains within our St. George coverage and the French alternative isn't such a great line for Black: }
3... d5 4. e5
{ The Advance variation, as we advocated in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. } 4...
Bd7 5. c3 Bb5
{ Black strives to make positive use of the inclusion of ...a6 to exchange off his potentially bad bishop. }
6. Bxb5+ axb5 7. O-O
{ As we showed in our other 1. e4 course, this should be a pretty nice edge for White. One idea is Ng5, another Ne1-d3, maintaining control while freeing the f-pawn for attacking duty. }
