[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other Fianchettoes D2: 1...a6"]
[Black "D2: 1...a6  #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defence, famously once used by Tony Miles to defeat world champion Anatoly Karpov in the European Team Championship. }
2. d4 { Needless to say, White should occupy the centre. } 2... h6
{ is the Creepy-Crawly Defence, a sometime Basman favourite, keeping open the options of ...b5, ...e6, ...d6 and ...g6. }
3. Nc3
{ is far from forced, but makes good sense. Black may now head for a St. George after all where our knight is on c3, but even more importantly, ...h6 doesn't look too useful: }
3... b5 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nf3
{ White's knight is far from unhappy if forced to relocate via e2 to g3 and meanwhile a strong pawn challenge is imminent, be that a4 or }
5... e6 6. e5
{ This advance makes a lot of sense when Black has weakened his kingside light squares, meaning that he will find it somewhat harder to go ...f6 or ...Nge7. White also frees e4 for the knight on c3 and will be able to maintain the powerful bridgehead on e5:   6...d6   6...c5  7.Be4!  maintains control while preparing to bring the knight closer to d6.  7.O-O  Nd7  8.Re1   8.d5!?  is also pretty tempting, gambiting to rip open lines towards the black king.  8...dxe5  9.Nxe5  Nxe5   9...Ngf6?  prevents Nxf7 Kxf7; Qh5+ after which White will hit e6, but fails to  10.Ng6  fxg6  11.Bxg6+  Ke7  12.Qe2  with a devastating attack down the e-file.  10.dxe5  . The exchange of knights has kept Black on the board, but isn't overly all that helpful for him. White will deploy the queen to g4, aiming to tie Black to the defence of g7, while also preparing to begin to exploit the weakened black queenside with Be4, whether immediately or after first Bf4 and Rad1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games IV"]
[Black "Speelman, Jonathan vs. Basman, Michael"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ 1...b6  2.d4  Bb7  3.Nc3  e6  4.Bd3  would be our standard Owen's route into the game. }
2. Nc3
{ And here we advocated  2.d4  against the French in Grandmaster Gambits: 1.e4. Black can avoid the French with  2...b6  when  3.Bd3  Bb7  4.Nc3  is another transposition. }
2... b6 3. d4 Bb7 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ The highly creative and original English IM heads for the main line of the Owen's. }
5. Nge2 c5 6. d5
{ This was a novelty at the time and probably one devised over the board by Jon Speelman, another extremely creative and original English player, if one who was somewhat stronger than Mike Basman, going on a few years after this game to briefly become world no.4 as well as a two-time Candidate. }
6... a6 7. a4
{ As Speelman's notes from 'Chess Informant 36' reveal, he was unsurprisingly keen to deny Black counterplay with  7.O-O  b5  . }
7... exd5
{ Basman decides that he might as well have a pawn for his suffering. It's an easy decision to criticise with hindsight, but in any case Black's position is quite uncomfortable, with his knight stuck on b8 and slow development not really cutting the mustard either, i.e.   7...Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Ng3  d6   9...exd5  10.exd5  Nxd5??  doesn't just fall for a Greek Gift, but allows something even stronger:   or  10...Bxd5  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  , hoping for  12.Qh5?  Nf6  , when White has a very pleasant choice between 12. Bxh7+ and winning the exchange with  12.Be4  .  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  12.Qh5  , with a decisive double attack, as  12...f5  13.Nxf5  continues to eye the loose bishop, as well as h7.  10.Bc4  . White is now all set to expand with f4 or even land his knight on a dream post after  10...e5  11.Nf5  . Black can chase it away, but continues to suffer, cramped and low on counterplay after  11...Bc8  12.Nxe7+  Qxe7  13.Qe2  when White may even have time to go Bd2, f3, g3, Rae1 and Kh1 before beginning to roll with f4. }
8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Nf4
{ This is such a good post for the knight, not only causing Black serious problems in the centre, but also planning a timely leap to h5 to strike against g7. }
10... Be6
{ Speelman thought this was the best try and, unsurprisingly, he was probably right.   10...Bb7?  11.O-O  Be7  12.Re1  is, just like with the a-pawns at home, a major issue for Black. White will turn up the pressure next move with Qg4 or Nh5 and castling is impossible:  12...O-O ?  13.Qh5  g6  14.Nxg6!  and the attack is already a mating one, in view of  14...fxg6  15.Bxg6  hxg6  16.Qxg6+  Kh8  17.Re5  .   10...Qe7+  is a better alternative, but after  11.Be3  Be6  12.O-O  Black remains significantly behind in development and vulnerable on the queenside.  12...g6  13.Re1  Bg7  would attempt to address that, but after  14.Be4  Nc6   14...Ra7  15.a5  b5  16.Nd5  Bxd5  17.Qxd5  is pretty crushing too.  15.Bxc6  dxc6  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Qf3  Black is simply suffering a structural nightmare. }
11. Be4 Ra7
{ Exploiting the inclusion of ...a6 and pretty much forced, with  11...Nc6?  failing to  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Qh5+  . }
12. O-O Be7
{ Speelman wondered if   12...g6!?  might have been an improvement and perhaps it is, although  13.a5!  @@StartBracket@@Softening up the black queenside.@@EndBracket@@  13...b5  14.Re1  still looks pretty good for White. He will begin to target the dark squares, with Nd5 or  14...Bg7  15.Be3  when  15...d6   15...Bxb2  16.Bxc5  Rc7  17.Bd6  Bxa1?  18.Qxa1  would be a dream exchange sacrifice for all the dark squares.  16.Bd5  leaves Black's position collapsing down the e-file in view of  16...Re7  17.Nxe6  fxe6  18.Bg5  . }
13. Ra3
{ Swinging the rook into play.   13.Qh5  would also have been quite strong, aiming to provoke a kingside weakness, while also intending an undermining Be3 and a5. }
13... O-O
{ A brave choice, although Black had to do something with Rg3 on its way. } 14.
Rg3 { White is now threatening a classic bishop sacrifice on h7. } 14... f5
{ 14...Nc6?  15.Bxh7+!  The more mundane   15.Nxe6  fxe6  16.Qh5  also wins.  Kxh7  16.Qh5+  was the aforementioned threat, and if  16...Kg8  17.Qh6  Bf6  18.Nh5  g6  19.Bg5  , overloading and winning.  Instead,   14...Bh4  aims to disrupt, but after  15.Qh5  f5  16.Rh3  White will again obtain a huge advantage by combining attack with weakening Black's structure:  16...fxe4  17.Rxh4  h6  18.Nxe6  dxe6  19.Qg4  , hitting all of e4, e6 and especially h6. }
15. Bd5 Rf6
{ This pretty much loses.   15...Bxd5  16.Qxd5+  Rf7  was necessary, as pointed out by Speelman, although after his  17.Nh5  Black would have remained under heavy pressure. One interesting point is  17...g6  18.Re1  Nc6  19.Rxe7!   19.Bh6  followed by Rge3 is a simpler alternative.  Qxe7   19...Nxe7?  20.Nf6+  Kg7  21.Bh6+!  is a real put that in your pipe and smoke it moment! It's now mate in five:  21...Kxh6  22.Rh3+  Kg5  or   22...Kg7  23.Rxh7+  Kxf6  24.Qd6+  Kg5  25.h4+  Kg4  26.f3  23.Ne4+  Kg4  24.f3+  Kf4  25.Rh4+  Ke3  26.Qd2  .  20.Re3  Qf8  21.Re8!  when  21...Qxe8  22.Nf6+  Kf8  23.Bh6+  Ke7  24.Nxe8  Kxe8  leaves Black with two rooks for the queen. However, his co-ordination and dark squares are shot, leaving White doing extremely well after  25.h4  followed by Bf4-d6 and a gradual undermining of the black queenside. }
16. Re1 { Increasing the pressure to decisive levels against e6. } 16... Bxd5
17. Qxd5+ Rf7
{ Black is also a goner after   17...Kf8  18.Nh5  Rf7  when the prettiest of all the sacrificial finishes is arguably  19.Bh6!  gxh6  20.Nf6!  Bxf6  21.Qd6+  , and if  21...Be7  22.Qxh6+  Ke8  23.Rg8+  ,  and   17...Kh8  18.Ng6+!   18.Rxg7!  also wins in view of  18...Kxg7  19.Nh5+  Kg6  20.Rxe7!  Qxe7  21.Qg8+  Rxg6  19.Rxg6  hxg6  20.Re3  . The simple threat is Rh3+ Bh4; g3 and  20...Bh4  or   20...Bg5  21.Rh3+  Bh6  22.Bxh6  gxh6  23.Qf7  Qg5  when a decisive switch-back is  24.Re3  21.Qf7!  leads to a fatality on e8. }
18. Nh5 g6
{ 18...Bf8  is demolished by, amongst others,  19.Bg5  , and if  19...Qc8  20.Nf6+!  gxf6  21.Bh6+  . }
19. Bh6 { Talk about a powerful first move from the bishop! } 19... Nc6
{ Thanks to the pin down the a2-g8 diagonal,   19...Bf8?  fails to  20.Re8!  . }
20. Rge3
{ Basman had seen enough. White threatens Nf6+ and   20.Rge3  Ra8  21.Rxe7!  Nxe7  22.Nf6+  ends all resistance. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scandinavian Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ Unsurprisingly there's nothing better than this natural capture and now we will focus our coverage on three main lines:  - E1:  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Bg4   - E2:  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Nf6   - E3:  2...Nf6  3.Nf3  Nxd5  and  2...Nf6  3.Nf3  Bg4  .   The development of the king's knight rather than  3.Nc3  may not seem aggressive, but it is likely to prove mildly annoying to black players looking to trot out their favourite line, like the fashionable  2...Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qd6   We'll even follow up in the  2...Qxd5  lines with a rapid  Be2 and O-O. That may not seem exactly aggressive, but once the king is safe White will quickly storm the center with d4 and c4 in many lines. Moreover, Black's critical line  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Bg4  sees him castling queenside, an approach which can lead to White launching a direct attack at quite an early stage. }
2... Qxd5 { Black's most popular move by a ratio of about two to one. } 3. Nf3
{ Kingside development first is White's mantra and note that the great Scandinavian authority and Chessable legend John Bartholomew described  3.Nf3  as 'underrated'. Now Black almost always goes  3...Bg4  or  3...Nf6  , but we should also check whether he might expand in the center straight away. }
3... e5 4. Nc3
{ Only now does White attack the queen so, since she must stay in touch with the pawn on e5. Retreating to d6 allows White to seize the initiative with 5. d4, so Black usually goes to a5 or e6. }
4... Qe6
{ Dissuading d4.   4...Qa5?!  is a more typical Scandinavian square for the queen, but not one which disrupts White's development in the slightest here:  5.Bc4  . White is now ready to castle, then lay siege to the e5-pawn with Re1, with a rapid d4 or Ng5 two methods by which a powerful early initiative may be seized. }
5. Be2
{ Modest development perhaps, but White does lead in development and is all set to go O-O and d4. Note too that 5...e4 would just cost Black a pawn and the initiative after 6. Ng5. }
5... Nf6 6. d4
{ Blasting open the position to favour White's superior development. } 6... e4
7. Ng5 { Aggressive and strong: e4 and f7 can be targeted. } 7... Qf5 8. O-O
{ Or the immediate  8.f3  . Having housed his king White will go f3 next and even has an immediate threat due to a neat tactic down the e-file: }
8... h6 9. Ngxe4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Qxe4 11. Re1
{ The aforementioned tactic. Black is simply losing material in view of } 11...
Kd8 { 11...Qh4?  12.Bb5+  is mate next move. } 12. Bb5
{ when the queen is skewered to the mate threat on e8. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scandinavian Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5
{ Unsurprisingly there's nothing better than this natural capture and now we will focus our coverage on three main lines:  - E1:  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Bg4   - E2:  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Nf6   - E3:  2...Nf6  3.Nf3  Nxd5  and  2...Nf6  3.Nf3  Bg4  .   The development of the king's knight rather than  3.Nc3  may not seem aggressive, but it is likely to prove mildly annoying to black players looking to trot out their favourite line, like the fashionable  2...Qxd5  3.Nc3  Qd6   We'll even follow up in the  2...Qxd5  lines with a rapid  Be2 and O-O. That may not seem exactly aggressive, but once the king is safe White will quickly storm the center with d4 and c4 in many lines. Moreover, Black's critical line  2...Qxd5  3.Nf3  Bg4  sees him castling queenside, an approach which can lead to White launching a direct attack at quite an early stage. }
2... Qxd5 { Black's most popular move by a ratio of about two to one. } 3. Nf3
{ Kingside development first is White's mantra and note that the great Scandinavian authority and Chessable legend John Bartholomew described  3.Nf3  as 'underrated'. Now Black almost always goes  3...Bg4  or  3...Nf6  , but we should also check whether he might expand in the center straight away. }
3... Nc6
{ can also be met by  4.Nc3  followed by Bb5 and/or d4, although here you may too prefer the outwardly more modest }
4. Be2
{ when Black usually transposes to the main line of Line E1 with 4...Bg4. Instead, 4...Nf6 will be seen in Line E2 and neither is the central advance to be feared by White: }
4... e5 5. O-O
{ Housing the king, refusing to fear ...e4 and intending to hit back with Nc3 and/or d4: }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qa5 7. d4
{ Only one king is safe here and it's not the one on e8. White may go d5, but his immediate threat is to take twice on e5 and go Re1, which all just leaves Black unable to equalize. }
7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4
{ The structure may be symmetrical, but development will count. White threatens Nb5 and Bd2, as well as Re1, and even racing his king to safety won't see Black equalize:   9...Be7  10.Nb5  O-O  11.Bf4  Black must now drop a piece back to the first rank to defend c7, leaving White able to begin to expand on the queenside with c4 or even begin to eye the kingside after Bd3, with a definite edge. }
*

