[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games V"]
[Black "Decoster, Frederic vs. Hopman, Pieter"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O
{ As per usual, White first develops the kingside, then prods the bishop and only then decides what to do in the centre. }
5... O-O-O 6. h3 Bh5 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. b4
{ Our favourite gambit and here we'll see that even a common mechanism for Black doesn't prevent him from coming under pressure. }
8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nd4
{ This is likely to lead to a further exchange, but does nothing to quell White's pawn storm. }
10. a4 Kb8
{ Far from an uncommon move in such positions, but every tempo can count and here   10...e6  11.a5!  must be the critical line, as we've just seen. }
11. Nb5
{ A powerful knight leap, as well as a move which reminds us that White doesn't just have to rely on pushing the pawns. He would be more than happy to give up a pawn to open the a-file. }
11... Nf6
{ 11...Nxb5?  12.axb5  Qxb5  13.d3  leaves the b-pawn taboo and Black probably already lost, with White set to go Be3 followed by Ra5 and Qb1 or just c4 and b5.  Instead,   11...Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  is more consistent with Black's opening play, but after  12...a6  13.d4!  you still have to want to be White with Bf4 next up:  the simpler   13.Na3  is also rather promising, heading for c4  13...Qd5   13...axb5?  14.axb5  threatens to win on the spot with Qa3 and even  14...Qxb5  15.c4!  won't save Black for long, as shown by  15...Qxb4  16.Bf4  and Rfb1  14.Bf4!  Qxf3  or   14...e5!?  15.Bxe5  Qxf3  16.Bxc7+  Kc8  17.gxf3  Rd7  18.Bg3  , still with a ginormous attack for the piece  15.Bxc7+  Kc8  16.gxf3  . Even with the queens off, White is happy to sacrifice a piece and no surprise with the black kingside still fully asleep: for example,  16...Re8  17.Bg3  axb5  18.axb5  Nf6  19.Ra8+  Kd7  20.Ra7  Kc8  21.c4  and the pawn armada will just overwhelm the black king after c5-c6. }
12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Ra3
{ Olé! This neat rook lift takes full advantage of the remaining centre pawns still being at home and merely confirms that White is just doing pretty well. }
13... Qd7 14. Rd3
{ White is happy to trade rooks to cost Black further time and ahead of expanding in the centre himself. }
14... Qc8 15. Rxd8 Qxd8 16. d4
{ 16.Qe2  e6  17.Bb2!?  is also pretty tempting and strong: a5-a6 may follow and, of course, the b-pawn is poisoned:  17...Bxb4?  18.Bxf6  gxf6  19.Qb5  and wins. }
16... e6 17. Bg5
{ This can hardly be terrible, of course, but we would have preferred   17.c3  or even just   17.b5!?  followed by c4, Bf4 and perhaps even then c5, with a huge, slow-motion attack. }
17... Be7 18. Re1 Qd6
{ 18...h6!?  was a more challenging defence, although perhaps here Decoster would finally have sacrificed, as with  19.Bf4  Nd5  20.Bd2!  , and if  20...Bxb4  21.c4  Bxd2  22.Qxd2  Nb6  23.Rb1  with a very strong attack for the pawn. }
19. c3
{ Maintaining control. Even here White is doing extremely well with his bishop-pair, extra space and Black lacking any real counterplay. }
19... h6 20. Bh4 Qd7 21. a5
{ 21.b5  was surely the right pawn to push and would just have left White doing very well. Qb3 and a5 will follow or  21...Nd5  22.Bxe7  Nxe7  23.Qd3  Rd8  24.a5  when a6 is set to leave Black with a serious light-square weakness around his king and even a cheeky Qh7 might present a major headache for him. }
21... a6 { Holding White up on the queenside. } 22. Qb3 Rd8 23. Rb1 c6
{ Finally, Black places this pawn on its most common square in the Scandinavian in general. He is no longer about to get mated in the short term, but is far from fully out of the woods. }
24. Rd1
{ A strange move and again something much more energetic was required:   24.c4!  . This way b5 is back on the agenda and Black wouldn't have been able to touch the d-pawn:  24...Qxd4?  25.b5!  cxb5  26.cxb5  Qxh4  27.bxa6  . The attack is clearly worth much, much more than a piece, as shown by  27...Bb4  28.Qa4  . }
24... Nd5
{ Now White will be unable to avoid the exchange of one half of his once mighty bishop-pair. }
25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26. c4
{ Finally going for it, but too late as Hopman is solidly enough placed. }
26... Nc7
{ 26...Nxb4?  27.Rb1  wins a piece,  but   26...Qxb4!?  was actually possible:  27.Qxb4  Nxb4  28.Rb1  Nc2  29.Bxc6  Nxd4  30.Rxb7+  Kc8  31.Rb6  Nxc6  32.Rxc6+  Kb7  33.Rb6+  Ka7  and the rook endgame is surely going to end in a draw, perhaps even immediately with  34.Rc6  Kb7  35.Rb6+  . }
27. Qc3 Qf6 28. Qe3 Qf5 29. Be4
{ Black must be OK after   29.Be4  Qg5  , and if  30.Bf3  Qe7  , with a rock-solid set-up,  but White might have tried   29.Qe5!?  , hoping for  29...Qxe5?  30.dxe5  Rxd1+  31.Bxd1  when there would have been definite prospects to turn White's extra space and far superior minor piece into good winning chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3
{ With a threat and as we saw back in Richmond-Smith, not only does the queen exert some pressure against f7, but may move too to another rather fine spot on g3.   This line should also come as a shock to Black, having been played in just under one hundred@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ games on the main databases, and it sometimes goes unmentioned, including not being discussed in Cyrus Lakdawala's 'The Alekhine Defence: Move by Move'.   Now Black has two main moves, of which the former is by some margin the most common:   F1:  3...e6   F2:  3...Nb6  There are two other moves which don't drop the knight, as we'll now see. }
3... Nb4
{ A tempting raid and one which exploits the queen's absence from d1, but Black will land up losing more time than White. }
4. Na3
{ Placing the knight on the rim, but preparing to drive Black back in disarray. This way White's position is also easier to untangle than after  4.Qb3  c5!  5.d4  d6  6.c3  N4c6  . }
4... c5
{ Seizing space so does potentially weaken d6, but seems prudent with c3 such an issue. }
5. c3
{ It's hard to resist  5.Bc4  and  5...e6  6.Qg3  d6  7.exd6  was probably a small edge in the only game to have reached this position, Matkovic-Viskic, Sv Filip i Jakov 2001, but driving the black knight backwards ahead of going Qg3 appears even stronger. }
5... N4c6 6. Qg3
{ This looks like an improved version of a c3 Sicilian for White, in part due to his active queen and just how many moves has Black made with his king's knight only to block in its partner? }
6... d5 { Breaking out so looks logical before White goes Nf3 and d4. } 7. exd6
{ White wants to open the position and exploit his active queen @@StartBracket@@6...d6 would also be met by 7. exd6@@EndBracket@@. }
7... exd6 8. Nf3 Nd7 { Hurrying the knight over to f6. } 9. Bb5
{ A different piece makes good use of b5. White simply wants to go O-O then begin to swing forwards after d4, so Black would be likely to try and disrupt such plans with a check. }
9... Qe7+ 10. Kd1
{ Once again, d1 will prove a more than good enough home for the white king. Clearly Re1 is a serious threat and even plugging the e-file doesn't enable Black to equalise. }
10... Nf6 11. Re1 Be6 12. Ng5
{ Keeping up the pressure. The position is far from conventional, but White does appear to be for choice. Not only will a timely Nxe6 pocket the bishop-pair, but Nc4 is on its way and even a queenside advance may become possible. }
12... O-O-O 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 Re8 15. d4
{ Vigorous and seemingly even stronger than  15.Nc4  or  15.Nc2  , as well as the tempting exchange on c6. White simply wants to exchange on c5 then tuck his king away on c2 and the alternative for Black involves opening the file towards his king.   15...cxd4  16.cxd4  d5  17.Bd2!?  The maximalist approach, keeping Black out of b4 while facilitating Rc1. White may also swing his queen across to b3 and the black king will surely quickly begin to feel the heat.   17.f3  should suffice for a pleasant pull. There is only one critical response:  17...Ne4!  18.Rxe4  dxe4  19.Rc1!?   19.d5  wins material and may be good, but is messy and far from clear after  19...Rd8  20.dxc6  Qg5  .  19...Qd7  20.Qb3!  White threatens Nc4-e5/a5 and even after  20...Bxa3  21.bxa3  Black's king appears in the greater danger with Qa4 next up and the d-pawn completely taboo:  21...Qxd4?  22.Bxc6  bxc6  23.Rxc6+  Kd8  24.Qb7  Qd7  25.Rc8+!  and wins, in view of  25...Qxc8  26.Ba5+ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3
