{ It's hard to resist  5.Bc4  and  5...e6  6.Qg3  d6  7.exd6  was probably a small edge in the only game to have reached this position, Matkovic-Viskic, Sv Filip i Jakov 2001, but driving the black knight backwards ahead of going Qg3 appears even stronger. }
5... N4c6 6. Qg3
{ This looks like an improved version of a c3 Sicilian for White, in part due to his active queen and just how many moves has Black made with his king's knight only to block in its partner? }
6... d5 { Breaking out so looks logical before White goes Nf3 and d4. } 7. exd6
{ White wants to open the position and exploit his active queen @@StartBracket@@6...d6 would also be met by 7. exd6@@EndBracket@@. }
7... exd6 8. Nf3 d5
{ isn't completely clear after  9.Nb5  Qe7+  , but White has a strong intermediate move: }
9. d4 cxd4 10. Nb5
{ Now Nfxd4 and Bf4 will follow with a dream anti-IQP position or a clever central manoeuvre: }
10... Qe7+ 11. Kd1
{ The king is actually pretty safe on d1, whereas Black's royal family are in some trouble. Not only is Nc7+ threatened, but White can create threats on d6 and down the e-file }
11... Na6 12. Bf4 Qd7 13. Nfxd4
{ White simply intends Bd3 and Re1+ and Black's position remains an uncoordinated mess whether or not he exchanges the queens:   13...Qg4+  14.Kd2  Qxg3  15.hxg3  Be7  16.Re1  White threatens Nxc6 bxc6; Nd6+ and Nxc8, picking up the knight on a6, and Bd3 may also follow and/or even Rh5. }
*

