1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3
{ With a threat and as we saw back in Richmond-Smith, not only does the queen exert some pressure against f7, but may move too to another rather fine spot on g3.   This line should also come as a shock to Black, having been played in just under one hundred@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ games on the main databases, and it sometimes goes unmentioned, including not being discussed in Cyrus Lakdawala's 'The Alekhine Defence: Move by Move'.   Now Black has two main moves, of which the former is by some margin the most common:   F1:  3...e6   F2:  3...Nb6  There are two other moves which don't drop the knight, as we'll now see. }
3... c6
{ was seen in Richmond-Smith, where White made a decent case for  4.d4  d6  5.a3!?  . Even stronger, though, is Simon's }
4. Nc3
{ when we saw in the notes to that aforementioned encounter how White might meet the rather meek  4...Nb6?!  . Black has two stronger choices: }
4... Nb4 5. Bc4
{ Taking full advantage of the early queen deployment and forcing Black into a sub-optimal weakening after all: }
5... e6 6. Bb3
{ Already White can claim a pleasant edge; d4 is on the way, as is Qg3/ g4 and Nf3, and there's not even a rush to improve the black knight with a3. Here Black probably must expand and break out: }
6... c5 7. Qg4 { To counter the possibility of ...c4. } 7... N8c6 8. Nf3
{ White continues to enjoy the easier development, with a3 now a definite threat, as is Nb5: for example, }
8... d5 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. O-O
{ More simple chess, tucking the king away before going a3 or looking to arrange d4. Black can obtain a central bind, but not equalize: }
10... e5 11. Qg3 Be6 12. Ne4
{ White increases the pressure against c5 @@StartBracket@@partly why the knight didn't instead venture to b5@@EndBracket@@, e5 and e6, and may even retain the bishops with Ba4 followed by a3. }
