[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine F1: 3...e6"]
[Black "F1: 3...e6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 e6
{ Black's most sensible and by far his most popular move, keeping the knight in the centre. It's certainly logical, but won't please all Alekhine players who are, after all, used to being able to activate their light-squared bishop after 3. d4 d6. }
4. Nc3
{ Simon's choice and a good one, challenging the knight on  d5  . White has actually tried quite a few alternatives, of which  4.d4  c5!  gives Black decent counterplay, as does  4.Qg3  d6  . }
4... Nxc3
{ Playing as Black tends to without the moves Qf3 and ...e6 inserted. } 5. dxc3
{ 5.Qxc3  isn't totally silly, but the text opens the d-file and prepares Bf4 followed by O-O-O. Note that White's king should be especially safe on c1 with an extra pawn in the shield wall in front of him. }
5... Nc6 6. Qg3
{ Overprotecting e5 while pressing on g7 in approved fashion. White can also just go  6.Bf4  , and if  6...g5!?  7.Bg3  h5  8.h3  . }
6... f6
{ Black chips away at the bridgehead, but this is a rather risky method, exposing his kingside to further attack. }
7. Nf3 { Developing while maintaining White's advanced presence on e5. } 7...
fxe5 8. Nxe5
{ Simple and strong, while also threatening the cheeky but strong Ng6! } 8...
Nxe5 9. Qxe5 d6 10. Qg3
{ Dropping the queen back to its favourite square and leaving White with a pleasant edge. He will complete development with Bd3 @@StartBracket@@threatening Bxh7@@EndBracket@@, Bg5 and O-O-O, and an advance of Harry may also prove awkward for Black. For example: }
10... Bd7 11. Bd3 Qf6 { Covering against the threat. } 12. Bg5 Qf7 13. O-O-O
{ White is fully mobilized and ready to go Be4 or even f4 and can you spot why Black can't easily complete development with ...Be7 and ...O-O? }
13... Be7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Bxh7
{ Boom! There goes a pawn, after which White will drop the bishop back to e4, possibly followed by arranging to advance the kingside majority. }
*

