1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 e6
{ Black's most sensible and by far his most popular move, keeping the knight in the centre. It's certainly logical, but won't please all Alekhine players who are, after all, used to being able to activate their light-squared bishop after 3. d4 d6. }
4. Nc3
{ Simon's choice and a good one, challenging the knight on  d5  . White has actually tried quite a few alternatives, of which  4.d4  c5!  gives Black decent counterplay, as does  4.Qg3  d6  . }
4... Nb4
{ leads to both sides losing time. Time, you might ask? Yes,  5.Qe4  N8c6  followed by ...d5 gives Black too much play @@StartBracket@@  6.a3?  fails to  6...d5  7.exd6  f5!  , overloading the queen@@EndBracket@@, so White must retreat: }
5. Qd1
{ White is now set to expand with d4 and a3, and the bridgehead on e5 should offset the loss of time involved: }
5... N8c6 6. a3 Nd5
{ was seen in Zunker-Gruettner, Giessen 1991, when if you quite like a small space advantage  7.Nxd5  exd5  8.d4  d6  9.Nf3  would be sensible. White can also retain the tension. }
7. Nf3 { with two possibilities } 7... d6 8. exd6
{ forces Black to recapture with the bishop, to avoid doubled d-pawns or a nasty intermezzo on c7: }
8... Bxd6 9. Ne4
{ White pursues the bishop-pair, while also preparing to develop with Bc4 and d4. }
9... e5 10. Bc4 Nf6 11. d3
{ Again, a slightly modest development, but now Bg5 and Qe2 may follow with some pressure or   11...Nxe4  12.dxe4  O-O  13.Be3  when White's development is slightly the easier. He may castle on either side and a kingside expansion isn't off the cards, not least with  13...Bg4  14.h3  Bh5  15.g4!?  Bg6  16.Qd3  followed by going long. }
