1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 e6
{ Black's most sensible and by far his most popular move, keeping the knight in the centre. It's certainly logical, but won't please all Alekhine players who are, after all, used to being able to activate their light-squared bishop after 3. d4 d6. }
4. Nc3
{ Other knight moves make little sense.  4...Nb6  doesn't even need to be met with  5.a4  , since 5. d4 leaves White with an improved version of Line F2, and }
4... Ne7 5. d4 Nbc6 6. Be3
{ was quite an aggressive and attractive set-up for White in Nurlygayanov-Tsol, Alushta 2008. Everything is in place to go long and after }
6... Ng6 7. O-O-O Be7 8. g3 d5 9. exd6 cxd6 10. h4
{ Black was already coming under pressure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine F2 3...Nb6"]
[Black "F2: 3...Nb6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... a5 { Prudently halting White's a-pawn in its tracks. } 5. d4
{ Only now that the b5-square has been slightly weakened does White advance in the centre. }
5... Nc6
{ Alekhine players often like to be quite creative with their knights @@StartBracket@@unsurprisingly perhaps considering their first move@@EndBracket@@, and this move begins to strike back in the centre. }
6. Be3
{ The most active way of dealing with the threat to d4, although playing as White has done without a4 and ...a5 inserted, i.e.   6.c3  , is likely a decent alternative. }
6... d6 { The natural Alekhine central counter. } 7. Bb5
{ Once again, a fine post for the bishop, as well as one which makes full use of the queen being on f3. }
7... Bd7
{ We've followed the game Rajkovic-Cvetkovic, Knic 2019, where White retreated with  8.Qe2  to retain control and facilitate Nf3. That makes good sense, as does developing the queen's knight: }
8. Nc3
{ Now that White has sufficient control of d5 he threatens a pretty disruptive e6 sacrifice. }
8... e6 9. O-O-O
{ Olé! This is far from forced, but is White's most aggressive continuation and also sets a small trap. }
9... d5
{ Prudently closing the position to reach a French structure.   9...dxe5?  10.dxe5  leaves Black in trouble down the d-file. White is ready to go Ne4 or obtain far too much for the e5-pawn:  10...Nxe5  11.Qg3  Nc6  avoids being cleaned up by Bxb6, but after  12.Nf3  there just isn't a good move for Black, White being all set to exchange on b6, then c6 and then crash through with Ne5. }
10. Nge2
{ Completing development and also offering some support to the knight on c3 in the event of ...Bb4. The position isn't completely clear, but White may well be slightly better.   Not only could Qg3 and Nf4 occur, but White is all set to go 11. h4, creating the possibility of Rh3, as well as intending h5 and if ...h6, White may well obtain too strong an initiative after g4 followed by arranging f4 as the pawn-roller just keeps rolling. }
*

