{ Only now that the b5-square has been slightly weakened does White advance in the centre. }
5... Nc6
{ Alekhine players often like to be quite creative with their knights @@StartBracket@@unsurprisingly perhaps considering their first move@@EndBracket@@, and this move begins to strike back in the centre. }
6. Be3
{ The most active way of dealing with the threat to d4, although playing as White has done without a4 and ...a5 inserted, i.e.   6.c3  , is likely a decent alternative. }
6... d6 { The natural Alekhine central counter. } 7. Bb5
{ Once again, a fine post for the bishop, as well as one which makes full use of the queen being on f3. }
7... Bd7
{ We've followed the game Rajkovic-Cvetkovic, Knic 2019, where White retreated with  8.Qe2  to retain control and facilitate Nf3. That makes good sense, as does developing the queen's knight: }
8. Nc3
{ Now that White has sufficient control of d5 he threatens a pretty disruptive e6 sacrifice. }
8... Nb4 { counters against c2, but White can actually ignore the threat: } 9.
e6 fxe6 10. Nh3
{ Suddenly Ng5 is a large threat and White enjoys promising compensation }
10... c6 11. Ng5 Qc8
{ Black creates an escape square while still attacking b5 and c2, but even here White enjoys decent play and compensation: }
12. Bd3 Nxd3+ 13. cxd3
{ Now the king can't go to d8 without dropping the rook in the corner, so just how will Black unravel and complete development? That's not at all obvious. Meanwhile White can go O-O and increase the pressure through such moves as h4-h5 and Nce4. }
*

