8. Nc3
{ Now that White has sufficient control of d5 he threatens a pretty disruptive e6 sacrifice. }
8... Nb4 { counters against c2, but White can actually ignore the threat: } 9.
e6 fxe6 10. Nh3
{ Suddenly Ng5 is a large threat and White enjoys promising compensation }
10... Nxc2+ 11. Kd2 Nxa1 12. Ng5 { is a winning attack: } 12... Bxb5 13. Qf7+
Kd7 14. Qxe6+ Ke8 15. Nxb5
{ Now Rxa1 is one threat, Rc1 a more subtle but vicious one, angling for ...c6; Ne4, and Qf7+ Kd7; Qf5+ and Ne6 is also in the position, for example:   15...c6  16.Qf7+!  Kd7  17.Qf5+  Ke8  18.Ne6  when White is winning by force, coming out a piece ahead after  18...Qc8  19.Nbc7+  Kd7  20.Nxa8  Qxa8  21.Nxf8+  Kc7  22.Ne6+  Kb8  23.Rxa1 }
