1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... a5 { Prudently halting White's a-pawn in its tracks. } 5. d4
{ Only now that the b5-square has been slightly weakened does White advance in the centre. }
5... Nc6
{ Alekhine players often like to be quite creative with their knights @@StartBracket@@unsurprisingly perhaps considering their first move@@EndBracket@@, and this move begins to strike back in the centre. }
6. Be3
{ The most active way of dealing with the threat to d4, although playing as White has done without a4 and ...a5 inserted, i.e.   6.c3  , is likely a decent alternative. }
6... g6 { rather asks for Harry: } 7. h4 h5 8. Nh3
{ Hurrying the knight into play, even though Black can castle in time to deal with the pressure against f7: }
8... Bg7 9. Ng5 { 9.Nf4  d6  10.e6!?  also deserves attention. } 9... O-O 10.
g4
{ Calmer play with  10.c3  is very possible too if you prefer, but it's hard to resist advancing Garry and in a manner which is likely to make any opponent rather alarmed. }
10... d6 11. e6
{ Continuing to fight for the initiative and not  11.gxh5?  dxe5  when that would belong to Black.   11...fxe6  12.Qe4  The position is very messy, but you'd have to want to take White in practice, especially with the element of surprise involved. Clearly Qxg6 is a huge threat and gxh5 is also on the cards.  12...Qe8!   12...Rf6  13.gxh5  e5  14.dxe5  seems safe enough for White, since now  14...Bf5?  15.Qg2  gives White a clearly superior version of the 12...Qe8 line, thanks to the hanging rook on f6 and  15...Nxe5  16.hxg6  followed by h5.  13.gxh5  e5!  14.Qxg6!   Offering a queen exchange, but likely a wiser choice than ceding the initiative with  14.dxe5  Bf5  15.Qg2  Nb4  .  14...Qxg6  15.hxg6  exd4  16.Bd2  The position remains completely unclear, with Black enjoying a central pawn preponderance and White a mobile kingside majority. Clearly he'd like to go h5-h6 and note too that ...d3 can be met by c3 or even possibly an exchange sacrifice, like Bxd3 Bxb2; Bc3. }
