1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... a5 { Prudently halting White's a-pawn in its tracks. } 5. d4
{ Without the a-pawns having advanced, Black has also pushed his d-pawn straightaway: }
5... d5 6. Bd3
{ already looks rather pleasant for White. There's no central pressure and how is Black going to get his queen's bishop outside the pawn chain, let alone create any play? It's also not hard to imagine White quickly generating some pressure with Nh3-g5 or Ne2-f4 in conjunction with Qg3: }
6... e6 7. Ne2 c5 8. c3
{ The position resembles the Advance French, but with White's queen actively placed. It will likely be nudged across to g3 and it's even possible to sacrifice the a-pawn to increase White's lead in development }
8... Bd7 9. Qg3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nxa4 11. O-O
{ White will continue with Nbc3 and may then advance the f-pawn or prefer, at least initially, to rely on piece-play, as with Bg5 and/or Nf4-h5. }
*

