1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... a5 { Prudently halting White's a-pawn in its tracks. } 5. d4
{ Only now that the b5-square has been slightly weakened does White advance in the centre. }
5... d6
{ is a better move with the d-pawn, and was advocated by Dzindzichashvili and Tillis without any further analysis, when White probably does best to retain the tension: }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Bb5 { Exploiting the downside to ...a5. } 7... Bd7 8. e6
{ This isn't White's only decent move here, but is the most forcing, as well as tempting. Clearly Black can't capture with the bishop and walk into a fork, so he is forced to retard his development: }
8... fxe6 9. Be3 g6 10. Nh3
{ This seems stronger than immediately lobbing Harry forwards. White threatens Ng5 while not rushing to commit the king @@StartBracket@@it will most likely go long, but may also head to f1 or even g1 in some circumstances@@EndBracket@@. }
