[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... d6
{ creates a retreat square for the knight, but White should not mind being encouraged to push ahead on the queenside: }
5. a5 N6d7
{ When did you last see Black make four of his first moves with his king's knight? }
6. e6
{ Our favourite disruptive pawn sacrifice and this is why White was happy to get his pawn all the way to a5. Now Black should accept the gambit: }
6... fxe6 7. a6
{ White continues to find ways to keep creating threats and clearly now Black must close the long diagonal: }
7... Nc6
{ 7...Ne5  8.Qe4  only seems to help White, maintaining the pressure while intending to develop the pieces with d4, Nf3 and Bd3. }
8. c3
{ Keeping Black out of d4 makes sense, although  8.Nh3!?  isn't ridiculous, and if  8...Nd4  9.Qd1  . }
8... Nce5 9. Qe3
{ Here rather than h3 for the queen to threaten a central advance with d4 @@StartBracket@@or even f4@@EndBracket@@. White will then be able to go Bd3 and Nf3 and we quite like his compensation in this rather unusual position, with Black struggling to untangle his kingside: for example,   9...bxa6  10.d4  Nf7  11.Nf3  g6  12.Nbd2  . This side-steps the slightly disruptive  12.h4  Bh6  , but White still wants to get an advance of Harry in, as well as just play against Black's weakened light squares after Bxa6.   9...Nf6?!  10.d4  Nf7  11.axb7  Bxb7  12.Qxe6  favourably regains the pawn, with Black's light squares weakened and  12...Qd7  13.Qb3!?  a disruptive retreat, possibly followed by c4 and Nc3 or just Nf3.   9...c5!?  might be best according to the engines, but even here White can hardly be unhappy.   10.f4  Nf7  11.Qxe6  is far from ridiculous and it's also possible to send the king's knight into the fray  10.Nh3!  g6  11.d4  cxd4  12.cxd4  Nc6  13.Ng5!?  . Black can prevent the knight settling on e6, but not equalize  13...Bh6  14.Qxe6  Bxg5  . White has acquired the two bishops and need not fear any discoveries or even the loss of d4,  15.--  Nxd4?  16.Qe4  White's superior development is quick to count, with the threat of axb7 renewed, not to mention ideas of Bc4, Ra3 and  16...Nc6  17.Bb5  . }
*

