{ White continues to find ways to keep creating threats and clearly now Black must close the long diagonal: }
7... d5 8. axb7 Bxb7 9. Qh3
{ places the queen on a fine square. White isn't so much keen to go Qxe6, as get in Nf3-g5 or create threats with d4 and Bd3: for example, }
9... e5 10. Nf3 Nc6
{ prepares to counter  11.Ng5  with  11...Nd4!  , but after } 11. Bb5
{ White's threat of Bxc6 Bxc6; Qe6 and Ng5 is far from trivial to deal with. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine F2 3...Nb6"]
[Black "F2: 3...Nb6  #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Qf3 Nb6
{ This is, of course, where the knight retreats to after 3. c4, but here White should be happy to see the knight retreating from the centre.  That said, the line was advocated for Black by Roman Dzindzichashvili and Bryan Tillis in their 'Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises' course. }
4. a4
{ We've only managed to track down one game with this advance, but we rather like it, continuing not to give Black any respite.  4.Qg3  d6  5.f4  and  4.b3  have also had their adherents, while White's most popular choice in the limited practice thus far has been  4.d4  , which we'll closely compared with what now follows. }
4... d6
{ creates a retreat square for the knight, but White should not mind being encouraged to push ahead on the queenside: }
5. a5 N6d7
{ When did you last see Black make four of his first moves with his king's knight? }
6. e6
{ Our favourite disruptive pawn sacrifice and this is why White was happy to get his pawn all the way to a5. Now Black should accept the gambit: }
6... Ne5
{ can be met by  7.exf7+  Nxf7  8.d4  with a pleasant edge, but sliding the queen diagonally forwards is tempting: }
7. Qe4
{ Now  7...fxe6  8.a6  retains good compensation and the other capture allows White much more than that: }
7... Bxe6 8. d4 Ng4 { The only square not to lose serious material. } 9. Qxb7
{ Black's light squares begin to creak and this seems even stronger than  9.a6  . White may only have his queen in play, breaking all the rules, but he enjoys the much more harmonious set-up }
9... Nd7 10. Nc3
{ The simple threat is Nb5 and there just isn't a great way for Black to prevent that. He can avoid a disaster on c7, but losing his a-pawn to do so when White's a-pawn is already up on b5 can only make for excellent news for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch Defence, as played by the great strategist on a number of occasions. }
2. Nf3
{ This simple choice makes a lot of sense, as Black now normally opts for  2...d6  or  2...e5  and, of course, the latter transposes to our Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4 repertoire, where we advocated meeting 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 with 3. Bc4 . }
2... f5
{ The infamous Colorado Countergambit. It's far from sound and an advance White should welcome - but don't go chasing that rook in the corner!  Instead, Black's main options are:   G1:  2...d6   G2:  2...Nf6   2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  is a position we hope you recognize! We covered this and then  4.Be2  at the start of our Scandinavian coverage.   2...e6?!  3.d4  d5  4.e5  may also seem familiar, especially to users of Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. This is an Advance French where Black has sub-optimally obstructed his f-pawn, leaving White with a pleasant edge after 5. c3 or 5. Bd3.   2...g6  3.d4  Bg7  is a strange type of Modern and  4.Nc3  d6  transposes to a position we'll consider in Line G1. }
3. exf5 { Needless to say the proof of the pudding lies in the eating. } 3...
d5 4. Bb5
{ Simple chess @@StartBracket@@4.d4 is also strong@@EndBracket@@, as White is happy to return the extra pawn to exploit the rather large hole Black has kindly created on e5. Instead,  4.Nh4?  is what Black is hoping for when he can go  4...Nh6  or even  4...e5!?  5.Qh5+  g6!  6.fxg6  Nf6  7.g7+  Nxh5  8.gxh8Q  Qxh4  with a right mess. }
4... Bxf5
{ 4...Qd6  fails to keep White out of e5:  5.d4  Bxf5  6.Ne5  and we've transposed to our main line. }
5. Ne5 { Upping the ante and, well, why not? } 5... Qd6
{ White has scored extremely well after this, but unfortunately for Black his other ways of dealing with the threat on c6 are little better. }
6. d4 Nf6 7. O-O
{ Simple chess, housing the king safely while keeping all White's options open. Bf4, Nd2-f3 or even c4 may follow. }
7... Nd7 8. Bf4
{ By no means White's only good move, but one which retains piece control of e5. }
8... Ndxe5 9. Bxe5 Qg6 10. Qf3
{ This seems even stronger than  10.Bxc7  . White now has ideas of Nd2 and c4, as well as Bxc7, will meet ...O-O-O with Bxc6 and ...Be4 will now run into Qh3.   In short, White's advantage is a large one and it's already hard to find even a playable continuation for Black. Just don't swipe the d-pawn too quickly! }
10... e6
{ 10...Be4?!  11.Qh3  Bf5  doesn't lead to a repetition, but rather  12.Bxc6+  bxc6  13.Qb3  followed by a timely Qb7 or just Nd2, Rfe1 and c4.   10...Bxc2  hopes for:   11.Qxd5??  Be4  , but White can do much, much better than that:   11.Nd2  Bf5  12.Rac1  . Now there's pressure against c6 and d5, as well as c7, and all the while Black's kingside pieces are rooted on their start squares. }
11. Qc3 Kd7 12. Nd2
{ Black is clinging on for now, but will do well to avoid for too much longer making further major concessions, with Nb3-c5/a5 and Rfe1-e3 on their way. }
*

