1. e4 Nc6
{ Instead,  2.d4  allows Black reasonable enough play after  2...d5  or  2...e5  , but if you really do want to explore something uncharted, you may wish to examine }
2. b4
{ We could only find one game with this gambit on the databases @@StartBracket@@it has also featured in a few Palliser-Moulton blitz games@@EndBracket@@, so it should come as quite a shock to a Nimzowitsch player and wasn't mentioned by 1...Nc6 guru Christian Bauer in his recent work 'The Modernized Nimzovich Defence 1. e4 Nc6!'.  Objectively, the gambit isn't quite sound, but fans of open lines and big centers shouldn't be too unhappy: }
2... Nxb4 3. d4 d6 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3
{ White's unhurried approach will not be unfamiliar to fans of the Wing Gambit against the Sicilian.   He may continue with Nge2 and O-O or simply expand in Austrian Attack fashion with f4, Nf3, O-O and surely reasonable enough practical compensation? }
