[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Not least in our coverage of the Remaining Fianchettoes, we've pretty much looked at all Black's options and will draw the line at the likes of  1...f6  and  1...a5  . Sometimes you just have to enjoy a strong center after  2.d4  and play chess from a position of strength! }
1... e6 2. d4
{ normally leads, of course, to the French, although Black can also enter Owen's waters here. We should mention as well }
2... c5
{ Now  3.d5  leads to quite a pleasant advantage for White and a cramped, inferior version of a Benoni for Black after  3...exd5  4.exd5  d6  5.Nc3  . If you prefer, White can also maintain the tension }
3. c3
{ Black usually responds with  3...d5  when after  4.e5  we're back into the Advance French, as covered in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Otherwise, White should just enjoy a nice central space advantage: }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Simple chess, maintaining White's proud center, although those with some experience of the c3 Sicilian may prefer  4.e5  . }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ White's center is secure and even bagging the bishop-pair shouldn't enable Black to equalize: }
5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nb4 7. O-O Nxd3 8. Qxd3
{ White's fine light-squared bishop has gone, but he leads in development and controls the center. Left to his own devices, d5 might well follow, which explains why Black has usually now headed for French-type waters:   8...d5  9.e5  Ne4  10.Nbd2!  Once again, White's simplest and likely strongest path.  10...Nxd2  11.Bxd2  . The position resembles a French or 3. Bb5+ Sicilian where Black has been left with his light-squared bishop. That is, of course, traditionally a bad piece in this structure and White must have an edge with his extra space and far superior development.  One good policy could be to combine play down the c-file with a kingside advance: for example,  11...Qb6  12.Rfc1  Bd7  13.Rc3!?  Bb5  14.Qe3  . Now Qf4 and Ng5 is one idea, h4 another, and exchanges merely serve to exacerbate Black's lack of counterplay:  14...Bb4?  15.Rb3  Bxd2  16.Qxd2  Black can handle the threat of a4, but we'd be surprised if he could also keep White at bay on the kingside after Ng5 h6; Nh3 followed by Rg3 and Nf4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #10"]
