1. e4
{ Not least in our coverage of the Remaining Fianchettoes, we've pretty much looked at all Black's options and will draw the line at the likes of  1...f6  and  1...a5  . Sometimes you just have to enjoy a strong center after  2.d4  and play chess from a position of strength! }
1... e6 2. d4
{ normally leads, of course, to the French, although Black can also enter Owen's waters here. We should mention as well }
2... c5
{ Now  3.d5  leads to quite a pleasant advantage for White and a cramped, inferior version of a Benoni for Black after  3...exd5  4.exd5  d6  5.Nc3  . If you prefer, White can also maintain the tension }
3. c3
{ Black usually responds with  3...d5  when after  4.e5  we're back into the Advance French, as covered in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Otherwise, White should just enjoy a nice central space advantage: }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Simple chess, maintaining White's proud center, although those with some experience of the c3 Sicilian may prefer  4.e5  . }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ White's center is secure and even bagging the bishop-pair shouldn't enable Black to equalize: }
5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+
{ has been almost as popular, but we're not sure why. Now  7.Nc3  d5  8.e5  Ne4  isn't totally clear, although White must have decent compensation after  9.O-O!  , and there's a simple route to a pleasant advantage }
7. Nbd2 d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. O-O Nxd2 10. Bxd2
{ This is simply a promising version of an Advance French, since d4 is secure @@StartBracket@@ Be3 will be next up @@EndBracket@@, leaving White able to expand with a3 and b4 or on the kingside, such as with Be3, h4 and Ng5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction  #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Not least in our coverage of the Remaining Fianchettoes, we've pretty much looked at all Black's options and will draw the line at the likes of  1...f6  and  1...a5  . Sometimes you just have to enjoy a strong center after  2.d4  and play chess from a position of strength! }
1... e6 2. d4
{ normally leads, of course, to the French, although Black can also enter Owen's waters here. We should mention as well }
2... c5
{ Now  3.d5  leads to quite a pleasant advantage for White and a cramped, inferior version of a Benoni for Black after  3...exd5  4.exd5  d6  5.Nc3  . If you prefer, White can also maintain the tension }
3. c3
{ Black usually responds with  3...d5  when after  4.e5  we're back into the Advance French, as covered in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Otherwise, White should just enjoy a nice central space advantage: }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Simple chess, maintaining White's proud center, although those with some experience of the c3 Sicilian may prefer  4.e5  . }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ White's center is secure and even bagging the bishop-pair shouldn't enable Black to equalize: }
5... d5
{ is the main alternative, but this is just going to be a good version of a French Tarrasch for White, as his knight isn't slightly clogging up his position on d2: }
6. e5 Nd7 7. O-O Be7
{ This would be a pure Tarrasch if White now went  8.Nbd2  , but instead he can maintain the tension and play for queenside expansion: }
8. a3 a5 9. Re1 O-O 10. Bc2
{ Having been prevented from expanding with b4, White switches his attention to the other flank. He can now go Qd3 and do observe too how Black doesn't have his usual counterplay with ...Qb6 and ...f6. He can push the f-pawn, but not equalize }
10... f6
{ 10...Re8  11.Be3  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  was a slower approach from Black in Prie-Dragomirescu, European Championship, Aix les Bains 2011, where White exploited his free hand to gradually edge forwards:  13.g3  cxd4  14.cxd4  Nf8  15.Rc1  Rc8  16.h4  when Ng5 was one idea and h4-h5 in conjunction with Nh2-g4 another strong and thematic one. }
