1. e4
{ Not least in our coverage of the Remaining Fianchettoes, we've pretty much looked at all Black's options and will draw the line at the likes of  1...f6  and  1...a5  . Sometimes you just have to enjoy a strong center after  2.d4  and play chess from a position of strength! }
1... e6 2. d4
{ normally leads, of course, to the French, although Black can also enter Owen's waters here. We should mention as well }
2... c5
{ Now  3.d5  leads to quite a pleasant advantage for White and a cramped, inferior version of a Benoni for Black after  3...exd5  4.exd5  d6  5.Nc3  . If you prefer, White can also maintain the tension }
3. c3
{ Black usually responds with  3...d5  when after  4.e5  we're back into the Advance French, as covered in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. Otherwise, White should just enjoy a nice central space advantage: }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Simple chess, maintaining White's proud center, although those with some experience of the c3 Sicilian may prefer  4.e5  . }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ White's center is secure and even bagging the bishop-pair shouldn't enable Black to equalize: }
5... d6 6. O-O Be7 { does nothing to challenge White's central plus: } 7. Re1
{ Facilitating Nbd2-f1-g3, as well as a timely e4-e5. } 7... e5 8. d5 Nb8 9. a4
{ This left White in control and with a very pleasant advantage indeed in Grischuk-Anton Guijarro, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020, where he was quick to take over: }
9... Nbd7 10. a5 Rb8 11. b4
{ 11...O-O  12.Na3  a6  13.Nc4  Re8  14.h3  cxb4  15.cxb4  Nf8  16.Be3  Black has been completely outplayed, White having made dream Classical King's Indian gains on the queenside, and without allowing any counterplay. One strong idea is Ba7 Ra8; Bb6 Qd7; Bc2!, winning material after Ba4. }
