[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch G1: 2...d6"]
[Black "G1: 2...d6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... g6 { The modern main line, taking play into Pircesque waters. } 5. Bb5
{ Aggressive yet simple development. White threatens d5 and so interferes with Black's own development schemes.  A great many other moves have been played, of which  5.Be3  Bg7  6.Qd2  may appeal to those with some experience of the 150 Attack against the Pirc. }
5... a6 { Black should deal with the pin so. } 6. Bxc6+
{ Naturally White wastes no time, damaging Black's structure while securing a handy enough lead in development. }
6... bxc6 7. O-O
{ Going long isn't completely ridiculous despite the b-file being open, but the king will be very safe on g1 and White is now well placed to look for early expansion in the centre with e5. }
7... Bg7 8. e5
{ Good cases can be made too for both  8.h3  and  8.Re1  , but White has scored quite well with this immediate advance, which also appears to have been slightly underestimated in Bauer's book, and it's always nice to place the opponent under a bit of early pressure. }
8... Nd5
{ Black usually leaps forward so, Alekhine style.   8...Nd7  9.Qe2  O-O  can be met by 10. Re1 followed by Bg5 or even  10.e6!?  fxe6  11.Ng5  , which regained the pawn with a definite edge in Euwe-Bogoljubow, 8th matchgame, Karlsbad 1941.   8...dxe5?  9.Nxe5  already leaves Black without a great way of defending his c-pawn, not least with Qf3 and Bf4 on their way, not to mention  9...Bb7?  10.Na4!  , clamping down on those queenside weaknesses with a strong bind. }
9. Ne4
{ An important move, keeping pieces on. White also moves the knight closer to the kingside @@StartBracket@@or even c5 if Black makes a rather positionally misguided exchange on e5@@EndBracket@@, while freeing the c-pawn for action. }
9... O-O 10. c4
{ Driving the black knight back to a somewhat sub-optimal location is undoubtedly White's most aggressive and also most principled continuation. }
10... Nb6 11. b3
{ Shoring up b3 and continuing to play against the black knight. White may now develop with Bf4 and Qc1, looking to go Bh6 with attacking chances, or he might even consider Ba3 and Re1, which is designed to keep Black's counterplay under control. }
11... Bg4 12. h3
{ Wasting no time challenging the bishop as the e5-pawn can be gambited. }
12... Bf5 13. Qe2
{ White's centre is secure and Ng3, Bf4 and Qe3 on their way, hence Black's next. }
13... c5 14. dxc5
{ Our standard mechanism of dealing with a ...c5 hit in many lines. } 14... Nd7
{ Once again, Black tries to exploit the pressure down the long diagonal, but White has a few strong continuations here, including developing with tempo. }
15. cxd6 exd6 16. Bg5 Qe8 17. Ng3
{ Black's structure was about to get shredded on f5, which simply meant that he was in a lot of trouble in Shirov-Bachmann, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020, and, yes, the remedy would be worse than the disease:   17...Be6?  18.exd6!  Bxa1  19.Rxa1  cxd6  20.Bh6  . White will regain the exchange @@StartBracket@@if he wishes@@EndBracket@@, leaving him a pawn to the good and with clear targets in the shape of d6 and the black king. }
*

