{ An important move, keeping pieces on. White also moves the knight closer to the kingside @@StartBracket@@or even c5 if Black makes a rather positionally misguided exchange on e5@@EndBracket@@, while freeing the c-pawn for action. }
9... O-O 10. c4
{ Driving the black knight back to a somewhat sub-optimal location is undoubtedly White's most aggressive and also most principled continuation. }
10... Nb6 11. b3
{ Shoring up b3 and continuing to play against the black knight. White may now develop with Bf4 and Qc1, looking to go Bh6 with attacking chances, or he might even consider Ba3 and Re1, which is designed to keep Black's counterplay under control. }
11... Bg4 12. h3
{ Wasting no time challenging the bishop as the e5-pawn can be gambited. }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 dxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Rb1
{ leaves Black a pawn to the good, but also suffering and clearly worse. His knight is far from happy and while  15...Nd7  prevents Nc5, it doesn't prevent White from obtaining a strong initiative with simple yet strong improving moves:  16.Bh6  Bg7  17.Bxg7  Kxg7  18.Rbd1  Qc8  19.Rfe1  .   Clearly Black is under some pressure, with the weak c6-pawn arguably the least of his worries. White may simply go Nc3 or even try for more with h4-h5. }
