{ White wants to go Nc3-d5 and while Black can prevent that, he should remain slightly worse:  16...Qe8  17.Nc3  e6  18.b4  Qc6  19.f3  .   This unbalanced position isn't completely clear, but White's ability to overprotect c5 and so force through b5 should leave him definitely for choice.   16...Qe8  17.Nc3  Qc6  18.Nd5  Rfe8  19.Bxe5!  when the tactics work for White:  19...e6   19...f6  20.Bc3  e6  21.Ne3  Qxc5  22.b4  Qe7  23.a4  leaves White's queenside pawn roller the dominant feature of the position, in part because Black can't obtain any play without allowing an exchange of bishops and/or creating a hole on d5.  20.Bxg7  exd5  21.cxd5  and White will emerge a clear pawn ahead, as with  21...Qxd5  22.Rxd5  Rxe2  23.Re5 }
