{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... g6 { The modern main line, taking play into Pircesque waters. } 5. Bb5
{ Aggressive yet simple development. White threatens d5 and so interferes with Black's own development schemes.  A great many other moves have been played, of which  5.Be3  Bg7  6.Qd2  may appeal to those with some experience of the 150 Attack against the Pirc. }
5... Bd7 6. e5 { seizes a strong initiative: } 6... dxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Qe2
{ or just  8.Bf4  then 9. Qe2 . } 8... Bg7 9. Bf4
{ This is a dream set-up for White, as in Martinez Alcantara-Lamard, Barcelona 2018. The bridgehead on e5 divides Black's position in two, with all the play belonging to White with O-O-O and h3 and g4 next up. }
