{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... Bg4
{ is Black's traditional approach, after which he'd quite like to counter on the light squares with ...e6 and ...d5. Just like in our main line with  4...g6  , White can pin straight away or simply bolster  d4  while taking a step closer to queenside castling: }
5. Be3
{ White simply wants to kick the bishop with h3 and there just doesn't appear to be a fully satisfactory method of development for Black: }
5... e6 { is the main line and Black's most popular try: } 6. h3
{ sees White sticking to the plan: } 6... Bh5 7. g4
{ Annexing space.  7.d5  is also strong. } 7... Bg6
{ Here White has often gone  8.Nd2  , but he can do much better than defend e4: }
8. d5
{ This seizes a strong initiative, in part because Black's bishop is a target and he is also rather vulnerable to Bb5+ ideas: }
8... exd5 9. exd5
{ White's options of Bb5+, g5 and even Nd4 and f4 mean that Black already faces serious difficulties }
9... Nb4 10. Bb5+ { Ever a key move in these 2... d6 Nimzowitsch lines. } 10...
c6 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Nd4
{ Intensifying the pressure while freeing Freddie  12...Rc8  13.f4!  Be4  14.O-O  . White threatens g5 and enjoyed a tremendous initiative in Miles-Mestel, Birmingham 1975. }
