[White "Nimzowitsch G1: 2...d6"]
[Black "G1: 2...d6  #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... Bg4
{ is Black's traditional approach, after which he'd quite like to counter on the light squares with ...e6 and ...d5. Just like in our main line with  4...g6  , White can pin straight away or simply bolster  d4  while taking a step closer to queenside castling: }
5. Be3
{ White simply wants to kick the bishop with h3 and there just doesn't appear to be a fully satisfactory method of development for Black: }
5... e5
{ prevents White from simply rolling forwards with h3, but does nothing to prevent our other favourite plan, the pin: }
6. Bb5 exd4 7. Qxd4
{ Once again, White refuses to fear doubled f-pawns @@StartBracket@@and the king's rook would love to enjoy a fine post on g1, gazing at g7@@EndBracket@@, while simply intending to blast ahead with O-O-O and e5: }
7... Be7 8. h3
{ White is even happy to offer a tempo to tempt an exchange on f3. } 8... Bd7
{ 8...Be6?!  9.e5!  is awkward for Black, whether he retreats and allows Bxc6 bxc6; exd6 or  9...dxe5  10.Qxd8+  Rxd8  11.Nxe5  Bd7  12.Nxd7  Rxd7  13.Ke2!  when White enjoys a lovely endgame advantage with Rhd1 and/or Bxc6 bxc6; Na4 on their way.  Likewise,  8...Bxf3?!  9.gxf3  O-O  10.Qd2!?  Ne5  11.Be2  is probably best avoided by Black with O-O-O, f4 and Rhg1 set to follow. }
9. Bxc6
{ Simple chess. White gives up the bishop-pair to avoid losing time and reduce Black's options for counterplay. }
9... Bxc6 10. O-O-O O-O 11. g4
{ This sounded the charge and with Black a little passively placed in Delchev-Mestrovic, Zadar 2002. White will simply go g5 then h4, Rhg1 if needed, and h5 or if ... Nh5, Qc4 or Qd3 should be fairly strong, preparing Nd4, Rhg1, Qe2 to hit the knight and f4. }
