{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... Bg4
{ is Black's traditional approach, after which he'd quite like to counter on the light squares with ...e6 and ...d5. Just like in our main line with  4...g6  , White can pin straight away or simply bolster  d4  while taking a step closer to queenside castling: }
5. Be3
{ White simply wants to kick the bishop with h3 and there just doesn't appear to be a fully satisfactory method of development for Black: }
5... e5
{ prevents White from simply rolling forwards with h3, but does nothing to prevent our other favourite plan, the pin: }
6. Bb5 Nd7
{ was once a great favourite of the Bosnian IM Zvonimir Mestrovic's, he of 4. Be2 and 5. h4 Pirc fame. However, once White seizes space, Black's game quickly becomes difficult: }
7. d5 Ncb8 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4
{ A strong advance, refusing to fear the upcoming closure of the kingside, presuming that Black doesn't want his bishop driven back to h7 instead: }
10... h5 11. g5 Be7 12. Nd2
{ Beginning a powerful regrouping; White simply wants to lay siege to h5. }
12... c6 13. Be2 Nb6 14. Nf1 cxd5 15. Bxb6
{ 15...axb6  . This was Pavasovic-Mestrovic, Slovenian Team Championship 2002, where Black was trying to distract White from his plan.  16.Bb5+!  Nd7  17.Qxd5  would have been even stronger, dominating the hole on d5 and with Ne3-f5 but one strong idea on the table. }
