[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch G1: 2...d6"]
[Black "G1: 2...d6  #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... e5
{ challenges in the centre, but doesn't have an especially good reputation in part because White can now take play away from the Four Knights Game and into the waters of the Ruy Lopez, Steinitz Defence:  5.Bb5  followed by O-O has been known for well over one hundred years to give White a pleasant edge.   If you prefer something independent, you may prefer to play as we did against the Black Lion: }
5. dxe5 Nxe5 6. Nd4
{ Keeping pieces on. Black is probably OK after  6.Nxe5  dxe5  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.f4  Bd6  , since the exchange of knights has left him a little less cramped. That said, this is still a valid option for White and one where he should probably explore space-gaining ventures with  9.f5!?  . }
6... Be7
{ 6...Bd7  7.f4  Nc6  8.Nf3  would keep pieces on and should be slightly better for White, no matter where Black places his dark-squared bishop. Bd3 and O-O would be a simple continuation for White, Be3, Qd2 and O-O-O an even more aggressive one. }
7. f4 Ned7 8. Qf3
{ The most aggressive post for the queen.  8.Be2  followed by O-O, Bf3 and Be3 also makes good sense as a set-up. }
8... O-O 9. Be3
{ Once again we find White prioritizing queenside castling and Black looking a little low on counterplay. Moreover, he can't really go in for an approach which pressures e4: }
9... Nc5 10. h3 { Taking control of a key square to facilitate castling. }
10... Re8 11. O-O-O Bf8 12. e5
{ The line-up of rook and queen on the d-file proves unsurprisingly unpleasant for Black, who is already in serious trouble:  12...dxe5   12...Nfd7  13.exd6  followed by Nf5.  13.Nc6!  not the most common way of winning a queen or White's only good move, but of course, after, say,  13...bxc6  14.Rxd8  Rxd8  15.fxe5  Nd5  16.Bc4  White should really be winning, not least with  16...Be6  17.Bxc5  Bxc5  18.Ne4  retaining full control of the position and leaving only White likely to attack after Re1 and Ng5 or even Qg3 and Nf6+. }
