1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... e5
{ challenges in the centre, but doesn't have an especially good reputation in part because White can now take play away from the Four Knights Game and into the waters of the Ruy Lopez, Steinitz Defence:  5.Bb5  followed by O-O has been known for well over one hundred years to give White a pleasant edge.   If you prefer something independent, you may prefer to play as we did against the Black Lion: }
5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ is less common. Here we are denied our favourite f4 push, but White enjoys easy development and should aim to exploit the knight's position on c6 by targeting the d5 point: }
7. Bg5
{ White threatens Nd5, as well as O-O-O+, and already enjoys the initiative: for example, }
7... h6 8. O-O-O+ Bd6 9. Bh4 Ke8 10. Nd2
{ Heading for c4.  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Bb5  is also quite attractive. } 10... Be6
11. Nc4
{ It is a bit positional, but White undoubtedly enjoys a pleasant edge. Black must either cede the bishop-pair or grovel with  11...Be7  12.Bg3!  Nd7  13.Nd5  Bd8  when  14.h4!?  looks like a useful gain of space, possibly followed by c3, Nce3 and Bc4, with full control over the position. }
