[Black "G1: 2...d6  #20"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... Nf6 { By far Black's main move, if not completely forced. } 4. Nc3
{ Straightforward development. Fans of space and King's Indian-type positions may wish to consider too  4.d5!?  , as played twice by Levon Aronian in the World Rapid and Blitz against Alexander Zubov, the leading 2600+ exponent of the Nimzowitsch along with Christian Bauer.  Then  4...Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Qe2  should be a pleasant pull,  so Black normally prefers  4...Nb8  when  5.Bd3  g6  6.c4  brings about King's Indian-like play. }
4... a6
{ rules out Bb5 at the cost of a tempo. If you're now happy with steady development, we should point out that White has done well with 5. h3, echoing Black's own approach. It's also possible to be more aggressive and advance in the centre: }
5. d5 Nb8 6. Be3
{ Simple development.  6.e5  dxe5  7.Nxe5  e6!  seems fine for Black. } 6... g6
{ A fianchetto is Black's normal approach. Otherwise,   6...e5  7.dxe6!?  Bxe6  8.Nd4  would free the f-pawn for duty,   and  6...Ng4  7.Bf4  will simply gain time after h3 and perhaps even g4 too. }
7. Qd2
{ White copies the 150 Attack approach against the Pirc, but in a position where Black has lost two tempi. He is ready to meet ...Bg7 with Bh6 and meanwhile can shore up e4 with Bd3, not least after ...b5 from Black. White may castle on either side, depending on Black's approach: for example, }
7... b5 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. Bh6 O-O
{ Now  10.a4  to challenge and force concessions on the queenside is tempting, but so is }
10. h4 { with dangerous attacking chances. } 10... Bg4
{ aims to cover the h5-square, but actually fails to prevent the key advance: }
11. h5 Bxh5 12. Nd4
{ White simply threatens f3 and g4, and even  12...b4  13.Nce2  Bxe2  14.Bxe2!?  leaves Black in all sorts of trouble:  14...Nxe4   14...Bh8!?  might be relatively best, but here White can even continue to offer the e-pawn as bait with 15. f4!? or simply go  15.Bxf8  Qxf8  16.Qxb4  Nxe4  17.Ne6!  15.Qe3  Bxd4   15...Nf6?  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Qh6+  Kg8  18.g4  is a killer.  16.Qxd4  Nf6  17.O-O-O  White spurns the exchange and simply wants to go Qh4 followed by g4, possibly Be3, and g5, with f4-f5, if somehow needed, another way of increasing the pressure. }
