1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... g6 4. Nc3
{ is likely to transpose to our main line. Black can delay ...Nf6, but it doesn't affect how White should develop: }
4... Bg7 5. Bb5 { Pinning, as per our recommendation against 4...Nf6. } 5... a6
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O
{ Now  7...Nf6  transposes to our main line, while if Black tarries White may consider seizing space and playing against the knight on g8 with  8.e5  @@StartBracket@@we should also mention that 7.e5!? is worth a thought too in this rare move order@@EndBracket@@, and there's also no need to be concerned about being pinned: }
7... Bg4 8. Be3 { Covering d4. } 8... Nf6 9. h3 Bxf3
{ or  9...Bd7  10.Qd2  followed by removing the bishop-pair from Black while slightly weakening his king's defenses with Bh6. }
10. Qxf3 Rb8 11. Rab1
{ White enjoys a pleasant edge. Ideas of e5 are very much to the fore and that advance may even benefit from further preparation, as with  11...O-O  12.Qe2  Qc8  to prevent Qa6  13.f4  when White might even regroup further, as with b3, Qf3, Rad1 and Bf2-h4 before crashing through with e5 and/or f5, all the while denying Black much counterplay. }
