[White "Nimzowitsch G1: 2...d6"]
[Black "G1: 2...d6  #29"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6
{ The independent main line of the Nimzowitsch and how Tony Miles always used to meet 2. Nf3. It's also slightly more popular than Black's other common choice at this juncture,  2...e5  . }
3. d4 { Needless to say, White helps himself to the central space on offer. }
3... e5
{ can be met in a number of ways, including straightforward development: } 4.
Nc3 { We'll see 4...Nf6 5. Nc3 in our main line and } 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6.
Bc4 Be7 7. O-O
{ is a pleasant edge, with Re1 on the way and Black slightly low on counterplay, as we saw back in Grandmaster Gambits: 1. e4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nimzowitsch G2: 2...Nf6"]
[Black "G2: 2...Nf6  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black offers a transposition to a line of the Alekhine, but unfortunately for him a line of the Alekhine that is under something of a cloud these days. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. c4 { Kicking the knight ahead of further expansion with 5. d4 . }
4... Nb6 5. d4
{ White is now set to roll Black over with Nc3 and d5, so Black pretty much must counter in the center. }
5... d6
{ We've now transposed to a line of the Alekhine, one which more commonly arises from  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@   1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.c4  Nb6  . Once upon a time, Richard dabbled in this unbalanced line as Black, but gave it up once it became clear that White could secure too strong an early initiative. }
6. e6
{ A key advance. As Black doesn't want to lose a piece to an early fork, he is forced to capture with the f-pawn and so retard his development. }
6... fxe6 7. Nc3
{ Simple development.  7.Be3  is also quite promising for White. } 7... g6
{ Black's standard approach, preparing to support the ...e5 advance with a bishop on g7.   7...d5?  8.c5  Nd7  9.Bb5  just looks extremely ugly for Black, thanks to his weaknesses on e6 and e5. White will exchange on c6, castle and then begin to exploit them with Ng5 and Re1. }
8. Be3
{ White shores up  d4  ahead of advancing Harry.  8.h4  Bg7  9.Be3  also works, but here  9.h5  e5!  isn't so clear. }
8... Bg7 9. h4 { Here comes Harry... } 9... e5
{ Once again, we see Black frantically trying to return the extra pawn to liberate his position. }
10. d5
{ As ever in this line, a strong advance and one which reminds Black of his light-square issues. }
10... Nd4 { Prudently returning the pawn. } 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13.
Qxd4 e5 14. dxe6
{ Simple chess, opening lines and pretty much forcing Black's next. } 14... O-O
15. h5 { transposing to our main 9...e5 line after } 15... Qf6 16. Qxf6
{ White hasn't anything better than exchanging queens and opening the h-file, not that he should exactly be unhappy. }
16... Rxf6 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. e7
{ The pawn sells itself as dearly as possible. This has been quite a long line, if also an instructive one and a fairly common scenario, Black beating off White's attack at the cost of endgame suffering.   Even here his king isn't happy, with Bd3 on the cards, as is O-O-O with definite ideas of c5.   18...Re6+  discombobulating.   18...Bf5?  19.O-O-O  followed by c5 is also very strong.  19.Kd2  Rxe7  20.Bd3  Bf5  21.Rh6  White continues to pressure g6 while facilitating Rah1. We've followed in the footsteps of, amongst others, Chessable's very own Maaike Keetman and White definitely enjoyed a clear plus here in the endgame in Keetman-Theulings, Groningen 2015.   18...Be6?  hopes for ...Re8 and ...Rxe7, but fails to the energetic  19.c5!  dxc5   19...Nd5  20.Nxd5  Bxd5  21.O-O-O  Bc6  22.cxd6  cxd6  23.Bc4+  when the e-pawn very much lives.  20.O-O-O  Re8  Now 21.Ne4 was strong in Petrik-Slacky, Banska Stiavnica 2010, and  21.Rd8  Bd7  22.Nb5!  likely even stronger. Preventing Nxc7 isn't at all easy and  22...Rc6  still loses to some further energetic play  23.a4!  a5  24.g4!  when Black is completely tied up and g5 followed by Bh3 the killer plan.   18...Bd7  is the safest square for the bishop, but fails to bring Black close to equality:  19.Bd3  Re8  20.f3  Rxe7+  21.Kd2  White leaves his king in the middle for the endgame. He will now either double on the h-file or prepare to invade down the e-file if Black offers a trade of rooks. Note too how much more active and useful the knight on c3  (Nd5, Ne4)  is compared with its counterpart on b6. }
*

