{ White is now set to roll Black over with Nc3 and d5, so Black pretty much must counter in the center. }
5... d6
{ We've now transposed to a line of the Alekhine, one which more commonly arises from  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@   1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.c4  Nb6  . Once upon a time, Richard dabbled in this unbalanced line as Black, but gave it up once it became clear that White could secure too strong an early initiative. }
6. e6
{ A key advance. As Black doesn't want to lose a piece to an early fork, he is forced to capture with the f-pawn and so retard his development. }
6... fxe6 7. Nc3
{ Simple development.  7.Be3  is also quite promising for White. } 7... e5
{ is Black's other main move, but is, of course, quite desperate looking. White should be happy to regain his pawn with straightforward play: }
8. d5 Nd4
{ 8...Nb8?  9.Ng5!  would be a positional disaster for Black with Qf3 and Bd3 on their way. }
9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Qxd4
{ White threatens Be2-h5+ and may castle on either side. As such, Black surely has to hit back in the center: }
10... e5 11. Qe4
{ Aggressive play.  11.Qd1  and  11.dxe6  Bxe6  12.Be2  Qf6  13.Qxf6  gxf6  are the alternatives and also fairly pleasant edges for White. }
11... g6 12. Bd3 Bf5 13. Qe2 { The standard retreat in this line. } 13... Bxd3
14. Qxd3 Qh4 15. Ne4
{ We've followed M.Muzychuk-Dornbusch, European Online Women's Rapid Championship 2020, where White enjoyed an ideal edge.   Complete control of e4 is always a useful asset in this structure @@StartBracket@@a bad King's Indian for Black if you like@@EndBracket@@.   As well as the immediate threat of Bg5, White can complete development with O-O and Be3, after which he will begin to prepare to breakthrough with c5. }
*

